<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Brite-PhoneOverload     06-04 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brite-Phone Overload,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Workers' Calls To Radio Station Knock Out Phone System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN BALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State employees trying to ``Stump the
Dummy'' or win ``Loot in the Boot'' were outfoxed when their bosses
blocked calls to radio station contests after learning the calls
had caused the government's phone system to crash.
   Over the past few days, state officials thought they had major
phone problems when the phone system went down for up to 20 minutes
three or four times a day.
   When they checked into the problem, they learned the phones
weren't working because so many state workers were clogging phone
lines by calling KLIK to play such games as ``Loot in the Boot,''
in which players guess how much money the country music station is
giving away.
   Officials on Friday had the phone company restrict state
employees' access to all Jefferson City radio station contest
lines. Workers using a state phone to call the stations now receive
a recorded message preventing them from getting through.
   Office of Administration Director John Pelzer said he did not
know how many of the 12,000 state employees who work in the capital
area were trying to get through to contest lines.
   ``The phone company said thousands and thousands of people _ and
not just state employees _ were calling. I don't know how many
employees would have to be on the phone at the same time to bring
it down, but this is the first time in the five years we've had
this system that it has been brought to its knees,'' Pelzer said.
   One enterprising employee devised a method using the ``flash''
and ``redial'' buttons on her phone to call KLIK's contest line on
eight different lines at once, Pelzer daid.
   ``We've always had a reasonable policy toward personal phone
calls,'' Pelzer said. ``If you need to call home to take care of a
problem, OK. If you're sitting around listening to the radio all
day waiting for the disc jockey to say, `I'll take the seventh
caller'' so you can win $1,000, that is not reasonable and I don't
think anybody could argue that it is.''
</TEXT>
