<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DowneyDropped     06-04 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Downey Dropped,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>TV Station Replaces Morton Downey Jr. With `Love Boat'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SCHENECTADY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Loudmouthed talk show host Morton
Downey Jr. has been replaced by reruns of ``The Love Boat'' on a
television station that canceled his show after just four days
because it was too obscene, a spokesman says.
   Downey, who often gets into shouting matches with guests and
audience members, was pulled Thursday, four days after his debut on
WRGB-TV, station general manager David Lynch said.
   The language and material of the syndicated ``Morton Downey Jr.
Show'' were too obscene for ``the image of the station,'' Lynch
said.
   Employees of the CBS affiliate spent 30 to 40 hours trying to
edit the one-hour show to be suitable for viewing in its 9 a.m.
time slot, he said. The show starts at 9 p.m. on its home station
of WWOR-TV in New Jersey.
   Until further notice, WRGB will replace the show with reruns of
``The Love Boat,'' Lynch said.
   In his Philadelphia debut, Downey more than doubled the ratings
that ``Hill Street Blues'' had received in the same time slot,
WPHL-TV officials said.
   ``To tell you the truth we're not surprised,'' said Karen
Corbin, WPHL programming director. Downey is ``a phenomenon; there
was never any doubt in our minds that if Philadelphia viewers were
given a chance to watch Mort Downey, they'd rush to do it.''
</TEXT>
