<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-US     06-04 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-US,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Secretary and Japanese discuss plans for jet fighter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci and Japanese
officials have discussed Washington's plans to develop a jet
fighter known as the FSX, a Carlucci aide said Friday.
   He also said Carlucci is ``very pleaced'' with American-Japanese
defense cooperation including sharing the costs of maintaining U.S.
servicemen in Japan.
   The aide, a senior Defense Department official, spoke with the
condition he not be indentified.
   Carlucci held two days of talks with senior Japanese Defense and
Foreign Ministry officials and there were no areas of significant
disagreement, according to the official.
   Carlucci arrived in Tokyo Thursday to brief Japanese authorities
on the U.S.-Soviet summit conference in Moscow and discuss
bilateral issues.
   The aide said Carlucci and Japanese defense officials discussed
only in general terms the plans to jointly develop the FSX fighter.
   ``However this works out it will be in a positive way,'' he
said. ``It is a signpost for the future for both of us because an
essential part of our defense relationship will be the exchange of
technology, a two-way flow.''
   The Japan Broadcasting Corp., a public television network, said
the two sides agreed to set up a ``technology steering committee''
to oversee the transfer of FSX technology between the Japanese
Defense Agency and the U.S. Air Force.
   It said the $1.3 billion needed for developing the jet fighter
will come from Japanese firms, with U.S. companies as
subcontractors, and the United States will develop the plane's
engines and Japan its radar system.
   Carlucci's aide said both countries ``are constantly
addressing'' the issue of financial support for the more than
50,000 American military personnel stationed in the main Japanese
islands and Okinawa.
   Some U.S. congressmen have said Japan should do more because of
the enormous increase in the value of the yen, which has more than
doubled against the dollar in the last three years.
   ``We're not going around with a tin cup because we need help
with our budget problems,'' the aide said. ``You can't go around
poor-mouthing your friends _ they get tired of it.
   ``When you talk about burden-sharing, we should talk about
mutual security and joint cooperation, and identify areas of
weakness.''
   Japan provides more than $45,000 worth of support annually for
each U.S. serviceman stationed here, Assistant Defense Secretary
Richard L. Armitage told Congress March 17. It also helps pay some
expenses of the 21,000 Japanese working at U.S. bases.
   ``Altogether, Japan will spend $2.5 billion ... the most
generous host-nation support arrangement the U.S. enjoys anywhere
in the world,'' Armitage said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
