<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 0250EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DoctorQuits     06-04 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Doctor Quits,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anesthesiologist Quits To Open Laundry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUDSON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An anesthesiologist says he is quitting his
practice to run a self-service laundry and dry-cleaning business
because the wash carries a lot less liability than medicine.
   ``When doctors have a malpractice suit, it's a $3 million to $5
million loss. If someone's laundry doesn't come out right, I just
pay them the $40 or so to cover it and it's done,'' said Dr. Joseph
J. Merigo.
   Merigo, 57, took over the Hudson Coin-Op on March 1. He said
insurance rates drove him out of his 20-year practice as an
anesthesiologist at Boston-area hospitals.
   ``A lot of people think you make a lot of money as a doctor,''
Merigo said. ``But you don't have any choice, your bills are so
high.''
   Merigo said his liability insurance premiums just about equal
his annual income, although he has never been sued.
   Merigo still works three mornings a week at Bournewood Hospital,
a psychiatric facility in Brookline, whose electroconvulsive
therapy center he helped found. He will stop practicing medicine
Oct. 23, when his insurance policy runs out.
   He admitted to some hesitation about the career switch. ``You
don't get the same kick from doing a suit that you do after doing a
good job in a life-threatening situation,'' Merigo said.
   And he has found that old habits die hard. He recently tended to
a customer who turned gray while dragging a bag of clothes into the
store.
   ``I asked her if she had problems with her heart and if she was
taking medicine. She said she was. I made her sit down and catch
her breath,'' Merigo said.
   ``That woman was in congestive heart failure right here in that
chair,'' he said, pointing to a seat near the cash register.
   But the laundry business has its rewards, he said. ``I figure if
I can buy another one of these, I'll be making about what I was
making as a doctor.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
