<2ND_LINE>AM-Students Struck, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0780,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Car Jumps Curb, Kills One Student, Injures Others</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with identities of students and driver;
additional witness comments. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEOFFREY HAYNES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car jumped a curb and ran into a large group of
children walking home from a middle school Friday, killing one and
injuring several others, police and witnesses said.
   The students were walking home from nearby Rosa Parks Middle
School when the car went up on the sidewalk and lawn, striking the
children about 2:30 p.m.
   Ernest Powell, 14, of Detroit died shortly after arriving at St.
John Hospital, hospital spokeswoman Dorothy Colombo said.
   The driver of the car, Johnnie Person, 66, of Detroit was
arrested, and was scheduled to be arraigned Saturday, but no
charges were filed as of Friday night, Officer Eric Gensley said.
   Three youngsters were hospitalized in fair condition with arm,
leg and head injuries. They were identified as Jamel Thompson, 12;
Dwayne Greer, 11; and Derrick Davenport, 12, all of Detroit,
Colombo said.
   Rose Robertson, a nurse at Henry Ford Hospital who was aiding
injured students at the scene, said she heard the driver tell
police that children threw a bottle at his car.
   She said other students were injured but chose to go home
instead of the hospital.
   ``The scene was chaotic. There were injured students laying on
the grass and there were adults and children trying to help,''
Detroit police Sgt. Martin Joseph said from the scene.
   Joseph said the driver did not appear intoxicated or high on
drugs.
   ``I didn't smell alcohol and the guy was walking OK,'' Joseph
said.
   After the late model Cadillac hit the students, it struck a
parked car and came to rest by a fire hydrant, Joseph said.
   Ken Smith said he was picking up his son at Rosa Parks Middle
School when he saw the accident at 2:30 p.m.
   ``One of the kids bounced a basketball out in the street,''
Smith said. ``An old black Cadillac _ I don't know what speed he
was going _ he hit the ball and went out of control and crashed
into a crowd.''
   Principal Raymond Demeulemeester said he was following the
children home when the accident happened ahead of him.
   ``There were children on the ground and some were screaming and
some were trying to help,'' Demeulemeester said.
   The principal said police arrived at the scene about three
minutes after the accident occurred.
</TEXT>
