<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Taiwan-Kidnap     06-04 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Taiwan-Kidnap,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kidnapped Japanese Schoolboy Found Safe, Police Seek Abductors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 8-year-old Japanese schoolboy,
kidnapped one week ago, has been found alive in a Taipei alley, his
eyes covered by tape and his head wrapped in a white cloth, police
said today.
   Police today launched a massive manhunt for the boy's kidnappers
who reportedly received $63,000 to free the youth.
   Police found Tetsuyoshi Ohta after the kidnappers informed his
parents of the boy's location, Taipei Police Chief Liao Chao-hsiang
told reporters.
   The boy had been missing since May 27 when he was abducted while
walking to a calligraphy lesson in suburban Taipei, according to
police.
   Newspapers, without naming sources, said the boy's mother
delivered a ransom of $63,000 to a hotel in Kaohsiung, 216 miles
south of Taipei, on Thursday. The newspapers gave no further
details and the mother refused to comment on the reports.
   Newspapers reported that Tetsuyoshi, in a white T-shirt and blue
jean shorts, looked startled when found by the police and said: ``I
am hungry. I want to go home.''
   Tetsuyoshi told reporters at the police station he was
blindfolded during the entire ordeal and was taken to several
places. He said he was not beaten.
   The boys' parents met him at the police station and were
escorted home by the police, the reports said.
   Police chief Liao said authorities were combing the island for
the two men and one woman whom the boy said were his kidnappers.
Liao said Tetsuyoshi was too frightened to give descriptions of the
three.
   Kidnappers, if convicted, can receive the death penalty in
Taiwan.
   According to police accounts, a man called the boy's parents on
the evening of the kidnapping and demanded $63,000 for the boy's
return.
   The next afternoon the boy's mother gave the money to taxi
driver Yeh Shao-ming, who honked his horn three times outside a
fast food restaurant in downtown Taipei, a signal specified in the
ransom demand.
   About 100 plainclothes police arrested Yeh on the spot and
retrieved the money. They were unable to find the boy, who police
believed was in a white sedan not far from where Yeh was waiting.
   Police said the taxi driver claimed he knew nothing of the
kidnapping and was paid by a woman to run the errand.
   In an open letter to a leading newspaper that appeared Monday,
the Ohtas pleaded for the release of their child.
   ``Please don't hurt our son and understand how we feel as
parents,'' the handwritten letter in the Chinese-language United
Daily News said. ``Release the child as soon as possible.''
   On Thursday night, news reports said, the boy's mother delivered
the ransom.
</TEXT>
