<2ND_LINE>PM-Names,0876</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To the tune of M-I-C-K-E-Y-M-O-U-S-E,
more than 3,000 invited guests showed up at Disneyland to honor
America's favorite rodent, who turns 60 this year.
   ``Yo, Mick, Happy Birthday,'' said Sylvester Stallone, who with
actors Michael Keaton, Molly Ringwald, Teri Garr and original
Mouseketeer Annette Funicello, joined Thursday's salute.
   The party, which featured a 12-foot-high birthday cake, kicked
off a multimillion-dollar promotion that will include commemorative
videos, free gifts to children who visit Disneyland and a 12-story
Earforce One balloon that will tour several U.S. cities.
   Mickey Mouse made his screen debut in ``Steamboat Willie'' on
Nov. 18, 1928, and has been a crowd pleaser ever since.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Best-selling author Jackie Collins, sister of
``Dynasty'' vixen Joan Collins, says she pursued a career in show
business after being expelled from her exclusive English high
school for smoking.
   Her parents told her, ```You're not bad looking. Why don't you
go off to Hollywood and be a movie star like your sister,''' she
recalled recently.
   Dismal bit parts steered Ms. Collins away from acting and toward
writing about the players. Her latest ode to life in the fast lane,
``Rock Star,'' held steady at No. 4 on last week's New York Times
best-seller list, following her last two tinseltown tell-alls,
``Hollywood Wives'' and ``Hollywood Husbands.''
   ``Some people tend to regard me as the Hollywood expert,'' she
said. ``I could write a book tomorrow with all the real names _
short one-liners that would let you know exactly who everybody
really was.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Col. Sherwood ``Woody'' Spring, an astronaut who
flew on a shuttle flight in 1985, is leaving NASA in August to
become director of the Army Space Program office.
   Spring will report to the Army Space Program's Fairfax, Va.,
headquarters on Sept. 1, NASA spokesman Jeff Carr said Friday.
Spring will train for nine months before becoming director next
June.
   Spring, who was selected to be an astronaut in May 1980, was a
mission specialist on the space shuttle Atlantis flight that
launched in November 1985.
   During that mission, Spring helped deploy three communication
satellites, and went on two spacewalks that totaled 12 hours.
   Spring logged 165 hours in space on that mission. Since then, he
has been doing general technical support work for the space station
project.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A physics professor honored for his
breakthrough in the field of superconductivity says he will leave
the University of Alabama to join the faculty of Columbia
University.
   Maw-Kuen Wu will join Nobel laureate T.D. Lee at the New York
City school.
   ``This was sort of a long dream,'' Wu said Friday. ``As a child,
he was one of my heroes, when I decided to be a scientist at a very
young age.''
   Wu last year led research that raised the temperature of
superconducting materials. The discovery improved the prospects for
taking superconductivity from laboratory experiments to practical
applications.
   After the discovery, scientists talked about transmitting
electricity over long distances without losses, magnetically
levitated bullet trains, faster computers and small but powerful
medical scanners.
   In January, Wu and a colleague on the project were awarded the
National Academy of Sciences' Cyrus B. Comstock Prize, presented
every five years for the most important discovery or investigation
in electricity, magnetism or radiant energy.
</TEXT>
