<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     06-04 0824</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,860</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>European Blast at Wheat Decision `Disappoints' Lyng</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   European complaints about the decision to
increase U.S. wheat production have been disappointing and at
variance with the facts, says Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng.
   ``I was terribly disappointed in your response to our decision
to lower the set aside requirements for wheat producers,'' Lyng
said Friday in a letter to European Community Agriculture
Commissioner Frans Andriessen.
   He took issue with a statement by EC officials in Brussels on
Wednesday that the U.S. decision to reduce the acreage idling
requirement for wheat growers from 27.5 percent of planted acreage
to 10 percent would result in an additional 10 million to 12
million tons of grain on the world market.
   ``The prospects are really quite different,'' he said.
   Lyng expressed hope ``that in the future we can respond to each
other's policy announcements with a greater regard for the facts of
the case.''
   He also complained in the letter that European wheat production
``continues at high levels despite repeated assurances that
production will be lowered.''
   In a strongly worded statement, the European commissioners
declared that the United States was violating international trade
agreements by increasing farm subsidies to American wheat producers.
   Farmers are required to idle the acreage specified by the
Agriculture Department if they are to be eligible for government
programs that include price support loans and income support
payments.
   ``U.S. wheat supplies available for export will be smaller''
than previously, even with less acreage idled, Lyng said. He
attributed this to lower stocks of wheat at the outset of the
marketing year.
   ``Smaller carry-in stocks will mean U.S. wheat supplies will
total about 90 million metric tons, nearly 3 million tons less than
a year earlier,'' he said. An attached chart showed overall
supplies at 109.4 million for 1986-87, 107.3 million for 1987-88,
93 million for 1988-89 and 90.4 million for 1989-90.
   He also said that because of participation by farmers in two
other acreage idling programs, ``the U.S. will continue to idle a
large amount of wheat land in 1989, about the equivalent to the
harvested wheat area of France, Spain and Portugal.''
   Lyng said the U.S. share of the world wheat trade was likely to
decrease even with the increased acreage to 40 percent or less,
compared with 42 percent last year and more than 45 percent in the
1970s.
   He said higher prices for wheat in the United States combined
with a 6.4 percent reduction in target prices ``will lower the
amount of subsidies paid to wheat farmers and increase their degree
of market orientation.''
   Target prices are set by Congress and adjusted by the
Agriculture Department to help determine the size of income support
payments made under some of the farm programs.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bigger supplies of some kinds of livestock and
poultry are leading to lower prices and driving down the return to
farmers on the food they produce, Agriculture Department economists
say.
   But moderate food price inflation overall is expected this year,
according to an economic analysis from USDA.
   The gap between consumer spending on food and the amount of
money farmers actually get out of it most likely will rise 6.6
percent this year to a total of $302 billion, according to the
analysis.
   Spending for domestically produced food is expected to rise 4eside
livestock and poultry supplies are
causing the change. A 50-cent cut in the milk support price is
expected to result in somewhat lower return to the dairy farmer
despite a slight increase in consumption.
   Fruit and vegetable prices are actually expected to be lower
amid expanded supplies of lettuce, potatoes, apples, pears and
strawberries.
   But stronger export demand for grains and oil crops as well as
reduced supplies of them should drive up prices somewhat and at
least partially offset a portion of the decline in farm value.
   Consumer food spending is expected to increase at about the same
rate as last year. Increased supplies of pork, poultry and some
other major commodities are expected to lower retail prices, but
the analysis foresees moderate food price inflation overall.
</TEXT>
