<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Duarte     06-04 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Duarte,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctors Try To Decide On Treatment For Duarte's Cancer</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be topped if developments warrant; no statement expected
from hospital before Monday.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salvadoran President Jose Napoleon Duarte
began his fourth day in a Washington hospital today, where doctors
are trying to decide how best to treat his liver and stomach cancer.
   Walter Reed Medical Army Medical Center issued a statement
Friday saying doctors at the hospital and Duarte's personal
physician would look at test results and ``present treatment
alternatives to the president and his family.''
   The hospital did not specify when a decision would be made. It
said Duarte was in guarded but stable condition.
   Both the hospital and Duarte's personal physician, Benjamin
Interiano, who is from El Salvador, have been reluctant to discuss
chances of Duarte's recovery. But a State Department official,
insisting on anonymity, told The Associated Press on Friday that
Duarte is suffering from terminal cancer.
   ``The only question is how long he will live. It's probably
measured in months,'' the official said.
   The official added there have been informal discussions in El
Salvador about the possibility of Duarte resigning his office. The
next in line in the order of succession is Vice President Rodolfo
Castillo Claramount, who is serving as acting president in Duarte's
absence.
   Duarte received a get-well visit from Vice President George Bush.
   Bush met with Duarte for 30 minutes in the Salvadoran
president's room at Walter Reed. During the visit, Bush ``wished
Duarte well and expressed his gratitude for what he's done for
democracy,'' Kristin Taylor, a spokeswoman for the vice president,
said.
   Duarte, 62, has been undergoing tests since his arrival at
Walter Reed on Tuesday night. He visited a special clinic Thursday
for magnetic resonance imaging tests to determine the extent of his
cancer.
   Duarte, who was born Nov. 23, 1925, in San Salvador, received a
civil engineering degree in 1948 from the University of Notre Dame
in South Bend, Ind.
   In 1960, he co-founded the Christian Democratic Party in El
Salvador and four years later was elected to the first of three
terms as mayor of San Salvador.
   He was expelled from the country by the military in 1972 while
running for president. He returned from exile in 1979 following a
coup by reformist-minded military officers. The next year he was
named a member of a military-civilian junta. He became president of
a new junta in December 1980.
   He won a five-year term in a presidential election in 1984 and
was hailed as a leader who could extricate his country from decades
of poverty and conflict.
   But an eight-year-old civil war with leftist forces continues
unabated, and the Central American nation's economy is in a
shambles. Duarte's party suffered a major defeat in municipal and
legislative elections in March.
   The Salvadoran constitution prohibits Duarte from running for
election again next March, and the rightist Republican Nationalist
Alliance appears to be in good position to win the presidency.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
