<HEAD>Bridge Tournament Draws Players Worldwide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A global card game organized by the World
Bridge Federation got under way Friday in up to 80 countries around
the world, a U.S. spokeswoman for the event said.
   ``We're anticipating close to 100,000 people,'' said Sherri Wolf
Rosen, a spokeswoman for the American Contract Bridge League, which
is headquartered in Memphis.
   The bridge championship for the United States, a separate
tournament from the worldwide event, also was scheduled over the
weekend in Memphis, Ms. Rosen said.
   The national championship involves seven six-member teams from
around the country. It was to conclude Sunday.
   The worldwide event using the same 24 bridge hands at each
location, was scheduled at bridge clubs and other sites in 2,500
cities, Ms. Rosen said.
   Playing was to start between 7 p.m. and 8 p.m. according to
local time at the various sites, she said.
   The contest attracted more than 73,000 players around the world
last year.
   Worldwide results were to be tabulated Saturday in Paris, Ms.
Rosen said.
