<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson     06-04 0588</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Back In California To Campaign In Town With High Cancer
Rate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUTTE, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson left the hectic pace of
delegate-rich California for a day to woo voters in less-populous
Montana and New Mexico where, he said, the people's concerns count
more than their political importance.
   Jackson was heading back to California Friday night to spend
today in the rural town of McFarland, which has a mysteriously high
cancer rate. He called on supporters to join him in McFarland to
call for government action in finding and correcting the cause of
the cancer.
   Montana and New Mexico will hold primary elections Tuesday, the
last day of the primary season. But they have been overshadowed by
the expensive contest in California, whose 314 delegates are the
richest prize of all the primaries, and New Jersey, which has 109
delegates.
   By contrast, New Mexico has 24, and Montana 19.
   But Jackson, speaking against a backdrop of white-capped
mountains, a deep blue Montana sky and expansive green plain, told
an airport rally in Bozeman:
   ``We cannot measure human beings and their needs just by their
political capital. ... It's their humanity that's at stake.''
   Later Jackson spoke at a dinner sponsored by the state
Democratic Party in Butte, where he was warmly received by the few
hundred in attendance, most of whom wore Michael Dukakis buttons.
   Jackson told the gathering that in Democrats across the nation,
``There is a rising spirit in the air that we can win.''
   He offered a prayer for Dukakis' wife, Kitty, who underwent
spinal surgery on Friday.
   Noting that the Massachusetts governor was home by his wife's
side, Jackson joked, ``He has done such a good job in
Massachusetts, I'm trying to keep him there four more years.''
   Also speaking at the dinner was John Dukakis, the son of the
front-runner.
   At the Bozeman airport, Jackson talked about the state's Indian
population and the need to respect their culture and religion,
about loss of family farms and ranches, and the need to fight
environmental pollution.
   The crowd of more than 300 was smaller than what Jackson is used
to, but some of his California audiences in the waning days of the
campaign also have lacked the size of his earlier rallies.
   Earlier, he spoke to more than 1,500 people in the trendy
central plaza of Santa Fe, N,M.
   There he said that environmental concerns are ``No longer a
fringe issue'' but are central to human existence.
   He spoke on the sun-baked plaza surrounded by the city's
trademark Indian sidewalk vendors who sell an array of turquoise
and silver jewelry.
   Jackson spoke of the controversy about federal plans to store
nuclear waste near Carlsbad and said, ``Safety before waste, that
must be your watchword.''
   Jackson said he did not know the context of reported comments by
his campaign manager Gerald Austin that the strongest Democratic
ticket would be Dukakis and Sen. John Glenn of Ohio.
   But he told reporters, ``Don't take that seriously.''
   Austin was quoted in the Boston Herald as saying Jackson was his
first choice for vice president with Dukakis, but that Glenn would
make for an almost unbeatable ticket.
   Jackson dismissed the report, repeating his earlier assertions
that if Dukakis wins, Jackson deserves consideration for vice
president, and vice versa.
   Jackson has taken up the McFarland issue as a central cause of
his campaign in its closing days. He mentioned it in all his Los
Angeles speeches over the past two days.
</TEXT>
