<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 0322EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Shipyards-Jobs     06-04 0593</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shipyards-Jobs,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Assess Impact of Navy's Shipyard Plans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers reacted to Navy forecasts of reduced
workforces at eight public shipyards with letters, planned
legislation and a resolve to keep employment at current levels.
   Rep. Norman Dicks, D-Wash., said Friday that the Navy's public
yards face a tough fight in the coming years.
   ``I can see a day where one or two of the public yards might not
exist because of the downturn of overhaul work,'' he said. ``It's
an ongoing struggle.''
   A Naval Sea Systems Command planning document obtained Wednesday
by The Associated Press projects a reduction from 71,100 to 56,400
jobs at the public yards by the end of 1991.
   The document contains job estimates based on anticipated ship
overhaul and modernization schedules.
   The systems command, which oversees the Navy's eight yards, said
Wednesday that ``exact naval shipyard employment figures will not
be determined until the budget process is completed for fiscal year
1989 and beyond.''
   The planning document was born out of a fleet scheduling
conference in May during which the Navy and its shipyard commanders
took a long-range view of the overhaul workload.
   The Navy still can adjust its assignments to reflect overhaul
budgets set by Congress for individual years. In addition, Congress
occasionally forces the Navy's hand by mandating that a certain
ship or class of ships be assigned to a specific yard for repairs.
   Congress has not yet completed work on the federal budget for
fiscal year 1989, which begins Oct. 1. Even after the spending bill
is passed, however, the Navy is given discretion to juggle
workforce sizes. In effect, the process of assigning overhaul work
and fixing employment levels never ends, so long as the Navy
remains within its budget.
   The employment forecasts and planned overhaul assignment
schedules alarmed Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa., who said he would take
steps to prevent or minimize job losses at the Philadelphia Naval
Shipyard, which now employs about 8,700.
   Heinz said the Philadelphia area congressional delegation will
introduce legislation to require that the Philadelphia yard have
the opportunity to compete for electronics and computer work on
ships.
   Meanwhile, Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., wrote to Navy Secretary
William L. Ball III and to fellow Appropriations Committee members
warning that a plan ruling out the electronics upgrades at
Philadelphia until 1991 would cause the yard to lose skilled
workers who represent a valuable Navy investment.
   The Philadelphia yard's workforce could be as low as 6,800 at
the end of the 1991 fiscal year, according to projections in the
working document.
   Dicks, whose district contains the Puget Sound yard, termed the
planning document ``a bare-bones projection'' and said he did not
believe employment would drop as low as predicted because past
forecasts of employment have normally been lower than the job
levels actually recorded.
   Dicks said employment at the yards, already down 9 percent since
January 1985, should not drop further for reasons of national
security.
   ``I think they should stay where they are now, and I'm going to
do everything I can to fight the decline,'' Dicks said.
   He said Puget Sound and other public yards ``have been quite
competitive'' so far in their battle to keep from losing too much
ground to private yards.
   Private yards, which already handle all new Navy ship
construction, have been competing for a larger share of overhauls.
   A General Accounting Office report in March found that,
``Overall, private shipyards are being awarded an increasing share
of the funds for all overhaul and repair work.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880604-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 0323EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AutoSales     06-04 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Sales,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Domestic Sales Up, Imports Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of domestic cars and trucks picked up late
last month, helping produce a 15.8 percent increase for the month
against a year ago, while import sales declined 3.1 percent, auto
companies reported.
   The eight companies that build cars and trucks in the United
States sold 437,233 vehicles in the eight selling days from May
21-31, up 14.8 percent from 380,732 in the identical period a year
ago.
   Together, domestic automakers sold 12.5 percent more North
American-made cars and 19.2 percent more domestic trucks than in
late May 1987.
   Overall sales of cars and light trucks, imported and domestic,
were up 10.8 during the month compared with May 1987.
   ``With less generous (sales) incentives ... we've still got some
momentum underneath this market, some good underlying strength,''
said Joseph Phillippi, an analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton in
New York.
   Domestic car sales by General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and
Chrysler Corp. rose 13.4 percent in late May from a year ago, while
Big Three domestic light truck sales jumped 17.9 percent, the
makers reported.
   In late May, GM and Ford increased their shares of the domestic
car market while Chrysler's share slipped slightly despite a 6.5
percent increase in sales. Together, the Big Three held 89 percent
of the domestic market.
   GM's late May domestic car sales rose 14.3 percent from a year
ago; Ford's rose 15.2 percent.
   Ford's domestic truck sales slipped 1.7 percent in late May,
along with its share of the market, while GM's truck sales rose
44.3 percent and its share grew to 42.9 percent from 35.4 percent
in late May a year ago.
   Chrysler's domestic truck sales, which include Jeep products,
were up 10.6 percent, but its share of the market fell slightly.
The Big Three control 97 percent of the domestic truck market.
   During all of May, foreign and domestic makers together sold
1,433,365 cars and light trucks. Domestic car sales rose 12.8
percent while domestic truck sales jumped 21.4 percent from May
1987.
   But while import car sales rose 3.6 percent from May 1987,
import truck sales fell 25.5 percent.
   During May, imported Japanese cars and light trucks made up 17.1
percent of all vehicles sold, a decline from 19.7 percent in May
1987. European car sales remained 23 percent lower than in May a
year ago.
   However, makers of some luxury European models, including
Mercedes-Benz and Volvo, reported a gradual return of customers who
were scared off earlier by the stock market collapse and
skyrocketing prices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
