<HEAD>Emergency Crews Find No Apparent Radiation Leak</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with fire department officials saying
alarm malfunctioned. No Pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CATONSVILLE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A report of a possible explosion and
radiation leak at a Martin-Marietta research facility near
Catonsville late Friday resulted from a false alarm, authorities
said.
   ``It was an apparent malfunction of the alarm system,'' said
James Friedline, a supervisor at the Baltimore County Fire
Department. Twenty firefighting units, with some 60 firefighters
rushed to the scene after the initial report, Friedline said.
   Cpl. Kevin Novak, a supervising dispatcher at the Baltimore
County Police Department said initial radio reports from the scene
indicated a possible radiation leak inside the building. But
emergency crews reported finding no leak and no sign of an
explosion.
   No one was evacuated. Interstate 95, which runs near the plant,
was not closed to traffic.
   The research facility is located in southeast Baltimore County,
about 5 miles south of the Baltimore city limits. It conducts
wide-ranging research in areas ranging from artificial intelligence
to chemistry and metallurgy.
