<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PreppiePrince     06-04 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Preppie Prince,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heir Apparent to Western Samoan Throne Gets Diploma</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALISBURY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of his prep-school classmates
expect to be doctors, lawyers or businessmen one day, but
17-year-old Malietau Malietoa has bigger plans _ ruler of Western
Samoa.
   Malietoa, who graduated Friday, is a prince of Western Samoa and
heir apparent to the tiny Pacific island nation's throne.
   ``Often I sit up late at night and think about this,'' said
Malietoa, who is known as Tau among his classmates.
   The student who would be king _ or tupu, as it is known in the
Samoan language _ spent the past year at the Episcopal all-male
school to learn Western ways to help him lead his country, now
ruled by his 73-year-old grandfather.
   An uncle who is an adviser to his grandfather suggested the
school in northwest Connecticut, and Malietoa agreed because he
wanted to live in a cold climate for a change.
   He has tried skiing, and played on the school basketball team,
although he confesses he did not totally understand the game.
   ``I think I was a wing or a guard,'' he said recently. ``Yes, I
think I was a guard.''
   His grandfather is the latest head of state in a dynasty that
goes back 1,500 years. Malietoa's father died in 1984. His son says
that made him the heir apparent.
   However, Nusi Mavala, chief administrator of the Samoan Mission
at the United Nations, said the matai, a group of titled heads of
leading families, would vote on a new head of state if anything
happened to Malietoa's grandfather, and there could be other
claimants. He said Malietoa could be the leading claimant.
   Malietoa has been a good student and has fit in well with other
students, ``but he's more serious than most,'' said the Rev. Peter
W. Sipple, head of Salisbury.
   Malietoa has no immediate plans for college, but is looking into
the possibility of enrolling at Harvard University as a special
tutorial student in studies that would be useful in governing a
nation.
   There are two countries in the Samoan chain of 16 volcanic
islands in the South Pacific.
   Six of the islands make up American Samoa, which has been under
U.S. control since 1900. The others make up Western Samoa, a
country of 1,130 square miles, about one-fifth the size of
Connecticut, with a population of 165,000.
   Malietoa describes Western Samoa as a benevolent but absolute
monarchy. Its economy is tied to bananas, copra and taro roots, as
it has been for centuries. It has its own currency but only for
internal use.
   ``We are poor, but we do not have hunger,'' he said.
</TEXT>
