<HEAD>Miners Found Alive After Wednesday's Mine Blast</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Combines Bulletin series, UPDATES with details.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BORKEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six miners buried 330 feet
underground for more than two days after an explosion in a coal
shaft were found alive early Saturday, Hesse State radio said.
   The radio said the six were discovered by rescuers in a pocket
of air. They were exhausted but otherwise appeared not be seriously
injured, the report said.
   The six men were among 57 miners in the shaft when the explosion
occurred Wednesday. The radio said there was hope that more
survivors may be found.
   By late Friday, rescuers had found 36 bodies and had brought 28
bodies to the surface.
   The first of the six survivors was brought to the surface at
about 5.30 a.m., the radio said.
   The blast at the Stolzenbach mine in the town of Borken, 72
miles northeast of Frankfurt, trapped the miners 330 feet below the
surface and by Thursday mine officials had given up hope of finding
anyone alive.
   The survivors were found about 60 hours after the accident.
   Rescuers said earlier that there were high concentrations of
deadly carbon monoxide in the mine.
   The survivors may have been helped by fresh air being constantly
pumped into the mine to aid the rescuers, the radio said.
   Experts were still trying to determine what caused the blast.
