<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 0406EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WritersStrike     06-04 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Writers Strike,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Writers-Producers Continue Contract Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAUREN BLAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators for movie and television
producers and scriptwriters agreed to continue contract talks this
weekend in an attempt to resolve a 13-week strike by the Writers
Guild of America.
   Both sides met Friday at the Alliance of Motion Picture and
Television Producers offices in Sherman Oaks but refused to say
what progress was made.
   ``People were very frank and candid. I think there is certainly
a new commitment to try on both sides,'' Brian Walton, executive
director of the guild told reporters after the meeting. He refused
to give details.
   Both sides said talks would continue over the weekend.
   Earlier Friday, striking scriptwriters sought to enlist owners
of ABC-TV affiliate stations nationwide in their labor dispute,
claiming the strike has caused television audiences to dwindle.
   The guild sent letters to owners and managers of 198 ABC
affiliates, urging them to press ABC to give ground in negotiations
to prevent further delays in the start of the fall TV season.
   The union will send similar letters to CBS and NBC affiliates,
said Cheryl Rhoden, spokeswoman for the guild. The ABC letters went
out first because the network's annual meeting for affiliates will
begin Monday in Los Angeles, she said.
   The writers walked out March 7 in a dispute that centers on
residuals, the payments they receive for reruns of one-hour
television shows. Demand for one-hour shows in rerun, or
syndication, is declining, and the producers had sought to index
residual payments to a show's rerun success.
   Lack of material has forced the networks to delay the fall
premieres of a number of series, and the writers, in their letter
to ABC affiliates, suggested quality had suffered as well.
   ``This strike is not only hurting writers. It's hurting you,''
the union letter said.
   TV's viewing audience declined 3 percent in the May rating
period, the letter said, ``and it's only going to get worse.''
   The absence of writers has forced studios to order TV movies
without needed rewrites, and the delayed fall shows will be rushed
into production, the letter said.
   In addition to residuals, other issues in the strike are
writers' demands for more say over changes made in scripts during
filming and greater credit for their work both on and off screen.
   The guild has signed independent contracts with about 80
independent producers, but the producers alliance maintains that
none of its large members have signed and that the producers who
did defect employ only a tiny fraction of the 3,000 active writers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
