<DOCNO> AP880604-0037 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 0409EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-SovietBook     06-04 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Soviet Book,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US, Soviet Writers Collaborate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One man served American presidents from
Franklin Roosevelt to John Kennedy, the other served Soviet leaders
in the central committee of the Communist party. Now they've
written a book together to show the faults and virtues of the
Soviet Union and the United States.
   ``We wanted to discuss the failures of the two systems,''
explained John Kenneth Galbraith, a former ambassador to India and
at 79 one of this country's best known economists.
   Stanislav Menshikov, 61, is the son of a former Soviet
ambassador in Washington. He agrees with Galbraith that the worst
problem the two systems have in common is bureaucracy. Galbraith is
concerned about bureaucracies in corporations; Menshikov about the
Soviet government.
   ``Our bureaucracy is more dangerous, more stifling, because it's
running not only the government but industry,'' Menshikov says.
   He now edits ``World Marxist Review'' in Prague, Czechoslovakia.
It is an official Communist organ published in 42 languages.
   They came together Friday night in a gilt-and-cream colored
salon of the Soviet embassy. They have met many times since they
first were introduced 24 years ago in a similar setting: Spaso
House, residence of the U.S. ambassador in Moscow.
   This time they were publicizing their book: ``Capitalism,
Communism and Coexistence: from a Bitter Past to a Better
Prospect.''
   The two spoke in brief interviews between greeting guests,
giving autographs and posing for pictures.
   Galbraith cited what he sees as parallels between Soviet and
American problems: the shortage of labor in ``low prestige''
industries, what he called the hardening of the arteries in big
industrial organizations.
   ``Some Soviet steel complexes are a lot like Pittsburgh,'' he
said.
   Menshikov compared the changes Mikhail S. Gorbachev is trying to
make in the Soviet Union with those made in this country under
Franklin Roosevelt. Both sets of reforms were designed to change
their systems in order to preserve them, he said.
   ``In Roosevelt's case what was the alternative?'' he asked. ``A
right-wing dictatorship, fascism _ or maybe communism.''
   He did not suggest what the alternatives to Gorbachev's reforms
would be.
   There are two kinds of coexistence, Menshikov explained.
   ``One is based on fear, on nuclear weapons _ it's unstable and
it can take you to the brink in no time: two ships that collide in
the Black Sea, two ladies who disagree and influence their
husbands,'' he said.
   Then he added: ``That's just a joke, of course, about the
ladies.''
   He suggested that in another kind of coexistence different
systems could live side by side just as different religions live
side by side in many countries.
   ``You remember there was a time when just to belong to a
different religion meant you were a hateful enemy,'' he said.
   The two men want to believe that kind of relationship will no
longer exist between people in the Soviet Union and the United
States.
   ``Our deeper purpose was to show that an American and a Russian
of different views could engage in civil and, we hoped, informative
discussions of our different and common problems,'' Galbraith
writes in the introduction to the American edition.
   Menshikov has written an introduction to the Russian edition, to
appear soon in Moscow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880604-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 0423EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-MilitaryCatalog     06-04 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Military Catalog,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GAO Cites Problems With Military Cataloging</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military is buying more parts than it
needs because of problems identifying the items in its inventory
catalog, a congressional study says.
   The U.S. General Accounting Office report, released Friday, said
the Federal Catalog System does not meet the congressional mandate
that every cataloged item be identified in a way that distinguishes
it from other parts.
   The GAO said it is conceivable that millions of dollars are
being needlessly spent to buy, catalog, store and issue duplicates
of items.
   ``The extent of duplication and other logistics problems caused
by inadequate item identification, or the unnecessary costs
incurred as a result, are largely unknown,'' the GAO concluded.
``However, these problems may be serious and costly.''
   The Federal Catalog System was established in 1952 to provide a
uniform cataloging system among the military services. By
identifying and differentiating supply items, cataloging enables
the government to know what it has in stock so it does not buy
items already in its inventory.
   The GAO said that as of the end of 1986, 30 percent of all
cataloged items did not have approved names and 29 percent were
described just well enough to meet minimum requirements.
   ``Thousands of items were misclassified or assigned duplicate
numbers in the federal catalog,'' the GAO added.
   Defense Department officials said the use of approved item names
has received greater emphasis in the past two years.
   ``The need to improve item identifications and reduce duplicate
items in the Federal Catalog System are central to many of the
ongoing efforts in the cataloging community,'' Jack Katzen, deputy
assistant secretary of defense for systems, said in a letter to the
GAO.
   The GAO said the Defense Logistics Agency has recently taken
several steps to improve item identification, but that for the most
part it is too early to gauge their effectiveness.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
