<1ST_LINE>u i AM-MineDisaster 2ndLd-Writethru a0468 06-04 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mine Disaster, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0468,0617</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Miners Found Alive After Wednesday's Mine Blast</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with details of miners, company
also reporting find. PICKS up 9th graf, `Wednesday's blast ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN FISCHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BORKEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six miners buried 330 feet
underground for more than two days after an explosion in a coal
shaft were found alive early Saturday.
   Hesse State radio said rescuers discovered the survivors in an
air pocket. They were exhausted but otherwise appeared not be
seriously injured, the report said.
   A spokesman for Preussen Elektra, the company which owns the
mine, also said the six did not suffer serious injuries and were
reunited with their families.
   The six men were among 57 miners in the shaft when the explosion
occurred Wednesday. The radio said rescuers were now hoping to find
more survivors.
   On Thursday, mine officials had given up hope of finding any of
the minors alive. By late Friday, rescuers had found 36 bodies and
had brought 30 bodies to the surface, according to the company
spokesman. Fifteen miners were still missing.
   The first of the six survivors was brought to the surface early
Saturday morning, about 60 hours after the explosion.
   Of the six, five were West Germans and one a Turk. There were 14
Turkish workers among the 57 miners trapped by the blast.
   Rescue workers said earlier that there were high concentrations
of deadly carbon monoxide in the mine. The radio report said the
survivors may have been helped by fresh air pumped into the mine to
aid the rescuers.
   Wednesday's blast at the Stolzenbach mine in the town of Borken,
72 miles northeast of Frankfurt, trapped the miners 330 feet below
the surface. The methane gas explosion rocked the ground like an
earthquake.
   On Friday, before the survivors were found, grieving family
members gathered at a makeshift morgue to say farewell to the
victims of West Germany's worst mining disaster in 26 years.
Turkish immigrants were among the dead.
   Also Friday, Heinz-Werner Meyer, the head of the union
representing 350,000 West German miners and energy workers, called
for ``an improvement of safety underground.''
   ``A thorough investigation of the causes of the accident and the
implementation of all possible safety measures are needed to
minimize the danger of an accident,'' Meyer said in an interview on
Saarland Radio.
   But Heinz Cramer, a member of the board of the company that owns
the ill-fated mine, said after the disaster: ``All safety measures
were adhered to.''
   A local prosecutor in the town of Borken was investigating the
accident to see if any criminal charges were warranted.
   Experts were still trying to determine what caused the blast.
   Rescue workers pulled the bodies to the surface using breathing
masks to shield them against dangerous levels of the deadly carbon
monoxide that had killed some of the miners.
   Many of the miners whose bodies have been retrieved suffocated
from lack of air after their emergency breathing masks ran out of
oxygen, while others died from their injuries, officials said.
   The blast killed about one-third of the work force at the
Preussen Elektra mine. The company is the leading employer in
Borken and one of West Germany's largest utilities.
   Peter Carl Ruehland, spokesman for Preussen Elektra, said the
company would pay funeral costs and the costs of flying the
immigrant workers' bodies back to Turkey, if family members
requested it.
   The Borken explosion is the worst West German mining accident
since 299 men died in 1962 at the Luisenthal mine in Saarland state
along the border with France.
</TEXT>
