<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Thatcher-Soviet     06-04 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Thatcher-Soviet,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thatcher Says Military Burden Forced Gorbachev's Reforms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher said Mikhail S.
Gorbachev has to reform the Soviet Union because his people can no
longer endure their military burden.
   ``They could not have gone on surviving as they were,'' the
British leader told a television interviewer at her 10 Downing
Street office Friday night.
   She spoke a few hours after saying goodbye to President Reagan,
who stopped over in London on his way home after his Moscow summit
with Gorbachev.
   In a separate interview with commercial Independent Television
News, Mrs. Thatcher said she knew it was impossible for the two
superpower leaders to reach agreement on strategic nuclear arms
reductions this week in Moscow.
   She said: ``It is a very complicated equation. I knew it was not
possible to do it. So, I think, did Mr. Gorbachev.''
   Speaking to the British Broadcasting Corp. program
``Newsnight,'' Mrs. Thatcher, who herself met with Gorbachev in
Moscow in spring 1987, said: ``I had the feeling that certainly
many people at the top in the Soviet Union _ and I believe many
other people as well _ knew they could not have gone on surviving
as they were.
   ``They could not go on with that military strength because
people wanted a higher standard of living.
   ``They had to change, and when you change, you do not know quite
the speed at which it will go. You do not know the difficulties,''
she said.
   Gorbachev has pushed a wide-ranging program of social and
economic reforms, which he calls ``perestroika'' or restructuring.
   The London-based International Institute for Strategic Studies
said in its annual, ``The Military Balance,'' in November that
while there was very little reliable information on Soviet defense
spending over the past year, it had announced at the end of 1986 a
record defense budget of $30.4 billion.
   However, the institute said most Western observers believed the
announced Soviet defense figures are only one-tenth or less of what
is actually spent. U.S. officials have put Soviet defense spending
at 16 to 17 percent of the country's gross national product.
   The institute said that would amount to $700 billion, compared
to the U.S. congressionally-approved figure of $296 billion for the
1988 U.S. defense budget.
   Mrs. Thatcher described Gorbachev's vision for his country as a
``miracle'' and said he was sticking to his reforming vision with
``great constancy and determination.''
</TEXT>
