<DOCNO> AP880604-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 0431EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NewZealandQuake     06-04 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-New Zealand Quake,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strong Quake Hits New Zealand, Nobody Reported Hurt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHRISTCHURCH, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong earthquake rattled the
lower part of New Zealand's South Island today, cutting electricity
to thousands of customers, shattering windows and causing several
landslides, officials said.
   No-one was reported injured by the quake, which registered 6.5
on the Richter scale, police said.
   In Washington, the U.S. Geological Survey reported that the
quake was the strongest tremor in the general area in more than 12
years, since a magnitude 6.7 earthquake on May 4, 1976.
   The 11:37 a.m. quake was centered in the Southern Alps near the
southwest corner of South Island, near Lake Te Anau and about 450
miles southwest of Wellington.
   Landslides closed two roads. Several water mains also burst
because of the tremor.
   The New Zealand Seismological Observatory said the quake was
similar to the one which caused severe damage to the town of
Edgecumbe and other parts of the Bay of Plenty district in March
last year.
   ``If it had occured in a more populated area there would likely
have been a lot of damage,'' said Dr. Ewan Smith, seismologist at
the Wellington observatory.
   Senior Constable Lloyd Matheson of Te Anau police station
described the quake as ``a very strong rocking motion _ shuddering
with a large roaring noise.''
   In addition to cutting power to an estimated 40,000 consumers in
Christchurch, the quake interrupted power supplies to the town of
Te Anau and parts of the city of Invercargill, 80 miles south of
the lake, police said.
   The Richter scale is an open-ended gauge of energy released by
an earthquake as measured by ground motion recorded on a
seismograph. Every increase of one number means that the ground
motion is 10 times greater.
   A quake with a magnitude of 6 can cause severe damage in a
populated area.
</TEXT>
