<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Biaggi-Wedtech     06-04 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biaggi-Wedtech,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Testimony About Meese At Wedtech Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III asked about a
contract for Wedtech Corp., a witness in the racketeering trial
involving the scandal-plagued defense contractor said in the first
testimony on what Meese allegedly said.
   Meese has denied helping the Bronx contractor obtain the Navy
pontoon contract.
   However, former Wedtech President Anthony Guariglia on Friday
testified at the U.S. District Court trial of U.S. Rep. Mario
Biaggi and six others that Meese asked about the contract at a
diplomatic ball in Washington in 1985.
   Biaggi and the others are accused of turning Wedtech, which is
now in bankruptcy, into a racketeering enterprise for the payment
of bribes to obtain no-bid government contracts.
   Guariglia is the last of four former Wedtech officials who have
pleaded guilty to corruption charges to testify at the trial in
exchange for leniency.
   He was the first witness to testify at the 13-week-old trial
about anything Meese allegedly said about the contract.
   Guariglia and other company officials have said they paid
$800,000 to attorney E. Robert Wallach, a close friend and
associate of Meese, to influence the attorney general.
   They have said Wallach told them he got Meese to intercede on
Wedtech's behalf for a series of contracts worth $143 million to
build pontoons.
   Wallach is under indictment on federal racketeering charges for
allegedly taking payoffs from Wedtech officials to influence Meese
and other public officials.
   Guariglia told the jury that Wallach introduced him, Wedtech
founder John Mariotta and other company officials to Meese and his
wife at an ambassador's ball in Washington.
   ``Mr. Wallach said to Mr. Meese what a fine job we were doing in
the South Bronx, that the company was growing and employment was
growing,'' said Guariglia.
   ``Mr. Meese asked how we were doing with the pontoon contract.
Mr. Mariotta said `Fine.' Mr. Meese asked if we were on time with
our deliveries, and I believe Mr. Mariotta said `Fine,' and that
was the end of the meeting.''
   Meese, who has not been charged with any wrongdoing, has denied
any involvement in that contract, but admitted intervening with the
Army to help Wedtech win an engine contract in 1982 while he was
presidential counselor.
   Meese attorney Nathan Lewin said Friday that because the
attorney general was in Germany, ``I can't give any direct comment
on whether he recalls or doesn't recall making that statement.
   ``If that statement was made by him (Meese), it is consistent
with his statements concerning his limited involvement or knowledge
of Wedtech matters,'' said Lewin, reached at his Washington office.
   Lewin said Meese ``has acknowledged that he had been told by
Wallach that Wedtech had obtained a pontoon contract.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
