<DOCNO> AP880604-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 0511EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Brazil-President     06-04 0617</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brazil-President,0639</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brazilians Want No More Excuses From President</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANA HAYWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRAZILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Now that President Jose Sarney has won
his coveted fifth year in office, Brazilians say he has also lost
his excuse for not boosting the nation's faltering economy.
   Congressmen, even leftists opposed to Sarney, expressed relief
the controversial issue was finally laid to rest when lawmakers on
Thursday gave him his long-sought extra year.
   However, many also said it was time for Sarney to show his stuff.
   ``Now, he has no more excuses,'' said Rep. Delfin Netto.
   Added Sen. Mario Covas, ``We'll see if finally his government
takes some initiative.''
   For his part, the president promised action. ``I will now
perform my duties with even more responsibility,'' said Sarney, the
nation's first civilian leader after 21 years of military rule.
   Legislators, who since February have been rewriting Brazil's
eighth constitution, voted in an historic session to give Sarney
the five years he fought so hard for. The vote was 328 in favor,
222 against, with three abstentions.
   The vote means 75 million Brazilians, including a generation in
their 40s who have never voted for president, will go to the polls
in November 1989, 29 years after the last presidential balloting.
   Polls have shown in the past year that most people in this
country of 143 million people wanted elections for president in
November 1988. Instead, elections will be held a year later, and
Sarney will step down in March 15, 1990.
   Sarney has said he has been ``hostage'' to the Constituent
Assembly, which took nearly a year and a half to lengthen his
four-year term.
   The president said uncertainty over his political future was at
the center of Brazil's triple-digit inflation, which has hit an
all-time high under his administration.
   Sarney also said he needed an extra year to consolidate Brazil's
transition to democracy. He said it would help in negotiations with
the International Monetary Fund and international bankers on
Brazil's $121 billion debt.
   He further hinted Brazil's democracy was at risk if he was
ousted after a four-year term, meaning Brazil's armed forces
wouldn't accept elections this year for fear of a leftist surge.
   Yet opponents of the five-year term see it differently.
   Sarney critics who crowded the public stands as voting took
place Thursday unfurled a flag reading: ``Five years _ betrayal to
the people.''
   Sarney's term was up for a vote because he was not popularly
elected. The 57-year-old provincial politician and poet from the
poor northeastern state of Maranhao came to power as the vice
president for the popular statesman Tancredo Neves, who died before
taking office.
   They were elected in indirect electoral college voting called by
military generals, who put Sarney on the Neves ticket. The vote was
to pave the way for non-miliary rule in this country where the
armed forces had governed since a 1964 coup.
   Although legally entitled to six years under the existing
constitution, Neves promised his transition government would end
after four years and that the Constituent Assembly would decide on
the next elections.
   Sarney initially said he only wanted a four-year term. Last
year, he said he needed another year because he had been unable to
put into effect the government programs he wanted and that there
was political uncertainty.
   Newspapers criticized the longer term and charged Sarney used
his political influence unethically.
   The powerful daily Folha de Sao Paulo wrote: ``The five-year
vote cost how many privileges and at what cost to the taxpayer?''
   The influential Rio de Janeiro newspaper said: ``President
Sarney obtained what he wanted: a fifth year to try to do what he
was uncapable of doing in three.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
