<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 0558EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SunkenShips     06-04 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sunken Ships,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sunken Japanese Ships Found in Pacific</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KOROR, Palau (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Divers have discovered 55 Japanese warships,
cargo boats and submarines sunk during World War II off Palau in
the western Pacific Ocean, the government announced.
   ``No one knew they were there,'' government spokesman Bonifacio
Basilius said Friday.
   Elderly Palauans believe the vessels were part of the Japanese
fleet used to protect the Philippines that had moved to Malakal
Harbor off Koror, Palau's capital, Basilius said.
   Japanese ships anchored at Malakal and Airai Harbor were
attacked by U.S. carrier-based fighter planes in March and July
1944, he said.
   Japan occupied Palau, which is about 600 miles east of the
Philippines and nearly 2,000 miles south of Tokyo, from 1922 until
American forces captured the island chain in 1945.
   The ships were found during the past four weeks by U.S. Navy
reservists on summer duty from Honolulu, Long Beach, Calif., San
Diego, and Texas, Basilius said.
   The U.S. National Park Service has been locating and marking
sunken ships, the spokesman said. The joint Park Service-Navy
project is expected to end in two weeks.
   Most of the search has been in and around Palau's rock islands,
which are limestone coral reefs with a mushroom-like appearance
created by wave erosion. None are inhabited.
   The divers are using underwater robots with cameras, Basilius
said. None of the ships were visible from the ocean surface, and
some have been found in waters 150 feet deep. Most were less than
five miles from shore.
   Divers were able to read the names on five of the ships, which
they described as in good shape for being under water for more than
40 years, Basilius said. The warships seemed to be destroyers.
   Palauans have known about a dozen other sunken Japanese ships,
Basilius said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880604-0050 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 0451EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-AIDS-BloodBank Bjt   06-04 0634</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS-Blood Bank, Bjt,0652</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jurors Clear Blood Bank in AIDS Liability Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state jury cleared a blood bank of liability in
the AIDS infection of a woman who received a tainted transfusion,
and a defense attorney said it was a victory for blood banks facing
similar lawsuits.
   The Denver District Court jury on Friday found United Blood
Services not liable for damages in the case of Susie Quintana, 50,
of Dolores, who contracted AIDS from a 1983 transfusion after an
accidental gunshot wound. The blood was from the United Blood
Services bank in Albuquerque, N.M.
   The six-member jury Thursday ordered an infectious disease
expert whose AIDS test falsely found Mrs. Quintana free of the
virus to pay $70,000 in damages, but found no liability on the part
of her former family doctor.
   Lawyers have said the case may be the first in the nation in
which a jury decided an AIDS victim's claim against a blood bank.
In a similar case in California in 1986, a settlement was reached
before the trial ended.
   ``There are many lawsuits, and they (the jurors) have done a
great service to blood banks around the country,'' defense attorney
Steve Labensky said after the verdict. ``Defense attorneys around
the country were watching this. A victory here will probably assure
a victory elsewhere.''
   Wiping tears from her eyes, Mrs. Quintana said she knew the jury
faced a ``tough decision'' in her case. ``But it means AIDS
patients will just have to keep fighting,'' said the mother of
four. ``I've fought this thing every since I found out I had it,
and I'll continue to fight it.''
   Mrs. Quintana and her 53-year-old husband, Chris, have not
decided whether to appeal, said their attorney, Maureen Reidy Witt.
   The southwest Colorado couple's suit sought unspecified damages,
but Witt asked the jury in closing arguments to award Quintanas
more than $13 million.
   The jury said the infectious disease expert, Dr. Donald Kearns,
was liable because he failed to explain precautions the couple
should have taken to avoid exposing Mrs. Quintana's husband to
acquired immune deficiency syndrome.
   Although the Quintanas testified they had sex after the tests,
Quintana has tested negative for the AIDS virus.
   Dr. Edward G. Merritt, the former family physician, was also
accused of failing to diagnose the virus and not recommending
precautions but was found not liable.
   The couple's lawsuit named the blood bank, Kearns and Merritt.
The Quintanas did not sue Southwest Memorial Hospital in Cortez,
where Mrs. Quintana received the transfusion.
   In closing arguments, Witt said the blood bank was negligent for
failing to properly screen donors and test its blood supply.
   She said testing routinely used at the time to detect the
hepatitis-B virus in blood could have been useful in eliminating
homosexual blood donors, who are at high risk for that disease as
well as AIDS.
   Douglas Irish, an attorney for the blood bank, said tests for
AIDS in blood were not available until two years after Mrs.
Quintana's transfusion.
   Labensky said his client felt ``what they were doing was
reasonably prudent at the time, and apparently the jurors agreed.''
   Jurors said they had difficulty deciding what AIDS screening
standards were at the time and whether the blood bank lived up to
them.
   ``Three of us felt they met the industry's requirements, and
three did not,'' said foreman Albert Gonzales. ``I was surprised we
came up with an answer.
   ``While there was tremendous sympathy for Mrs. Quintana and her
family, we had to set that aside and look at the evidence.''
   AIDS breaks down the body's immune system, leaving victims
susceptible to infections and cancer.
   It is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or
syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products,
and from pregnant women to their offspring.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880604-0051 </DOCNO>
