<1ST_LINE>r i PM-MadameMao 1stLd-Writethru a0429 06-04 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Madame Mao, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0429,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jiang Qing Reportedly Has Throat Cancer, Refusing Operation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Jiang being treated in
hospital. PICKS up 7th graf, `The newspaper ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jiang Qing, the widow of Chinese leader Mao
Tse-tung who played a key role in China's Cultural Revolution, has
throat cancer but is refusing a treatment that would leave her
voiceless, a pro-Beijing newspaper reported today.
   Jiang Qing, 74, is receiving treatment for the cancer at a
Beijing tumor hospital and was told by doctors she needed an
operation, the Chinese-language Wen Wei Po said in a front page
article that did not cite sources.
   But she refused the operation because she no longer would be
able to talk, the report said.
   Jiang was a member of the notorious ``Gang of Four,'' who were
accused of ordering illegal arrests during the 1966-76 Cultural
Revolution and trying to seize total power after Mao died in 1976.
   They and six other Cultural Revolution leaders were convicted in
1981 after a lengthy show trial. Jiang was initially sentenced to
death but the sentence was later changed to life in prison.
   Chinese officials earlier this year said Jiang was under
treatment in prison for an unspecified ``geriatric disease.'' But
the Wen Wei Po story said she received permission to be treated in
the hospital.
   The newspaper also reported that Chen Boda, formerly a close
aide to Mao and one of the fallen power-brokers of the Cultural
Revolution, was at the tumor hospital being treated for cancer.
   Officials earlier confirmed that Chen, 83, one of the most
fervent and hated persecutors of alleged rightists during the
Cultural Revolution, had been released on bail for medical
treatment. He was serving an 18-year term.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
