<DOCNO> AP880604-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 0617EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Arms     06-04 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Arms,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Arms Adviser Says START Treaty Will Be Difficult</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading U.S. arms official said today that it
is still ``theoretically possible'' for the superpowers to reach an
accord on long-range nuclear weapons before President Reagan leaves
office.
   However, Edward Rowny, who serves as special adviser to the
president and secretary of state on arms control, said serious
obstacles remain.
   ``If the Soviets were to work as hard and as fast as they worked
the last couple days in Moscow, yes, we could have a treaty,''
Rowny said at a news conference. ``It remains to be seen whether
they will show that much interest.''
   Rowny came to Beijing to brief Chinese officials on the
just-ended Moscow summit Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev and
Reagan, whose term ends this year.
   ``I don't want to say there couldn't be a START (strategic, or
long-range, nuclear arms) agreement. I'm also saying it's extremely
difficult and many, many difficult issues remain,'' he said.
   Among those issues are verification of air- and sea-launched
cruise missiles and mobile intercontinental ballistic missiles as
well as differences over Reagan's so-called Star Wars plan to put
defensive weapons in space, he said.
   Rowny said Washington ``recognizes China's support'' in bringing
about the just-signed Soviet-U.S. treaty to abolish
intermediate-range missiles. He declined to characterize his
meetings today with Vice Foreign Minister Zhu Qizhen and other
Chinese officials, saying only, ``I get good questions and good
support from the Chinese.''
   The official Chinese media has been mildly critical of the
fourth Reagan-Gorbachev summit, particularly on the issue of
disarmament.
   ``This summit had few concrete achievements to its credit,'' the
official China Daily said today in an editorial.
   The people of the world, it said, are happy to see U.S.-Soviet
dialogue but ``are far from satisfied when it (the summit) ended
without a breakthrough in the talks on a treaty cutting by half the
strategic offensive nuclear arsenals of both superpowers, which the
summit was previously intended for.''
   Rowny said, ``We believe we have done all that the traffic will
bear'' on strategic disarmament for now.
   He also expressed concern that momentum on arms control will be
lost as Gorbachev and other Soviet leaders prepare for a major
Communist Party meeting in the coming weeks.
   ``He'll be distracted and others will be distracted,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
