<1ST_LINE>u i PM-TunnelCollapse     06-04 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tunnel Collapse,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>27 Miners Feared Dead In Tunnel Collapse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DIPOLOG, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 27 gold miners were
believed killed when mine tunnels crudely dug on a remote
mountainside caved in after a heavy rain, a local official said
today.
   One miner was rescued by fellow workers shortly after the
accident occurred Friday night but his left leg was so badly
injured that doctors had to amputate it when he arrived at a
hospital here today, the official said.
   Benito Tolentino, mayor of the municipality of Sibutad where the
cave-in occurred, told reporters that a lack of equipment was
hampering rescue efforts on Mount Lablab, 30 miles from here and
450 miles southeast of Manila.
   Tolentino, who accompanied the unidentified survivor to report
the accident, said rescuers were armed only with picks and shovels
and were having difficulty reaching the trapped miners.
   He said there was little hope that any of them was still alive.
   Tolentino said 28 people were working in a network of tunnels
below a 45-foot-deep shaft when the surface caved in after two days
of heavy rain. He said he has ordered a temporary halt to any more
gold prospecting at the site.
   About 20,000 prospectors from different parts of Mindanao island
have converged on this area since gold was discovered there last
September, Tolentino said. He added that at least 12 people had
been killed in previous cave-ins.
   Hundreds of people have been killed in similar accidents
throughout Mindanao over the years.
   Armed only with picks and shovels, the miners often work without
any professional supervision. Some of the men burrow into
mountainsides while others use wooden pans to wash dirt away from
gold nuggets or dust in streams.
</TEXT>
