<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 0623EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDSBill     06-04 0482</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Bill,0498</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>R.I. House Passes Bill To Require AIDS Testing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rhode Island House passed a sweeping
bill requiring the AIDS virus test for all prison inmates and for
marriage license applicants, hospital patients and others unless
they sign a waiver.
   ``I think it's something everyone can live with,'' Rep. Anthony
Carnevale Jr., Democratic chairman of the House Health, Education
and Welfare Committee, said following the action Friday.
   The measure was expected to receive Senate approval. It closely
resembles a bill originally proposed by Republican Gov. Edward D.
DiPrete, and he said he would sign it.
   The bill would require the test for the virus that causes
acquired immune deficiency syndrome for prison inmates and people
convicted of prostitution and intravenous drug use.
   It requires that marriage license applicants, hospital patients
and clients of family planning and sexually transmitted disease
clinics be tested unless they sign a waiver.
   The bill contains language to prevent discrimination against
those who carry, or are perceived to carry, the virus. It requires
health care providers to report the names of those testing positive
to the state Department of Health.
   ``Rhode Island has been a national leader on the AIDS problem,''
DiPrete said. ``I think you'll soon find other states following our
leadership.''
   As of Jan 1., Illinois has required marriage license applicants
to take the test.
   The House also approved two of five proposed amendments. The
bill was expanded to include testing for disability insurance
applicants, and a provision was dropped that would have seen the
measure expire July 1, 1990, if insurance companies had not
established a high-risk insurance pool for those who test positive
by then.
   ``If the insurers don't want to come through the way they say
they will, you will already be back in session'' and can deal with
it then, Carnevale told the House.
   Legislators tabled an amendment to require physicians only to
inform marriage applicants of the hazards of AIDS and the
availability of tests.
   Rep. Nicholas Tsiongas pleaded passionately for dropping the
requirement that the names of those testing positive be reported to
authorities.
   The Democrat, who is the Legislature's only physician, said a
central registry would deter those in high-risk groups from being
tested. The House rejected his amendment.
   The House also defeated an amendment to remove
anti-discrimination language.
   ``This is a health care bill and not one that emphasizes civil
rights,'' said Rep. Bradford Gorham, the amendment's Republican
sponsor. ``What we're doing is saying people with AIDS have all
sorts of rights that those people with other deadly diseases''
don't, he argued.
   Carnevale disagreed. ``It's the heart of the bill. You can't
tell someone to be tested without giving them protection.''
   Rep. Ray Rickman, a Democrat who voted against the bill, said it
would waste enormous sums of money testing people not at high risk.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
