<1ST_LINE>u i PM-USJets 1stLd-Writethru a0501 06-04 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US Jets, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0501,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Agrees To Base Planes From Spain In Italy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 7 grafs with details of decision.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Italian government today agreed to accept the
U.S. F-16 fighter planes being evicted from Spain, a cabinet
minister announced.
   The decision, which had been expected, followed a formal request
from NATO to transfer the 72 nuclear-capable jet fighters to Italy.
   The planes, which make up the U.S. Air Force's 401st Tactical
Fighter Wing, are now based at Torrejon air base near Madrid. Spain
has said they must be withdrawn within three years.
   Remo Gaspari, a Christian Democrat minister, announced the
decision to reporters while the Cabinet meeting led by Premier
Ciriaco De Mita was still under way.
   ``We have taken the decision naturally hoping it will be like
the missiles in Comiso,'' Gaspari said.
   Comiso is the Sicilian base where U.S. cruise missiles were
installed as part of NATO's response to a Soviet missile buildup.
The missiles will now be removed from Comiso under the U.S.-Soviet
treaty on medium-range nuclear missiles.
   There was no immediate announcement on where in Italy the planes
will be based.
   Italian government officials have said the transfering of the
F-16s would be examined by Parliament but that a vote would likely
not be needed.
   The Communists, Italy's second largest party, are opposed to the
transfer. But De Mita's coalition of his Christian Democrats
together with Socialists, Republicans, Social Democrats and
Liberals has a comfortable majority in both houses.
   NATO's defense ministers made the formal request to Italy during
a meeting in Brussels on May 26.
   Lord Carrington, secretary general of the Western alliance, said
then that the planes represent ``a considerable portion of our
strength in the southern region.''
</TEXT>
