<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Malaysia-Detainees 1stLd-Writethru a0485 06-04 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Malaysia-Detainees, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0485,0625</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Released Detainee Holds Press Conference</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 5th graf, `Tan was ...,' to UPDATE with
comments from prime minister. PICKS up 6th graf, `The bespectacled
...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HARI S. MANIAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An opposition leader accused the
government today of holding him and six other political activists
on false charges and demanded freedom for other political prisoners
in Malaysia.
   ``We have been detained under trumped-up charges,'' said Tan
Seng Giaw, vice chairman of the opposition Democratic Action Party
who was released Friday after spending more than six months in jail.
   Another opposition leader, also released, said he was looking
forward to getting back to politics and union work and that the
prison experience had left him unbowed.
   ``I want the Prime Minister to release all those who were
arrested with me and are being held under the ISA,'' Tan said
during the conference held at the party's national headquarters.
   Tan was referring to Malaysia's Internal Security Act which
allows imprisonment without trial for activities which challenge
the Malaysian government. Under the act, individuals may be
imprisoned indefinitely with a board reviewing the detention every
six months.
   Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad later told reporters the
government does not intend to detain forever those arrested under
the ISA.
   ``We are not keeping them forever. It depends on them,'' he said
when commenting on Friday's release. Mahathir said the prisoners
would get a fair review in front of the appeal board.
   The bespectacled Tan, stroking a goatie beard grown while he was
in the Kamunting Prison near Ipoh, said he had not been subjected
to physical torture.
   Tan came to the press conference directly from the prison, 120
miles north of here.
   The six others released Friday included opposition figures, a
Christian social worker, a university lecturer and Chinese
educators.
   Tan said the conditions for his release restrict him to his home
at night, and he must tell police when he plans to leave the Kuala
Lumpur area.
   The acting secretary general of Tan's party, Lee Lam Thye, said
the party launched a signature campaign to urge the prime minister
to release the remaining detainees.
   A total of 109 people were detained during a two-month period
beginning last October. Tan was jailed on Nov. 2, 1987.
   Prime Minister Mohamad Mahathir has maintained the detentions
were necessary because the individuals contributed to racial
tension and their arrests were needed to prevent Malay-Chinese
racial clashes.
   On Oct. 28 last year, the government also banned the
English-language Star daily, the Chinese-language Sin Chew Jit Poh
daily, and the Malay bi-weekly Watan for fanning racial tension.
   Tan said that while in jail the detainees were allowed to
exercise and read, but newspapers and magazines were censored
before delivery.
   Asked if he was interrogated, Tan replied, ``What is there to
interrogate?'' He said he had not advocated violence and that he
was not a subversive.
   Tan added the detention has not changed his views in any way and
he was determined to continue his fight for ``a better country for
all''.
   The 46-year-old physician was joined by his wife and two
daughters after the conference.
   Democratic Action Party parliamentarian and Central Committee
Member Vethamuthu David, who was also released, said detention was
difficult but that it failed to change his political views.
   David at a press conference at his residence today said he was
looking forward to going back to his political and union work
   David is Secretary General of the Malaysian Trades Union
Congress and General Secretary of the Transport Workers Union. He
denied he had fanned racial tensions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
