<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BabyFound 1stLd-Writethru a0471 06-04 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Baby Found, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0471,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Missing Baby Reunited With Family</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 4-8, bgng, `Sompis told ...,' with 6 grafs to
UPDATE with court ruling baby can go back to Thailand. PICKS up,
9th graf, `Nui was ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A two-year-old boy who was
abducted 17 months ago in Thailand for sale on the baby black
market has been reunited with his mother in Malaysia.
   The joy of meeting with her baby was reflected on Sompis
Kleepjampee's face at the Tengku Ampuan Fatimah Children's Home in
Kuantan on Friday.
   Sompis, 32, lost her youngest child, Nui Kleepjampee, in
February 1987 in Prakanong, Bangkok, the National News Agency
Bernama reported from Kuantan.
   Sompis told reporters through an interpreter that her son was
kidnapped by an old woman who had offered her a job. The baby was
then sold to a ring that markets babies for adoption.
   Sompis said the woman came to her house in Prakanong, Thailand,
and offered her a job because the woman said she felt pity for her
after learning that her husband had left her and that she supported
four children, including Nui.
   She said the woman later took her to a beauty salon and carried
Nui, who was then nine months old.
   The woman ran off with the baby while she was shampooing her
hair in the salon, she said.
   Today, a court ruled that Sompis could take the child home to
Thailand.
   Sompis, shed tears of joy, soon after magistrate Mrs. Mariana
Yahya, gave the order in Kuantan, 120 miles east of the capital,
the national news agency Bernama reported.
   Nui was among five Thai children who were rescued and placed in
the children's home under protection of the Welfare Services
Ministry after they were kidnapped and sold in Malaysia by a
criminal syndicate.
   Thai police and Malaysian authorities found Nui and three other
babies in Mentakab, Malaysia, and the fifth one was found nearby in
Jerantut earlier this year.
   The baby found in Jerantut was reunited with its mother in the
home in February. Santi Isrowuthakul, a staff member of the Center
for the Protection of Children's Rights in Bangkok, said his
organization was still trying to contact families of the other
three Thai babies.
   He said the syndicate that was involved in kidnapping the five
babies had been smashed after the March arrest of a 72-year-old
woman in Thailand.
</TEXT>
