<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 0634EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Mecham     06-04 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham,0624</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Notes At Issue In Mecham Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prosecutors in former Gov. Evan
Mecham's criminal trial asked that the jury be allowed to see a set
of notes once considered a ``smoking gun'' in the charge he
concealed a $300,000 campaign loan.
   Maricopa County Superior Court Judge Michael Ryan said Friday he
would rule before the trial resumes Monday on whether to allow
testimony on the three pages of notes by Vern Gasser, a former
member of the Mecham Finance Committee.
   Meanwhile, former U.S. Rep. Sam Steiger, who was convicted of
pressuring a parole board member while working as a gubernatorial
aide to Mecham, was sentenced Friday to four years probation, a
$5,480 fine and 700 hours of community service.
   Steiger, 59, was convicted April 7 of theft by extortion in
threatening Board of Pardons and Paroles member Ron Johnson over a
personnel vote.
   Mecham and his brother, Willard, are charged with concealing the
$350,000 loan from Tempe developer Barry Wolfson. Willard Mecham
was his brother's 1986 campaign treasurer.
   The notes, which Gasser took during a finance committee meeting
in fall 1986, were considered a ``smoking gun'' against Mecham
during January's House impeachment hearings. The notes say, ``show
Evan borrowed money'' and ``don't show borrowed money.''
   However, Gasser said in court Friday he could not recall who
made the statements or who attended the meeting.
   In arguments with the jury absent, Willard Mecham's lawyer, Joe
Keilp, said the notes and testimony should not be admitted. Keilp
said he feared there would be implications that Willard Mecham may
have made the statements Gasser's notes referred to.
   Prosecutor Barnett Lotstein said the notes should be admitted
because they referred to a meeting involving Mecham campaign
strategists.
   Earlier Friday, Ryan rejected a motion for a mistrial by the
defense, which contended the prosecution presented improper
evidence implying wrongdoing in the handling of the Mecham
campaign's checkbook.
   The judge said he thought the testimony Thursday from a state
handwriting expert was ``quite innocuous'' and may prove relevant
regarding Willard Mecham's bookkeeping practices.
   Handwriting expert William Flynn had testified there had been a
number of ``whiteouts, erasures and alterations'' in the checkbook.
He did not speculate on the reasons for the changes.
   The Mecham brothers sat with their attorneys and declined to
talk to reporters.
   Jurors were read parts of Willard Mecham's January testimony to
the state grand jury in which he denied wrongdoing when he lumped
the $350,000 loan into a $465,000 total listed on financial reports
as a contribution from Evan Mecham.
   ``I felt he (Evan Mecham) would eventually be responsible for
paying it back,'' Willard Mecham told the grand jury. ``I didn't
feel I was doing anything wrong at the time and certainly didn't
feel I was violating the law.''
   The transcript also showed Willard Mecham said he did not know
until after the loan's existence was diclosed by the news media
about a letter in which his brother promised Wolfson the loan would
remain confidential.
   Willard Mecham testified at the time that he was told by the
secretary of state's office that similar amounts could be lumped
together, but he did not ask whether amounts from different sources
could be combined.
   If convicted on all six counts of perjury, willful concealment
and filing false documents, Evan Mecham faces up to 22 years in
prison. Willard Mecham faces three similar counts and up to 9{
years in prison if convicted.
   The first-term Republican governor was removed from office April
4 when the state Senate convicted him of two unrelated impeachment
counts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880604-0062 </DOCNO>
