<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea 1stLd-Writethru a0493 06-04 0689</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0493,0705</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Orders Major Crackdown On Unrest, Student Burns Himself</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with student burning himself in
protest, picks up 4th graf ``The government ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A radical protester tried to burn
himself to death and four student leaders were arrested at a U.S.
Army base today as the government ordered a crackdown on violent
unrest.
   A student identified as Park Rae-chun, 24, doused himself with
inflammable liquid and ignited it in an anti-government protest at
Soongshil University in southern Seoul.
   ``Overthrow military fascists,'' Park shouted before setting
himself afire. Hospital officials said he was in critical condition.
   Two other radical students have killed themselves in the past
month as part of anti-government protests. Ritual suicide is a
traditional form of protest to try to shame the government.
   Four radical student leaders were arrested at U.S. Army
headquarters in Seoul after they tried to force their way through
its main gate. The students, who were seized by South Korean
police, wanted to see U.S. Army commander Gen. Louis Menetrey to
demand permission to march to the North Korean border.
   Radical students plan to march to the Communist North Korean
border June 10 to try to force reunification of the divided Korean
peninsula. A U.S. Army spokesman said that only the South Korean
government can grant permission for civilians to visit the border
and that it was a purely domestic matter.
   Meanwhile, Prime Minister Lee Hyun-jae warned in a nationally
televised speech that the government would not tolerate violent
protests by radical students and striking workers. He said the
government was determined to maintain law and order.
   ``The government will sternly deal with all violent acts,'' he
said.
   South Korea has been hit by a wave of violent protests in recent
weeks with students demonstrating against the government and the
United States. In addition, striking factory workers have been
seeking pay hikes.
   Authorities said students attacked two police stations in the
southern city of Kwangju with firebombs before dawn today and
caused minor damage. No arrests or injuries were reported.
   Lee accused radical students who plan to march to the border
June 10 of being pro-North Korean and threatening the safety of
South Korea. The pro-Western south and the totalitarian north are
bitter enemies who often clash.
   ``North Korea has been strengthening its stance ... apparently
encouraged by South Korean students,'' Lee said.
   Radical students plan to march June 10 to the border truce site
of Panmunjom to meet with North Korean students and reunite the two
nations.
   Unification of the two Koreas, divided since 1945, is a highly
emotional issue for many Koreans, and radicals have been attempting
to use it to gain support. Most people in the south are distrustful
of the north, which invaded the south in 1950 and started the
Korean War.
   The prime minister said the government agreed free discussion of
reunification was necessary, even though authorities limited the
issue in the past.
   Students elected 13 representatives at a meeting today at Yonsei
University in Seoul to take part in the proposed talks with North
Korean students. Some students yelled ``Yankee go home'' and
``Unite the fatherland.''
   Four student leaders then went to the U.S. Army headquarters to
demand they be allowed to go to the border next week. The Panmunjom
truce site is under U.S. military control.
   The four were seized by police as soon as they arrived at the
U.S. base. A U.S. officer briefly met with one of the leaders
before they were taken away by police as they yelled anti-U.S.
slogans.
   Police repeated warnings today that students would not be
allowed to march to the border and said anyone doing so would be
arrested. The heavily militarized border 30 miles north of Seoul is
off limits to civilians.
   Radical students have been pushing for reunification with the
north, claiming that the United States enforces the division so it
can rule the south as a colony. The students demand expulsion of
42,000 U.S. troops based in the south under a defense treaty.
</TEXT>
