<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FoiledRobbery     06-04 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Foiled Robbery,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bank Robber Dies Of Injuries In Shootout After Wild Chase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bank robber's getaway was foiled by a car
wreck, a former policeman who shot him twice and a witness who ran
him down with a station wagon, and the man died hours later, police
said.
   John Thomas Barthelemy, 28, died late Friday at St. Joseph's
Hospital of wounds to the side of the neck and the abdomen. Alleged
accomplice Dianna Sue Cardiff, who is pregnant, was in stable
condition at Tampa General Hospital.
   Police said both were shot by Dr. Robert Dinsmore, a
chiropractor and former Tampa policeman, who saw the mid-afternoon
holdup at a Southeast Bank branch and pursued the robbers in his
car.
   A mile from the bank, at an intersection in a subdivision, the
suspects ran a stop sign and their car collided with two others.
   Dinsmore stopped his car and got out holding a gun. Barthelemy
was wielding a gun when he and Ms. Cardiff jumped out of the
getaway car, and a shootout began at close range, police said.
   A fourth person, whose car had collided with the robbers' sports
car, also pulled out a gun and fired one shot, but he wasn't hurt.
The driver of the other car involved in the wreck ``stayed in his
car and stayed out of the way,'' Lt. Jesse James said.
   ``Bullets were flying everywhere,'' James said. He said Dinsmore
and Barthelemy each fired several shots.
   Dinsmore was shot once in the shoulder and hospitalized in
stable condition. Lt. T.A. Ressler said it's doubtful he will be
charged.
   ``He apparently was acting within the law at the time to
apprehend a felon violator,'' Ressler said.
   Ms. Cardiff, 21, who lived with Barthelemy in Tampa, was charged
with attempted first-degree murder and armed robbery with a
firearm. Police said Barthelemy robbed the bank at gunpoint and
took a bag full of money, while Ms. Cardiff drove the getaway car.
   After the shootout, Barthelemy and Ms. Cardiff ran down the
street, and a witness pursued in a station wagon. Barthelemy
pointed his gun at the witness, who reacted by hitting the suspect
with the car. Barthelemy then dropped his gun and the money.
   Police found the robbers a short time later hiding behind bushes
about 60 yards from the site of the shootout. They were captured
without further incident and taken to separate hospitals.
   The bank's money was recovered, but Sgt. R.J. Reynolds said
police hadn't determined the total.
</TEXT>
