<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 0707EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-StrangeBequest     06-04 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Strange Bequest,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Leaves $275,000 Estate To U.S. Treasury</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COOKEVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thurman Z. Luke wore denim overalls and
lived in what some considered a modest house, but when the
75-year-old died he left a $275,000 estate to the U.S. Treasury.
   Luke, who died at his Baxter home in east Tennessee last March,
directed in his will that all his property be sold and the proceeds
be given to the Treasury to help pay off the national debt.
   The property included four money-market certificates in
Cookeville banks worth $215,000, a checking account with an $18,299
balance and a home worth $25,000.
   Also included in the will dated December 1983 were various
household furnishings.
   The document was filed in Cookeville's Probate Court and
attorney Don Dickerson was appointed as executor. Luke's two living
brothers and sisters signed waivers declining administration of the
will.
   ``I have never been married, and so I have no natural object of
affection to whom to pass my estate,'' Luke said in the will.
   Luke grew up in Appalachia and like many farm boys traveled to
Michigan in the 1940s, when the auto industry thrived. He served in
World War II and saved his Army paychecks, accumulating $17,000 by
the time he left the military.
   He pre-arranged his burial, and requested that no public
announcement be made at the time of his death.
   His only other request was that his rank in the military _
corporal _ be included on his tombstone.
   Friends said he frequently talked about the problems of the
government and liked to discuss politics.
   ``I would call him one of those natural-born `agitators' _ a
person that just delighted in arguing some issue,'' said his first
cousin, Billy Luke of Cookeville.
   ``You know, he just liked to take the other side, to argue. He
was sharp and very well read, especially on politics and history,
and he did worry about the government being in debt,'' he said.
</TEXT>
