<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Two Rocket Makers To Propose Private Sites To Build New Shuttle
Boosters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two rocket manufacturing companies are vying
to build the next generation of the space shuttle booster rocket.
   Morton Thiokol Inc. of Brigham City, Utah, which builds all the
current shuttle boosters, has told NASA it wants its Promontory
Point, Utah, site to be considered for the improved rockets.
   Hercules Inc. of Magna, Utah, together with Atlantic Research
Corp. of Gainesville, Va., have proposed a site eight miles west of
Montgomery, Ala.
   The successful firm could get a $1.2 billion plant and an
employment contract that could last into the next decade since the
advanced rockets are expected to arrive in the mid-1990s and
replace the current boosters completely in 1997.
