<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>House Earmarks $1.6 Billion for Super Collider</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House moved one step closer to funding for
the superconducting super collider, voting overwhelmingly to
approve a Department of Energy spending blueprint that includes
$1.6 billion for the project.
   The super collider, a massive high-energy physics project which
advocates say could lead to breakthroughs in understanding basic
matter, would be authorized $147 million in fiscal 1989 and $675
million and $774 million the following two years.
   There is no guarantee that the money would flow to developing
the superconductor following Friday's vote since actual spending is
controlled by separate appropriations legislation.
   The bill sent to the Senate on Friday by a 290-27 vote would
authorize continued spending on a wide variety of research and
development by the Department of Energy, including clean-coal
technology and alternative motor fuels.
</TEXT>
