<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru   06-04 0706</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0458,0728</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Calls For End To General Strike, Braces For More Unrest</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with second day of strike,
Palestinian woman shot in clash. Pickup 7th graf pvs, `The
civilians ...' EDITS to TRIM</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arabs in the occupied territories ignored
appeals by the Israeli army and kept shops shuttered today for the
second day of a strike called by the underground Palestinian
leadership.
   Israeli soldiers shot and wounded a 55-year-old Palestinian
woman in a clash today in the occupied Gaza Strip, an Arab reporter
said. She was shot in the hand in the Nusseirat refugee camp when a
melee broke out as soldiers went to a school, said the reporter,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   He said soldiers severely beat a 15-year-old boy in the clash.
   A military spokesman said he was unaware of any disturbances in
Gaza or the West Bank. Israel army radio said the Nusseirat camp
and Bureij refugee camp, also in Gaza, were put under curfew.
   Stores were closed and buses and most cars stayed off the
streets in the territories. In Gaza City, at least 15 burning tires
were blocking main roads and troops fired tear gas to clear away
protesters, the Arab reporter.
   Leaders of the 6-month-old Arab uprising called the strike to
protest the visit of U.S. Secretary of State George Shultz to the
region to promote a peace initiative.
   Shultz arrived Friday in Cairo and was traveling to Jordan and
Syria today and Israel on Sunday.
   Major General Yitzhak Mordechai, who commands the Gaza area,
appealed to residents to maintain calm during today's anniversary
of Israel's invasion of Lebanon, promising aid and relief to those
who complied.
   On Friday, soldiers and unidentified civilians shot two
Palestinians to death and wounded at least five other West Bank
Arabs.
   Since the beginning of the uprising Dec. 8, 201 Palestinians and
two Israelis have died.
   An Israeli army officer shot and killed a 26-year-old Arab
Friday in Tzafa village near Ramallah, north of Jerusalem, after
unidentified Israeli civilians killed a 20-year-old man in Shuyukh
village near Hebron.
   The civilians also wounded three others in the incident,
hospital officials in Hebron and police said.
   ``Just before nightfall, a military patrol in the village was
surrounded and showered with rocks,'' an army spokesman said. ``An
officer shot first in the air, but when he was in danger for his
life, he shot at the people's legs, and the 26-year-old was
killed.''
   Israeli radio identified the dead man as Muhamad Ranen.
   In a separate incident Friday, troops shot and wounded two Arab
youths after they blocked roads with rocks and threw stones at an
army patrol in the market area of the West Bank city of Nablus.
   The army maintained curfews and movement restrictions on about
200,000 residents of the territories in order to squelch unrest.
   Police said they suspected a group of four Jewish youths may
have been involved in the killing of the Shuyukh man, identified as
Mustafa Ahmed Halaika.
   An army spokesman said no soldiers were in the area when the
shooting took place.
   As Shultz launched the fourth round of his peace mission, Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir reiterated his staunch opposition to the
American plan to promote an international Middle East peace
conference.
   Shamir insists on direct bilateral talks between Israel and its
Arab neighbors.
   His political rival, Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, said he was
optimistic about an international conference because of what he
said were encouraging changes in Soviet attitudes.
   A poll published Friday in the Hebrew daily Hadashot newspaper
indicates Peres' left-of-center Labor party has gained in
popularity in recent months and could win 53 parliament seats in
the November elections, up from 50 in March.
   Maj. Gen. Mordechai used the platform of Israeli television's
Arabic service to appeal to Gaza Strip residents to ignore today's
anniversary as well as the Sunday anniversary of the 1967 Six Day
War, when Israel captured the land.
   He promised to lift curfews and release prisoners if residents
returned to ``life, work, trade and school.''
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said he would release 120
teen-age boys from prison Sunday as a gesture of goodwill.
</TEXT>
