<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CrackHouses     06-04 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crack Houses,0478</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Miami Begins Razing Drug-Addict Havens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD W. SWINTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Miami has adopted Tampa's plan to systematically
demolish abandoned houses believed to harbor drug addicts and thugs.
   Heavy bulldozers razed two abandoned houses Friday to initiate
the ``crack attack'' designed to wipe out drug dens in declining
neighborhoods.
   ``This is the kind of full-force effort we need in our city to
get rid of the crack problem,'' said Vice Mayor Rosario Kennedy.
   Ms. Kennedy, with Tampa Mayor Sandy Freedman at her side, went
to the dilapidated Overtown section of Miami to announce the plan.
Ms. Freedman began the policy last week when she coaxed private
demolition companies to voluntarily level 50 vacant houses in three
days.
   On Friday, Ms. Kennedy urged other cities to adopt the ``crack
attack'' policy and raze unsafe abandoned structures that create a
haven for drugs and crime. She said Miami had more than 100 such
unsafe structures she would like to see demolished, but first they
have to go through routine condemnation procedures.
   Hector Lima, chief of the Code Enforcement Department, said
Miami has 238 buildings that are being condemned.
   The Miami demolition policy follows a rash of crack-house
burnings in March believed to be the work of anti-drug vigilantes.
Miami fire investigators instituted round-the-clock patrols of
suspected crack houses looking for one or more arsonists, but no
one was arrested.
   After advocating a public-private partnership in the demolition
program, the women climbed up onto a frontend-loader and, with the
guidance of operator Gerardo de Aza, crashed into one of the houses
set for demolition.
   ``The (crack addicts) are just going to go some place and do the
same thing,'' said 22-year-old neighbor Ruben Santiago as he
watched the media swarm around.
   ``It's not useless. They can build something new there. But
(demolition) is not going to stop (the drug dealing). There will
always be crack houses,'' he said.
   While city officials were not sure if the abandoned single-story
wood-frame house had ever been the site of any arrests, Santiago
said there had been several arrests there.
   In his 15 years in the neighborhood, Santiago said, the
structure had been converted from a single-family home to a rooming
house. He said two years ago residents of the area had set the
rooming house on fire to get rid of the crack addicts who lived
there. It had been a shell ever since.
   Angela M. Jordan said she had seen many drug buys on the corner
where the house sat during her four months in the neighborhood.
   ``That will sure get them off the corner,'' she said as the
house shook and piece fell in. ``But if they don't sell drugs
there, they'll go some place else. They'll find someplace to sell
it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
