<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Shultz 3rdLd-Writethru a0527 06-04 0806</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0527,0826</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Sees Mubarak, Hussein To Start New Peace Mission</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with Shultz meeting king. PICKS
UP 10th graf pvs, `Earlier, Shultz...' EDITS to trim.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz
discussed his Middle East peace plans with the leaders of Egypt and
Jordan today and called for a settlement based on Palestinian
rights as well as Israeli security.
   ``This is not a matter of winner-take-all, in which one side can
win everything it wants,'' he said in a prepared statement on
arrival in Jordan from Egypt.
   ``Palestinians and Israelis must learn to treat each other
decently, respect their mutual right to live in security and
fulfill their political aspirations,'' Shultz said.
   Foreign Minister Taher Masri met Shultz at Amman's military
airport and escorted him to the royal palace where he had talks
over lunch with King Hussein.
   In his arrival statement, Shultz said ``Jordan has a crucial
role to play'' in Arab peace with its western neighbor, Israel.
   Shultz has stressed that Israelis and Palestinians both have
legitimate claims to the land held by Israel, and said there is
room for them to live together. He listed as his first goal
Israel's exchange of land for Arab recognition.
   Second on his list in the arrival statement was a call for an
``equitable settlement of the land issue,'' although he said it was
up to the participants to decide how much territory Israel should
give up.
   Before leaving Cairo, Shultz met with Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak in private for about an hour, then for another hour with
aides.
   ``We're off to a good start, I think,'' Shultz said following
the talks.
   Shultz was due to fly back to Cairo tonight.
   In earlier remarks to reporters traveling with him, the
secretary conceded that he is shuttling again between Arabs and
Israelis with no indication they are willing to accept his plan for
negotiations.
   The trip marks his fourth effort this year to provide
Palestinian Arabs self-rule _ but not statehood _ as the first step
toward setting up talks on an overall Middle East settlement.
   ``You have to be willing to work against the odds, to swim
against the current, in the hope (that) by keeping at it eventually
you get some way, if you can,'' Shultz told reporters on his flight
to Cairo from London.
   As he arrived Friday night, he read a five-page statement
exhorting Arabs and Israelis ``to lay aside prejudices, hatred and
overblown dreams in favor of a negotiated settlement.''
   His message seemed aimed at Israel's Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir, who resists ending Israel's occupation of West Bank land in
exchange for peace, and at Arab extremists seeking to overthrow the
Jewish state.
   ``Too often, people become convinced that only their dream or
their causes are legitimate,'' Shultz said. ``They deny the rights
of others. They avoid the realism on the ground.''
   In deference to Mubarak, who has endorsed the U.S. plan in
principle, Shultz made Cairo his base, with today's flight to
Jordan and hops Sunday to Israel and Monday to Syria.
   The trip was slotted in between the Moscow superpower summit
meeting in Moscow and an Arab summit opening Tuesday in Algeria.
   The Kremlin has backed Arab demands for a peace conference in
which the big powers, including the Soviet Union, could influence a
settlement. Shamir and Shultz want the conference to be no more
than an umbrella for direct negotiations between Arabs and Israelis.
   Shultz suggested the Soviets may be inching away from their
position. ``They have started to use the word `effective' rather
than `authoritative,' and they've made a point of saying that
wasn't a loose slip of the tongue,'' he said.
   According to reports in Israel and the Persian Gulf, Shultz is
thinking of revising his negotiation plan to provide for Egyptian
participation in deciding the future of the Israeli-held Gaza Strip.
   The reports have Egyptians joining Palestinians in a delegation
dealing with Gaza, while Jordan and another Palestinian group would
negotiate with Israel over the West Bank.
   Egypt administered Gaza and Jordan controlled the West Bank
until Israel took both territories in the 1967 Six-Day War.
   Yasser Arafat, chairman of the Palestine Liberation
Organization, said in an interview Friday with Radio Monte Carlo:
``There cannot be a solution if the Palestinian question is
ignored. As long as Shultz wants to omit this basic point in the
Middle East, his initative will not work. If he has anything new to
say, let him go ahead.''
   The Shultz plan does not call for a Palestinian state. It would
give the 1.5 million Palestinian Arabs on the West Bank and in Gaza
some control over their daily affairs, with the territories' final
status left for future negotiations.
</TEXT>
