<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Punjab     06-04 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Punjab,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Journalist Shot To Death in Punjab</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh extremists today shot and killed a
Sikh freelance reporter in the northern state of Punjab in the 10th
Sikh assassination of a journalist in the past eight years.
   The Press Trust of India said Parduman Singh, 55, was shot
outside a school he runs in Hoshiarpur, 75 miles northwest of the
state capital at Chandigarh.
   PTI said shopkeepers and businessmen closed their stores to
protest the slaying.
   Singh was a stringer for PTI, the English-language Indian
Express newspaper and several Punjab-based papers.
   Sikh extremists have been waging a guerrilla war since 1982 in
Punjab for an independent homeland. Sikhs make up less than 2
percent of India's 800 million people but are a majority in Punjab.
   The Sikhs, whose religion was founded about 500 years ago as an
alternative to Hinduism and Islam, say they are discriminated
against by India's majority Hindus.
   Singh was the second Sikh journalist slain in Hoshiarpur in the
past month. On May 4, a Punjabi newspaper editor, Bant Singh, was
shot to death by Sikh radicals.
   The first journalist felled by Sikh assassins was Lala Jagat
Narian, editor of the Hind Samachar group of newspapers. He was
killed on Sept. 9, 1981. His son and successor, Ramesh Chander, was
shot to death in 1984.
   Police today recovered another decomposed body from the Golden
Temple complex at Amritsar. It was the 22nd corpse found inside
Sihkdom's holiest shrine since police ended a 10-day siege of the
complex on May 18.
   Some of the 200 Sikh extremists and sympathizers who surrendered
during the siege confessed that nearly 40 people were tortured and
killed by Sikh radicals and their bodies buried inside the complex.
Some were people who had gone to the shrine to pray.
   The extremists also have been blamed for the deaths of more than
1,250 people in hit-and-run attacks around the state this year.
Most of the victims have been Hindus or moderate Sikhs opposed to
the separatist campaign.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
