<HEAD>Militiaman Killed In North Ireland</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with IRA claiming responsibility.
No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An off-duty militiaman was shot
to death outside his home in Northern Ireland today, the eighth
member of the Ulster Defense Regiment to be killed this year,
police said.
   The outlawed Irish Republican Army claimed responsibility.
   Lance Cpl. Michael Darcy, 28, a bachelor living with his widowed
mother, was killed as he parked his car outside his home in
Castlederg.
   ``He had no time to fire back. A man was seen running from the
scene and we assume it was a terrorist crime,'' a Belfast police
spokesman said.
   The town is close to the Irish Republic border and 65 miles west
of Belfast.
   The killing brought the known death toll in the province to
2,648 by police count since 1969, when the IRA launched its violent
campaign to end British rule and unite the predominantly Protestant
province with the mainly Roman Catholic Irish Republic.
