<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FrommeTransfer     06-04 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fromme Transfer,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Manson Follower Moved from West Virginia to Kentucky Prison</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN L. HERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lynette ``Squeaky'' Fromme, serving a
life term for attempting to kill then-President Gerald R. Ford in
1975, has been transferred from a federal prison in West Virginia
to the Lexington Federal Correctional Institution in Kentucky,
officials said today.
   Fromme, who was sentenced May 25 to an additional 15 months in
prison for escaping from the all-female Alderson Federal
Correctional Institution in West Virginia, was moved Friday to the
Lexington prison, said Alderson Warden Ron Burkhart.
   ``It's basically a level 1 security installation but within that
institution we operate a high security unit,'' Burkhart said.
``She'll be housed in the high security unit.'' Lexington is
basically a minimum security institution, while Alderson is medium
security. But Alderson had no facility for housing dangerous
inmates or those considered escape risks.
   During her sentencing on the escape charge, Fromme told U.S.
District Court Judge Elizabeth V. Hallanan in Beckley that she
couldn't promise that she would not try to escape again.
   Fromme had said she escaped from Alderson on Dec. 23, 1987, in
order to be closer to convicted mass cult killer Charles Manson,
who is serving a life term in San Quentin in California.
   Fromme said in a telephone interview in early May she had hoped
to be moved to a federal prison in California to have better
contact with Manson.
   ``I've been working on getting him back to court,'' she said.
   Fromme, 39, spent two days wandering in the Appalachian
mountains around the prison before she was recaptured, rain-soaked,
on Christmas Day.
   Fromme was the first person sentenced under a special federal
law covering assaults on presidents, a statute enacted after the
1963 assasination of President John F. Kennedy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
