<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SoCalQuake     06-04 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SoCal Quake,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quake Rocks Riverside-San Bernardino Area</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REDLANDS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of Riverside and San
Bernardino counties were rattled by an earthquake that was widely
felt but caused no injuries or damage, authorities reported.
   The quake, measuring 3.8 on the Richter scale, struck at 5:32
p.m. Friday, said Hall Daily, a spokesman for the California
Institute of Technology in Pasadena.
   It was centered six miles east of Redlands, near the boundary
dividing the two counties and about 70 miles east of Los Angeles,
Daily said.
   ``It was strongly felt in Riverside,'' said Kathy Watts, a
scientist at the Pasadena lab.
   Callers from San Bernardino and from Idyllwild, in the San
Jacinto Mountains, also reported feeling the jolt.
   But Riverside police received no reports of injuries or damage,
Sgt. Joanne Flores said.
   ``It wasn't that hard of an earthquake,'' said Lee Hester, a
police dispatcher in Hemet, about 20 miles southeast of the
epicenter. He said no damage was reported there.
   The Richter scale is an indirect gauge of the energy released by
an earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph. For small quakes, every increase of one number means a
tenfold increase in magnitude.
   An earthquake of 3.5 to 4 on the Richter scale can cause slight
damage in the local area in places such as Southern California
where building codes are strict.
</TEXT>
