<HEAD>IRA Claims Responsibility For Weekend Shooting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The outlawed Irish Republican
Army claimed responsibility Saturday for the fatal shooting of an
off-duty member of the Ulster Defense Regiment security force.
   Lance Cpl. Michael Darcy, 28, was shot early Saturday while
parking his car outside the home he shared with his widowed mother
in Castlederg, 65 miles west of Belfast.
   ``He had no time to fire back,'' a Belfast police spokesman
said. ``A man was seen running from the scene, and we assume it was
a terrorist crime.''
   The IRA is fighting to oust the British from Northern Ireland
and unite the predominantly Protestant province with the mainly
Roman Catholic Irish Republic. It made its claim in a statement to
the news media.
   The British-trained Ulster Defense Regiment is a mainly
Protestant security force.

