<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia-Protest     06-04 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia-Protest,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cotton Mill Workers Stage Protest March</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSTAR, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 150 workers of the country's
largest cotton mill marched through this central city Saturday to
protest wage cuts, the state Tanjug news agency reported.
   The demonstrators from the Djuro Salaj mill met at the town hall
with city and factory officials and protested a salary slash of
14.2 percent planned this month, the report said. Wages were also
cut in May, after the government launched major austerity measures.
   The program included substantial price hikes, wage cuts of up to
30 percent and a 23.9 percent devaluation of the dinar, the
national currency. It is designed to curb the country's 170 percent
inflation rate and help repay a $21 billion foreign debt.
   The average monthly pay at the mill has been a little less than
$125 a month.
   The protest came after a three-day strike at the factory
involving about 2,000 workers.
   The influential Belgrade daily Politika said Saturday that after
the austerity measures were announced, some companies raised prices
100 percent or more. It said most price increases were 30 percent
to 95 percent.
   The government has appealed to manufacturers to show restraint
in raising prices, the state-run media reported.
   After a meeting on Friday, the government called on ``all
organizations ... which hiked their prices over and above plans to
obligatorily reexamine and change their decisions.''
