<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 1122EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSDoctor     06-04 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Doctor,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctor Who Fought to Keep Hospital Privileges Dies of AIDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cook County Hospital doctor who won a court
battle to keep his job even though he suffered from AIDS has died,
officials said.
   Dr. Alan Bouffard, 42, a neurologist, headed the neurology clinic
and electroencephalographic laboratory at the hospital, officials
said. His name was not released during the court proceedings that
led to a consent decree allowing him to keep full medical privileges
over the initial objections of the Cook County Board.
   He died of AIDS complications May 25, and in accordance with his
wishes, no services were scheduled, the Chicago Tribune reported
Saturday.
   ``He never wavered, not for a moment, in his commitment to pursue
full remedy and reinstatement consistent with good medical
practice,'' said Harvey Grossman, his lawyer and legal director of
the Illinois chapter of the American Civil Liberties Union.
   ``He understood on many levels what the issues were for
(AIDS-)infected people like himself,'' Grossman said. ``As a doctor,
he knew both the facts of transmission and the implications of not
continuing to participate in society.''
   In February 1987, the Cook County Board voted to deny Bouffard
medical privileges at the county hospital out of fear he might
contaminate patients. The hospital's executive medical staff voted
to reinstate him, and the case went to court.
   On Feb. 24, 1988, a consent decree issued by a federal court in
Chicago restored all his medical privileges, while requiring him to
wear double gloves for certain procedures.
   His efforts were on behalf of the rights of all people who have
the AIDS-causing virus to continue as productive members of society,
Grossman said.
   ``He was a very courageous man,'' the lawyer added.
   Bouffard received the 1988 Civil Liberties Award of the ACLU of
Illinois in a private ceremony several weeks ago.
   AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, destroys the body's
defenses against disease, leaving a person prey to life-threatening
infections and certain cancers.
   The virus that causes the incurable and fatal syndrome is
believed to be passed mainly through sexual intercourse, shared
hypodermic needles and from infected mothers to their infants before
or during birth.
   A co-worker, Dr. James Stone, described Bouffard as a free
thinker who kept his private life to himself.
   ``He worked hard and came in early,'' Stone said. ``He was Cook
County's expert on brain wave analysis and nerve-muscle diseases.''
</TEXT>
