<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 1132EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-YouthViolence Bjt   06-04 0691</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Youth Violence, Bjt,0712</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pistol-Packing Kids Terrorize Some Neighborhoods</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three suspects arrested for selling drugs in an
apartment building were each carrying crack. Each was carrying a
loaded pistol.
   None was older than 15.
   ``They were hardnosed,'' police Inspector Philip Sheridan
recalled. ``They were actually berating us for arresting them.''
   Surrounded by the drug trade and the violence it breeds, some of
New York City's children tote guns as casually as others carry
school books or baseball gloves.
   In Brooklyn's Crown Heights, a poor neighborhood a half-hour
subway ride from midtown Manhattan, kids act ``like they have a
license to carry guns,'' said the Rev. Hardy Smallwood Jr., a
community leader.
   He said parents are increasingly afraid of their own children,
and the cause is clear. ``It's all crack, that's what it's all
about,'' he said. ``It's a never-ending battle.''
   Before the rise of crack, a potent, inexpensive form of cocaine,
``we never had this amount of violence,'' said Sheridan, who has
arrested boys as young as 12 in Crown Heights carrying .25-caliber
automatic pistols.
   The city's schools have been focal points of the new juvenile
violence. Following a recent rash of attacks on teachers, the
president of the city's teachers union demanded better schoolhouse
security.
   During the 1986-87 school year, 1,495 weapons _ ranging from
crossbows and martial arts weapons to zip guns and pistols _ were
taken from students.
   This year, the number of weapons taken from students is up about
10 percent _ 1,579 from the start of the school year to April 30 _
and in the last six months there have been at least a dozen
incidents in which students were injured by gunfire.
   The problem is forcing educators to suggest remedies that once
seemed extreme. Under sweeping new security procedures announced
Tuesday by Mayor Edward I. Koch and schools Chancellor Richard R.
Green, students who attack school workers would be expelled _
despite the state's compulsory education law.
   Metal detectors are going up at the doors of some schools, and
additional police patrols will guard the most crime-ridden schools.
   ``Putting in a metal detector alters the image of the school,''
said Bruce Irushalmi, director of the Board of Education's Office of
School Safety. But, he added, ``So do weapons.''
   Irushalmi and Ed Muir, head of the United Federation of Teachers'
safety committee, link the increase in weapons to an increase in
student drug trafficking.
   Children, largely immune to harsh court punishment, have been
used by drug gangs for years to steer customers, watch for the
police or work as couriers.
   In inner-city neighborhoods with few good jobs, teen-agers can
easily earn in a day or two what many adults make in a week.
   ``The amount of money made in these lower-level organizations is
just incredible,'' said Robert Strang, a spokesman for the federal
Drug Enforcement Administration's New York office.
   For example, an $11,000 kilogram of cocaine can be processed into
$250,000 worth of crack, said William Hopkins, supervisor of the
Street Research Unit of the state Division of Substance Abuse
Services.
   Police say drug rings increasingly are hiring children, mostly
boys in their early teens, to market their wares.
   To guard their investment, dealers pass out pistols _ frequently
small, inexpensive .25-caliber automatics called ``pea shooters'' by
drug dealers whose own weapon of choice is the powerful 9mm
automatic.
   ``If a kid is hired to sell crack off the corner ... he might get
ripped off,'' said Sheridan. ``It's a lot cheaper to give a kid a
gun than to lose your drugs.''
   ``With 35 vials of crack selling for $8 to $10, you're putting
$350 worth of drugs in the hands of a 13-year-old, and he's very
vulnerable,'' he said. ``So the dealers will give them a gun to
protect their interests.''
   Sheridan tries to make sense of what he sees each day on ghetto
streets.
   ``There's a great frustration with our young people today,'' he
said. ``The lifestyles that are presented to them _ the guy with the
gold chain, the guys with the BMWs _ these are the people they
emulate.''
</TEXT>
