<1ST_LINE>u p AM-StatePrimariesRdp Bjt   06-04 0772</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-State Primaries Rdp, Bjt,0784</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seven States Vote In Year's Biggest State Primary Day So Far</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE SILVERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Skirmishes over four U.S. Senate seats, a wide-open race for
Montana governor and a California potpourri of propositions
highlight the ballots in seven states Tuesday, the busiest state
primary day so far in 1988.
   In Newark, N.J., two black Democrats are competing for their
party's nomination to the congressional seat being vacated by Peter
Rodino after 40 years. In San Diego, Mayor Maureen O'Connor is
overwhelmingly favored to win election in a nonpartisan race to a
full four-year term.
   The California propositions include statewide measures that would
permit the quarantining of AIDS victims, ease the government
spending limits imposed by Proposition 13 a decade ago, and cap
runaway spending on political campaigns.
   In local measures of note, Sacramento voters could become the
first in the nation to close a nuclear power plant, the troubled
Rancho Seco facility; and voters in San Bernardino County _ the
nation's largest county _ will decide whether to carve away the
eastern, desert portion to create a new county called Mojave.
   The most hotly contested Senate primary is in New Mexico, where
four Republicans think first-term Democratic Sen. Jeff Bingaman is
vulnerable because of his liberal voting record in a state that
strongly supports defense spending. State Sen. Bill Valentine and
longtime party activist Corky Morris have held the lead in polls for
the GOP nomination. Bingaman is unopposed in the Democratic primary.
   The only other first-term Democrat seeking re-election this year,
Sen. Frank Lautenberg of New Jersey, faces a challenge from two
little-known primary opponents. He is gearing up for his November
clash with the unopposed GOP nominee, Peter Dawkins, a Heisman
Trophy winner, Rhodes scholar and Vietnam War hero who resigned from
the Shearson-Lehman brokerage house in New York City last year and
moved to New Jersey.
   The national GOP has targeted both Bingaman and Lautenberg, and
both states have Republican governors who will campaign for the
party's nominee.
   In California, Republican Sen. Pete Wilson has no primary hurdle
as he seeks a second term, but he will have to overcome a jinx in
November _ for more than 30 years, no one has been re-elected to
that particular Senate seat. On the Democratic side, Lt. Gov. Leo
McCarthy faces two political unknowns.
   The fourth Senate race is in Montana, where Democrat John Melcher
is seeking the nomination for a third term. His only primary
challenger is attorney Robert Kelleher, who advocates a
parliamentary form of government. The unopposed GOP candidate is
Conrad Burns, a Yellowstone County commissioner and former
broadcaster.
   Montana also features a lively race for governor, a post held by
Democrats for 20 years. Two-term Gov. Ted Schwinden's decision not
to run for a third term gave Republicans hope of recapturing the
office, but their leading candidate, Secretary of State Jim
Waltermire, was killed in an April plane crash. The remaining GOP
contenders are former state Sen. Stan Stephens and state Rep. Cal
Winslow.
   The six-man Democratic field includes a comeback bid by former
Gov. Thomas Judge, who lost to Schwinden in the 1980 primary. The
two other leading candidates are Attorney General Mike Greely, who
has a drunken driving conviction on his record, and former state
Supreme Court Justice Frank Morrison Jr.
   Here is a look at the other states voting Tuesday:
   ALABAMA _ Democratic Reps. Claude Harris of Tuscaloosa and Bill
Nichols of Sylacauga are favored to turn back primary challenges.
   Races for three Alabama Supreme Court seats have turned into
unusually rough-and-tumble scraps in which big business and
insurance companies are backing one slate of Democratic candidates,
while trial lawyers and less conservative interests are backing
another slate. One of the candidates with trial lawyer support is
Circuit Judge Mark Kennedy of Montgomery, a son-in-law of former
Gov. George C. Wallace. He is running against Anniston lawyer A.W.
Bolt, who is supported by business lobbies, for an associate justice
post.
   IOWA _ Sixteen supporters of political extremist Lyndon LaRouche
are running in Democratic primaries, five for congressional
nominations and the rest in state legislative districts. Four
Democrats are seeking the nomination to oppose first-term GOP Rep.
Fred Grandy, who for years played Gopher on television's ``The Love
Boat.''
   SOUTH DAKOTA _ The state is having one of its quietest elections
in memory, with no statewide races on the ballot. And there are only
26 primary races for the 105 state Senate and House seats. The
state's lone congressman, Democratic Rep. Tim Johnson, is unopposed
in the primary as is his Republican challenger, state Treasurer
David Volk.
</TEXT>
