<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Dog'sBattle     06-04 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dog's Battle,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Dog's Eye Surgery So Successful He May Return to Force</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police dog with eye cancer whose supporters
raised $5,000 when the city refused to pay for his surgery has come
through the operation so well, he may be able to return to active
duty, police said.
   Zeus, a 7-year-old German shepherd, returned home Friday with his
handler, Officer Mike Kendig, one day after undergoing surgery to
remove the cancerous eye at a Sacramento, Calif., animal hospital.
   He has been fitted with a temporary prosthesis and will go back
to Sacramento next month to be fitted with a permanent one, said
Sgt. Greg Dion, a police spokesman.
   Meanwhile, Zeus will return to training in about three weeks to
determine whether his other senses will compensate enough for the
loss of the eye to let him return to full-time police work, Dion
said.
   Zeus became a celebrity when it was reported the city would not
pay for the operation because he was taking early retirement. That
spurred a fund-raising effort that netted more than $1,000 in a few
hours and has reached nearly $5,000, according to police Capt. Jim
Weston.
   The city has since announced it will foot the entire $1,400 cost
of Zeus' operation and the prosthesis. The donations will be
refunded if people ask for their money back; the rest will be put in
a city fund earmarked for police dogs.
</TEXT>
