<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--Reagan-Trade     06-04 0173</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Reagan-Trade,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Renews Favorable Trade Status for China, Hungary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan on Saturday renewed a grant of
favorable trade status to China and Hungary but allowed similar
status for Romania to lapse.
   The president's action continues in effect for 12 months a waiver
granted to the Chinese and Hungarian governments under legislation
passed in 1974. The legislation conditions ``most favored nation''
status on satisfactory immigration policies.
   Reagan said that he was permitting the waiver for Romania to
expire because Romania has renounced extension of the so-called
``most favored nation'' tariff treatment under the act.
   He said that the waivers have made it possible to maintain
bilateral trade agreements with the three countries and give U.S.
companies the ability to compete in those countries' markets.
   Hungary ``has continued to take a relatively positive and
constructive approach to emigration matters,'' the president said,
and China has a ``relatively liberal policy on emigration ....
reflected in the steadily rising number of immigrant visas issued by
our embassy and consulates in China.''
</TEXT>
