<DOCNO> AP880604-0104 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 1214EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis-ImmigrantSon Bjt   06-04 0880</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Immigrant Son, Bjt,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Strike A Chord With Immigrant Son Image</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The story of Panos Dukakis and Euterpe Boukis
is a classic tale of immigrants, a saga of poor Greeks who landed in
America with nothing and achieved through sheer effort a piece of
the dream.
   Michael Dukakis has carefully cultivated his image as an
immigrant son during his Democratic presidential campaign, an ethnic
portrayal rarely seen in his earlier days in public life.
   ``Seventy-five years ago, a young Greek man arrived in Manchester
from a town in western Asia Minor. He spoke very little English and
had about $25 in his pocket,'' Dukakis recalls on the stump.
   Panos, his father, worked in the mills and put himself through
college. He went on to Harvard Medical School, a rare educational
leap for an immigrant, and became a wealthy obstetrician. Euterpe,
his mother, arrived here at the age of 9, toiled in the textile
factories and became the first girl in her hometown to go to college.
   Dukakis is rightfully proud of his family, telling the story with
equal parts love, pride and political acumen. It is a tale certain
to strike a chord with melting-pot Americans.
   But critics say the governor never mentioned his ethnic roots
during the pre-presidential years and turned to them now only as a
campaign tactic to attract ethnic voters as well as build a huge
fund-raising base from the Greek community.
   ``I don't remember him ever mentioning it ... and I was listening
pretty carefully,'' said former Massachusetts Gov. Francis Sargent,
a liberal Republican who lost the 1974 election to Dukakis. ``I knew
he was a Greek, but he didn't trumpet it.''
   ``Although I think he was always aware and proud of his Greek
heritage, it was not something that has ever been intimately
connected with his politics,'' said Martin Linsky of Harvard's John
F. Kennedy School of Government.
   To many Massachusetts voters, Dukakis was associated not with
first- and second-generation Americans, but with Harvard academics
and white-collar suburban liberals. He grew up in financial comfort,
graduated from Harvard Law School, and made his name in politics in
the 1960s as a leader of young politicians out to reform the state
Democratic Party, which was run largely by pols with a strong ethnic
affiliation. And his political base was Brookline, a predominately
Jewish upper-middle-class Boston suburb.
   Paul Brountas, long-time friend, fellow Greek and campaign
chairman, says Dukakis' ethnic emphasis helped identify him to a
national audience that knew little of the Massachusetts governor,
and helped him stand apart in the crowded Democratic field in the
early weeks of the campaign.
   ``When you're running nationally and when people don't know who
you are, you have to identify yourself, your values, your
background, before you get into issues,'' said Brountas. ``That's
not necessary to run for governor. He was very well known when he
ran for governor.''
   Brountas said the governor's 1976 trip to his parents' homeland
was a turning point, triggering deep feelings of ethnic pride.
   ``It made an impact on him. I remember one night (in Greece) we
were at a semi-formal government dinner with several dignitaries,''
Brountas recalled. ``He was asked to say a few words. He was quite
poignant, emotional. It was the first time I'd seen him talk about
his heritage that way.''
   Long-time Dukakis observers say hints of the immigrant son began
emerging publicly during his 1978 campaign, which he lost to Edward
King, and became more visible in 1982 as he successfully fought to
win back the governorship.
   A 1982 television advertisement _ which came to be known as the
``Zorba the Greek'' ad _ featured Dukakis standing in front of a
house his father lived in while saving money for school. With
traditional Greek music playing in the background, Dukakis spoke
about his father's life.
   ``What it did was give him a history,'' said Michael Goldman, a
Boston-based Democratic political consultant. Before that, Goldman
said, ``What did you know about Michael Dukakis? He was from
Brookline and he went to Harvard. ... The perception was he was sort
of a Yankee.''
   Dukakis' focus on his heritage never played such a central role
in his political life until his presidential bid.
   ``He's never had to reach down that deep before,'' said Linsky.
``It's an internal thing. It's never been necessary before. He's
never had to draw on his own roots as a personal and emotional
matter. He's always been able to achieve what he's achieved without
getting to that point. Running for president was a different
operation.''
   Dukakis' Greek ancestry helped him win votes on several fronts,
says Ralph Whitehead, a professor at the University of Massachusetts
at Amherst.
   ``It's helping him with ethnic voters, and I think it's regarded
by many voters in the Democratic Party, be them ethnic or otherwise,
as a sign that he's down to earth, even if he isn't necessarily
earthy,'' Whitehead said.
   And, Whitehead added, ``Dukakis' Greek identity gives him all the
advantages of the Ellis Island mystique and none of the
disadvantages'' that have shadowed some Italian-American politicians.
   ``In the eyes of the Democratic electorate, Dukakis has almost
the ideal form of ethnicity,'' said Whitehead. ``Dukakis has become
sort of generically ethnic.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
