<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BlueTV     06-04 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Blue TV,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nude Show Aired During Kids' Hour</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A city-owned television station accidentally
broadcast a video of a topless woman during a program for young
people intended to discourage teen-age pregnancy and drug abuse.
   ``They flubbed and they're very contrite,'' Mayor Edward I. Koch
said of the incident, which occurred about 4:20 p.m. Friday on WNYC.
``They don't allow this kind of nudity for adults. They would not
intentionally put this show on a children's hour.''
   ``They say a producer fell asleep at a switch,'' Koch said
Saturday. ``The producer is supposed to screen them.''
   The New York Post reported the incident in its Saturday editions.
   Koch said it wasn't known how the clip got into the pre-recorded
program, which was ``provided by the video industry.''
   ``There's no liability here. It's a mistake. We're not going to
hang anybody,'' said Koch. ``The producer who works for WNYC is
ultimately responsible.''
   Asked if the unidentified producer would be disciplined, Koch
replied, ``He'll be told, `Stop sleeping.'''
   The program, ``Video Music Box,'' reaches hundreds of thousands
of youngsters each weekday afternoon.
   WNYC gets 30 percent of its funds from the city and 70 percent
from the WNYC Foundation, a non-profit group partly appointed by the
city.
