<HEAD>Burma Says White Foreigners Training Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White foreigners are training Karen ethnic
insurgents fighting the central Burmese government, official Burmese
media said Saturday.
   A television program showed a photograph of a mustachioed
Caucasian training soldiers of the Karen National Union in the use
of a rocket launcher. He was identified only as an ``unnamed
foreigner.''
   The photograph was among documents seized from the rebel group
after a clash with government troops May 30 in eastern Burma, the
television report said.
   A few foreign mercenaries, including some from France and
Australia, are known to have provided training to the Karens, one of
several ethnic minority groups fighting for greater independence
from the central government.
   The report said documents seized showed some foreigners had given
weapons training to the rebels at Manapler, Mela and Wanghka, three
major Karen strongholds.
   The documents were seized after a Karen rocket attack on Pa-an,
the capital of Karen State. Two people were killed and 11 others
wounded, according to government accounts.
