<DOCNO> AP880604-0126 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 1401EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Gala     06-04 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Gala,0467</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Westerners Dance and Smash Instruments In China's Great Hall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Western performers smashed violins and pranced in
black leotards Saturday on the stage of Beijing's Great Hall of the
People, where Mao Tse-tung once warned of Western decadence.
   The gala performance in the hall, used for sessions of China's
Communist Party and parliament, capped a long weekend of luxurious
pleasures for about 200 tourists from 21 countries.
   Their tour _ called ``the return of Marco Polo'' after the
travels to China of the 13th century explorer from Venice _ was
designed to raise funds for the restoration of the Italian lagoon
city and of China's Great Wall.
   The foreign guests were joined by about 7,000 Chinese for the
gala evening.
   The performers included French popular singer Mireille Mathieu,
Russian-born ballerina Maia Plissetskaia, Spanish soprano Monserrat
Caballe and Paris Opera Ballet dancers Sylvie Guillem and Manuel
Legris.
   Guillem and Legris danced to music by the 19th century French
composer Daniel Auber and then returned later in black leotards to
present a sensual modern piece.
   Chinese artists performing included tenor Liu Weiwei and the
choir and orchestra of the Central Opera Theater.
   The evening was broken up by the performance of French artist
Arman. He appeared dressed in a white workman's suit, smashed
several cellos and violins and created a large collage out of the
pieces while a Chinese string quartet played Beethoven's ``Great
Fugue.''
   The show was opened by Ying Ruocheng, vice-minister of culture
and the actor who played the prison warden in the Academy
Award-winning film ``The Last Emperor.''
   Members of the tour each paid $4,300 for the four-day excursion,
including a masked ball, chauffeur-driven black Chinese-built
limousines and boating at the Summer Palace _ the sumptuous retreat
built in the late 19th century by the Empress Dowager Cixi.
   The group earlier Saturday rented out a section of the Great Wall
northeast of Beijing for a champagne lunch.
   The organizer of the tour, Daniel Vial, said the fee for renting
the Great Wall was $54,000, but he did not know the total cost of
the Great Hall extravaganza.
   China, which once shunned all contacts with the West and as
recently as last year staged a major political campaign against
Western ideas, is now avidly promoting tourism as a way to earn
badly-needed foreign currency.
   On Sunday, some members of the tour will attend an auction of
donated Western and Chinese art staged by London-based Sotheby's,
with proceeds also going to Venice and the Great Wall.
   Organizers now say, however, that the Chinese have charged such
high prices for transportation, food, site rentals and service that
the project will barely break even.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
