<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 1413EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LehderPlot     06-04 0691</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lehder Plot,0713</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witness Tells Of Plan To Secure Lehder's Arrest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plot to lure Colombian drug lord
Carlos Lehder Rivas into the arms of U.S. agents by using his
friendship with a convicted smuggler was in the works when Lehder
was caught by police in 1987 following a shootout at a jungle
mansion.
   Lehder, 38, was convicted in May, following a seven-month trial,
of all 11 counts of a 1981 indictment that alleged he conspired to
smuggle some 3.3 tons of cocaine into the United States via the
Bahamas from 1978 to 1980.
   Lehder, a leader of the Medellin cartel of Colombian drug
smugglers, faces life plus 150 years in prison when he is sentenced
July 20 by U.S. District Judge Howell W. Melton. The cartel has been
blamed for smuggling 80 percent of the cocaine brought into this
country.
   George Jung, 45, the first witness in Lehder's trial, said he was
contacted by an FBI agent in 1986 with a proposal that he travel to
South America to help lure Lehder into a position where he could be
captured by U.S. agents, such as on a ship in international waters.
   ``The plan was finalized. It was to the point that I was going to
go down there,'' Jung, of Weymouth, Mass., said in a jailhouse
interview with The Associated Press.
   Federal officials asked that Jung's location not be revealed.
   An FBI official in Washington confirmed Jung's story on the
condition that his identity not be revealed.
   He said the plan never got past the discussion stage because of
Lehder's arrest in Colombia in February 1987 and because of the
incredible amount of paperwork and approvals required for such an
operation.
   Jung met Lehder when both were inmates in federal prison in
Danbury, Conn., in 1974 and said he considered the young, brash
Colombian as ``a brother.''
   ``He was very intelligent, articulate, well-mannered. He had an
elegance about him. He was a cut above the rest,'' said Jung.
   They formed a cocaine business using Lehder's drug connections
and Jung's contacts in this country.
   Their first trips involved young women who brought back cocaine
hidden in the lining of suitcases. Jung then began making one or two
flights a week to California, carrying 15 to 25 kilograms, and
dealing with connections he had made in the marijuana business.
   ``We introduced the drug on a large scale in L.A.,'' Jung said.
   That relationship eventually soured when Lehder went behind his
back and cut Jung out of the business.
   In February 1986, while Lehder was still a fugitive hiding in the
jungles of South America, Jung said he was contacted by federal
agents while he was being held in Miami awaiting trial on charges he
smuggled some 660 pounds of cocaine into the United States.
   ``They were working on a plan for me to go down to Colombia and
befriend Carlos again,'' he said. ``It set me back for a few
minutes.''
   In June 1986, Jung pleaded guilty to one count of conspiracy to
import cocaine and was sentenced to 15 years.
   That fall, discussions began again, including a possible mock
prison escape as a cover story, ``a reason for me to be back in
Colombia.''
   Before the plan could be put in motion, Jung heard a television
report of Lehder's arrest near Medellin, Colombia. Lehder was
immediately placed on a plane and flown to the United States.
   Jung said he was promised nothing in exchange for his testimony
against Lehder, although prosecutors promised to make his
cooperation known to his sentencing judge, who was considering a
motion for reduction of sentence.
   So far, Jung has not heard anything about his sentence being
reduced.
   Jung was the first of 115 witnesses to take the stand against
Lehder.
   ``We definitely looked at each other. ... It was like it had come
to an end and it was time to clear the books,'' said Jung. ``I had
no second thoughts, no qualms.''
   While in prison, Jung has written a book on his life of crime
called: ``Grazing In The Grass Until The Snow Came.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
