<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 1422EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthKorea     06-04 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Korea,0518</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radical Students Attempt Suicide, Arrested At US Army Base</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A student tried to burn himself to
death in an anti-government, anti-U.S. protest Saturday, and four
students demanding permission to go to the northern border were
arrested at a U.S. Army base.
   Park Rae-chun, 24, doused his body with flammable liquid and
ignited it at Soongshil University in Seoul.
   ``Overthrow military fascists!'' he shouted before setting
himself afire. Hospital officials said Park was in critical
condition.
   Student sources said Park left a suicide note that strongly
criticized the government and the United States, which has 42,000
troops stationed in South Korea under a mutual defense pact.
   Ritual suicide is a tactic used by South Korea dissidents to
shame the government. In May, two students killed themselves in
anti-government protests.
   Police arrested four student leaders at the headquarters of the
U.S. Army in Seoul on Saturday. The four tried to force their way
through the main gate to get U.S. permission for a planned march to
the border.
   At a meeting Saturday at Seoul's Yonsei University, radical
student leaders elected representatives to meet with North Korean
students June 10 at the truce village of Panmunjom, which is in the
demilitarized zone and under U.S. military control.
   Four students then went to the U.S. base to demand permission to
go to the border. But police seized the students when they arrived
at the base.
   A U.S. officer briefly met with one student before police took
them away in a bus as the students yelled `Yankee go home!'' and
other anti-U.S. slogans.
   A U.S. Army spokesman later said only the South Korean government
can grant permission for civilians to visit the border.
   Police said Saturday that any students marching to the border
would be arrested.
   Radicals said Saturday that they called the June 10 march to
Panmunjom to reunify the divided Korean peninsula and North Korea's
participation in the Olympic Games in Seoul. North Korea is
boycotting the Games after the South rejected its demand to be made
a co-host.
   North Korea's official news agency reported Saturday that its
government will not allow the International Olympic Committee
president to visit the capital of Pyongyang to encourage North
Korean participation in the Games.
   Committee president Juan Antonio Samaranch had said he would
accept an invitation to visit North Korea but had ruled out
discussing a demand to be a co-host of the Games.
   The student arrests followed a government warning to crack down
on unrest and what authorities called radicals aiding North Korea.
   Prime Minister Lee Hyun-jai warned Saturday in a nationally
televised speech that the government would not tolerate violent
protests.
   Unification of the two Koreas is an emotional issue for most
Koreans. Most people in the South are distrustful of the North,
which invaded the South in 1950.
   Radical students have attacked U.S. diplomatic posts in recent
protests demanding the U.S. troop withdrawal. The students claim the
United States enforced the 1945 partition of Korea.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
