<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Najib     06-04 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Najib,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Najib Meets Gorbachev in Moscow</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: One word cq for Najib</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan President Najib made a surprise call
Saturday on Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev to review the
superpower summit and settlement of the conflict in Afghanistan,
Tass said.
   The news agency said Najib stopped off in Moscow en route to New
York, where he will attend the Third Special Disarmament Session of
the United Nations General Assembly.
   The brief Tass dispatch said Najib ``spoke highly'' of
Gorbachev's summit meeting last week with President Reagan. It said
Gorbachev and Najib touched on the Afghanistan government's attempts
to end the bloody civil war and on relations between Kabul and
Moscow.
   The meeting was not announced in advance.
   The Soviet Union began pulling its more than 100,000 troops out
of Afghanistan on May 15 under an agreement signed in April in
Geneva. The troops arrived in December 1979 to help the Kabul
government fight anti-Marxist guerrillas.
   The Soviet Union has warned it might halt or slow the pullout
unless Pakistan stops aiding the guerrillas. Many of the guerrillas'
weapons come from the United States.
   Also at Saturday's meeting with Najib was Soviet Foreign Minister
Eduard A. Shevardnadze and Central Committee foreign affairs
secretary Anatoly Dobrynin, Tass said.
</TEXT>
