<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Journalist-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru   06-04 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Journalist-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0492,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Journalist Talks About Imprisonment In Afghanistan</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: To CORRECT spelling of Biloslavo, SUB 8th graf, `Biloslavio
said...' and 11th graf, `Biloslavio said...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Italian journalist jailed for more than six months
in Afghanistan said he had to rely on the charity of other prisoners
to get enough to eat and that he wanted to go back to Afghanistan.
   Fausto Biloslavo, 26, arrived in Rome on Thursday aboard a
special private plane from Kabul. He had entered Afghanistan in July
with anti-Marxist insurgents and was arrested Nov. 14 after he was
captured by two children with machine guns.
   In March, he was convicted of espionage and sentenced to seven
years in prison. His release Thursday came after a plea from Italian
President Francesco Cossiga. He had shared a cell with French
freelance photojournalist Alain Guillo, who was freed last week
after an appeal by French President Francois Mitterrand.
   During a news conference Friday, Biloslavo declined to give many
specifics about his imprisonment. He said he will eventually publish
notes he wrote on the inside of cigarette packages.
   He said he was held at Puli Charki prison in Kabul after his
trial.
   ``I had to relay on the charity of the poor people held there in
order to have enough to eat and clothes to wear,'' he said. Later,
he said an Italian diplomatic official helped him get enough food
and clothing.
   He said that besides the Afghan prisoners at Puli Charki, he saw
40 Pakistanis, 20 Iranians and a young Turk. He said 95 percent of
the foreigners had been ``brutally tortured,'' but he declined to
say how.
   Biloslavo said he was not beaten after his imprisonment, but said
he was whipped by an officer after his capture.
   He denied that someone could have turned him in, but added that
the Afghan resistance movement is extremely fragmented and
``contains a number of rogues'' for whom ``a reporter would be worth
thousands of dollars.''
   After his arrest, he said he was taken to the prison of the
``secret police,'' where he was held for four months in conditions
he described as ``decent.''
   Biloslavo said his trial was a farce and that the accusations
were ``crazy.''
   He said he was never given any hints as to his approaching
liberation, and the only way he had kept in touch with the outside
world were through rumors and the official television.
   He said he would seek a visa to return to Afghanistan.
   Anti-communist guerrillas have been fighting a civil war in
Afghanistan since the late 1970s. Soviet troops entered the country
in 1979, replacing one pro-Soviet regime with another and staying to
protect that regime from the guerrillas.
   The Soviets began withdrawing their estimated 115,000 troops from
Afghanistan in May.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
