<DOCNO> AP880604-0143 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 1538EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Students     06-04 0651</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Students,0678</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Students End Soviet Stay On A `Summit' Note</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN FRIEDMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of American students who spent two months
in the Soviet Union return home this week, buoyed by experiences
that ranged from wading in a Russian swamp to feeling the
electricity of superpower summitry.
   The 16 students, mostly from Dartmouth College in New Hampshire,
took classes in Russian language and literature, as well as
environmental issues, at Moscow State University. The program was
born of the December summit meeting in Washington.
   In return, a like number of Soviet students will study in
Hanover, N.H., this summer.
   The students witnessed the hopeful political changes under
Mikhail S. Gorbachev, but they also saw the prejudices toward women,
blacks and Jews, as well as the bleakness of the Soviet economy.
   ``There was graffiti in the elevator at the university,'' said
Celia Jablow a senior from Claremont, Calif. ``It said `Kill a Jew,
save the Soviet Union.' One of our people erased it.''
   ``It is really a hard thing to talk to someone for two hours
continuously about how much they hate blacks and how incompetent
biologically they think they are,'' added Catherine Atwell, a junior
from Washington, D.C.
   She also recounted hearing continually how women should stay in
the home, as well as hearing the phrase, ``You've got a girl's
memory.''
   But the students said that Muscovites seemed to be more
politically aware under Gorbachev, less afraid of foreigners, and
more hopeful about their future _ although the economic changes are
slow to arrive, what with shortages of sugar and toothpaste.
   On May 29, while on a field trip to a swampy nature preserve near
the Oka River, about 70 miles northwest of Moscow, the group
gathered around a TV set in the home of a groundskeeper and joined a
group of Russians to watch President Reagan land in the Soviet Union.
   ``They were really happy to see Reagan _ much happier than we
were,'' said Atwell.
   ``Yeah, we made a few cynical remarks along the way _ you know,
typical American students,'' added Peter MacDonald, a junior from
Andover, Mass. ``When Reagan spoke, everyone would watch us and when
Gorbachev spoke, everyone (of us) would watch them.''
   The Americans, who have all concentrated on Russian studies and
have studied the language an average of three years, were questioned
by the Soviets on Reagan's referring to their country as ``the evil
empire.''
   ``They asked us, ``Did he really say that?''' Atwell said.
   Another of the Dartmouth group, Paul Wlodkowski, of Augusta,
Maine, met briefly with Reagan after his speech to Moscow university
students and acted as a translator for Cable News Network.
   Jablow said their student accomodations weren't bad, but the main
problem was ``a certain feeling of being trapped.'' There were no
telephones in the dormitory rooms, which each housed two students.
   Visitors would drop by often and not ``understand the need to be
alone at times when you need your own space,'' Jablow said.
   There was little time to do sightseeing, she said. ``Most of your
time you weren't in class or doing homework, you felt an obligation
_ at least I did _ to meet people and talk.''
   Although the exchange program was designed to concentrate on
environmental studies, group adviser and Dartmouth professor Barry
Scherr said its real purpose was to give the students greater
exposure to Russian language, literature and society.
   Other Dartmouth Students on the trip were Loretta Berger, of
Lexington, Mass.; Katherine Chernishov of Riverdale, N.Y.; Heidi
Crebo of Marston's Mills, Mass.; Mark Filimonov of Hanover, N.H.;
Joseph Hatem of Methuen, Mass.; Betsy Heafitz of Swampscott, Mass.;
Peter Hujik of Monona, Wis.; Jeffrey Matusow of Durham, N.H.; and
Allison Smith of Bath, Ohio.
   There also were two students from Minnesota's Carleton College,
Brett Duffy and Anders Nelson, and Deborah Budek of Wheaton College
in Massachusetts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
