<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Smoking-ChildAbuse     06-04 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Smoking-Child Abuse,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Says Mom's Smoking Around 4-Year-Old Is Child Abuse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Circuit Court judge has ruled that a
woman smoker may not light up in confined areas around her
4-year-old child, but the angry woman says she'll appeal the order.
   ``Exposing a child whose lungs are still growing to passive smoke
is another form of child abuse,'' Judge Bill Swann said Friday after
issuing the order to Priscilla Bullock.
   Ms. Bullock said she was in court to respond to a petition filed
by her ex-husband, Christopher Reeves, to lower his child-support
payment and to modify visitation privileges. His petition was denied
two months ago and he was appealing to Swann.
   The petition was denied again, but Ms. Bullock said that ``from
out of the blue,'' Swann granted a request by her ex-husband's
lawyer to prohibit the mother from smoking around the child in a
confined environment, such as a home or a car.
   ``I am 30 years old. This is a violation of my civil rights,''
she said. ``My (former) husband drinks beer and I didn't say he
couldn't drink around the child. ...
   ``It's time for me to move out of Tennessee if a judge can keep
me from having a cigarette in my own home.''
   Ms. Bullock also must not allow others to smoke in her home if
the child is present.
   Swann, who said he has made similar rulings in the past two
years, said in these cases ``the court takes judicial notice of the
particular dangers passive smoke has on developing lungs.''
   He said providing a healthy environment is as important as
ensuring the child has adequate food, clothing, shelter and
education.
   Ms. Bullock said she would appeal Swann's ruling.
</TEXT>
