<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 1549EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pope-Ferrari     06-04 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope-Ferrari,0491</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Takes Spin In Sports Car, Talks to Boss</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PIERO VALSECCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FIORANO MODENESE, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II took a spin in a
sleek red Ferrari sports car to the cheers of a crowd Saturday when
he visited the headquarters of Italy's most renowned racing team.
   Piero Lardi Ferrari, the son of the company's grand old boss,
drove the ``Mondial Cabrio'' along the Fiorano track near Modena,
where the company's Formula One racers are tested.
   The car, capable of reaching speeds in excess of 155 mph,
occasionally sputtered as it moved around the track at 12 to 18 mph
with the pope aboard.
   John Paul, on his second day of a five-day visit to the
Emilia-Romagna region, stood and clenched the windshield as the car
negotiated the twisty course between two lines of several hundred
cheering faithful.
   ``Il papa in pista!'' (the pope on the track), the announcer
shouted into the loudspeakers. The drive was the highlight of the
pontiff's three-hour visit.
   The pope had been expected to meet Enzo Ferrari, the 90-year-old
company chairman and avowed agnostic who in the past has had stormy
relations with the Vatican, which had harshly criticized his racing
activities.
   Piero Lardi Ferrari said the meeting was canceled because his
father developed a fever Thursday night ``and preferred not to leave
home.'' The elder Ferrari suffers from a kidney disease. His son
said Saturday that his father's condition was not serious.
   The pope met privately with Ferrari relatives and talked to the
elder Ferrari by telephone.
   ``They spoke for about five minutes,'' Vatican spokesman Giovanni
D'Ercole said. ``It was a courtesy gesture by the pope toward
Ferrari. They exchanged good wishes, and the pope listened with
great attention. One can imagine that Ferrari was moved.''
   The pope also met with Ferrari Formula One drivers Gerhard Berger
of Austria and Michele Alboreto of Italy and addressed a crowd of
workers from a stand on the edge of the track.
   He shook hands with the two drivers and cast a quick glance at a
Ferrari racer exhibited in the courtyard along with some old models.
   He looked amazed and said ``it's an impressive speed'' when
Berger told him it can reach 186 mph.
   In his speech to a few thousand workers and their families, the
pope denounced serious pollution and threats to the environment
``caused by the anxiety of the maximum profit, which leads to a
senseless exploitation of natural resources.''
   He again emphasized the ``right to work'' for all people and said
that technological innovations ``must be pursued and accepted, but
must be oriented to the service of the man.''
   Before leaving Fiorano, he thanked the audience ``for your
patience and for the gifts, which allow me to make some charity.''
   The gifts included a horse and dozens of wheels of Parmesan
cheese.
</TEXT>
