<DOCNO> AP880604-0152 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 1626EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Reagan     06-04 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Reagan,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lord Reagan? One Lawmaker's Hope</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan should be given an honorary
peerage or similar honor when he leaves office in recognition of his
contribution to world peace, a Conservative lawmaker suggested
Saturday.
   ``I think the whole British nation would rejoice if an honor of
great distinction could be bestowed on him,'' said Harry Greenway, a
member of Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's governing party.
   Greenway noted other foreigners have been included in Britain's
ancient system of honors, titles and awards, most recently former
U.S. Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger who received an honorary
knighthood in February.
   ``I see no reason why arrangements could not be made for an
honorary peerage to be bestowed on President Reagan, not only in
recognition of his unique special relationship with Britain but also
to mark his massive contribution to world peace,'' Greenway said.
   The Anglo-American relationship has flourished under Reagan and
Mrs. Thatcher, who have struck a close personal friendship to cement
their working alliance.
   Reagan underlined that relationship last week by stopping in
London on his way home from the Moscow summit with Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev to give Mrs. Thatcher a briefing. Reagan leaves
office in January.
   Greenway said if Reagan were made an honorary peer, ``such
recognition, unique, bold and breathtaking, would signal how much we
recognize what this great man has done for world peace.''
   British peerages formally are awarded by Queen Elizabeth II,
although most are made on the prime minister's recommendation.
   Unlike British peers, honorary peers are not entitled to sit in
the House of Lords.
   Weinberger was the 56th American to receive an honorary
knighthood.
   Other Americans with the honor include actors Douglas Fairbanks
Jr. and Sidney Poitier, former U.S. Ambassador Walter Annenberg,
former Sen. William Fulbright, philanthropists Paul Mellon and John
Paul Getty II, industrialist Henry Ford III, and Dean Rusk, a former
secretary of state.
   Weinberger received his honorary knighthood for being ``a staunch
friend to Britain, remembered most of all for his unfailing support
and assistance during the Falklands War,'' the Foreign Office said
at the time.
   The United States provided naval intelligence and political
support to Britain during its victory over Argentina in a 74-day war
over the Falkland Islands in the South Atlantic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
