<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0627 06-04 0755</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0627,0773</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinians Strike to Protest Shultz Mission</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS INSERTS 5 grafs after 4th `Curfews and' with Tel Aviv march;
pick up 5th `At Shuyukh...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arabs shut down the occupied lands for a second
day Saturday to protest the Middle East tour of Secretary of State
George Shultz, and Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said he still
opposes the U.S. peace plan.
   Israeli soldiers breaking up a protest shot a 55-year-old Arab
woman in the hand in the Gaza Strip's Nusseirat refugee camp, a
local reporter said. The army confirmed the injury and said it was
investigating the circumstances.
   Stores were closed and public transport halted in the occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip, where a rebellion against Israeli rule
began six months ago among the 1.5 million Palestinian residents.
The strike also paralyzed Arab east Jerusalem.
   Curfews and closures continued for at least six towns and refugee
camps with 120,000 Arab residents.
   In Tel Aviv, about 5,000 Israelis marched to support ending the
occupation in exchange for peace.
   Fights started when police arrested a woman wearing a dress with
the design of the Palestinian flag, which Israel has outlawed.
Police said eight people were arrested.
   ``There was a problem with the woman, who was asked to take the
flag off her body,'' said a police spokesman, whose name was
withheld in keeping with regulations. ``Her friends tried to prevent
her arrest.''
   Witnesses said police punched and clubbed photographers who took
pictures of the incident.
   Witnesses said passersby shouted insults and spat on the marchers.
   At Shuyukh village, near Hebron in the West Bank, about 250
residents marched in memory of 20-year-old Mustafa Ahmed Halaika,
who was shot to death Friday. Members of his family accused young
Jewish settlers of the killing, and Israeli authorities said they
were investigating.
   An army officer killed another Palestinian later Friday when
Arabs surrounded and stoned his military patrol in Tzafa village,
near Ramallah north of Jerusalem, the army said.
   At least 201 Palestinians have been killed since riots began Dec.
8 in the territories Israel captured from Jordan and Egypt in the
1967 war, a six-day confict that began 21 years ago Sunday. An
Israeli soldier and a Jewish settler also have been slain.
   Shamir told Israel radio he still opposes the U.S. proposal for
an international peace conference and does not expect a breakthrough
while Shultz is in the region. He also opposes trading land for
peace, the other essential part of the American plan.
   The prime minister said of Shultz: ``He has a very difficult
mission. He is entitled to encouragement but we must be frank with
him. We can't nurture illusions.''
   He said the secretary, on his fourth visit to the Middle East in
five months, had undertaken a ``very ambitious plan.'' Shultz began
his tour Friday in Cairo, visited Amman on Saturday and is due here
Sunday.
   ``Is is known that Americans excel in their spirit of optimism,
and we should learn from their optimism, but this optimism should
not blind one's eyes,'' Shamir said.
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, Shamir's partner and rival in the
tenuous government coalition, supports an international conference,
but his political adviser Nimrod Novik said little could be done
before Israeli elections in November.
   Shultz should try to ``sustain the momentum and work on the
(peace) package, so that once the decision is made by the Israeli
electorate in November the package is ready,'' Novik said.
   Shamir leads the right-wing Likud bloc and Peres heads the
center-left Labor Party.
   The Palestinian uprising has become the central election issue.
Its underground leaders called the three-day general strike to
protest the U.S. peace plan because it does not include an
independent Palestinian state.
   On Saturday leaflets began circulating in the West Bank and Gaza
signed by the Islamic Resistance Movement, which broke with the
regular underground leadership earlier this year.
   They called June the ``month of damnation to the occupation'' and
declared: ``We should continue the uprising for a long time. We
should not heed any voices calling for ending the uprising or making
it less important.''
   Palestinians should use ``stones, slingshots, sticks, Molotov
cocktails and empty hands'' to resist Israeli rule, the leaflets
said.
   Gen. Yitzhak Mordechai, Israeli commander in the Gaza Strip,
urged residents to ignore the war anniversary. He promised better
living conditions and relief from curfews in areas that remain quiet
and said summer visits from relatives abroad would be forbidden in
trouble spots.
</TEXT>
