<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Panama-Evictions     06-04 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Evictions,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Evict Hundreds of Panama City Shanty Dwellers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police have evicted hundreds of people
from their cardboard and tin homes in Panama City and ordered them
to burn the shacks, saying the squatters had invaded private
property.
   Many of the victims were people who had lost their jobs during
the past few months as Panama's economy went into a tailspin because
of the political crisis brought on by the confrontation between the
Reagan administration and Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, the head of
Panama's Defense Forces.
   ``We came here because we had nowhere else to go,'' said Angelina
Concepcion, a mother of two, as she gathered some of her few
belongings early Saturday and piled them by the side of a road.
   Police who began the evictions Friday night stood by and watched
as she worked. They refused to talk to journalists and barred
photographers from the area.
   Residents said the police ordered them to leave and said the
shanties would be burned down. Police then set fire to some of the
one-room structures, according to the victims.
   ``I made mine out of wood because they told us we could stay if
we built good homes,'' said Evangelista Samaniego whose building was
set ablaze in the open, swampy zone.
   Early Saturday crews sent from the company that owns the land and
trucks from the Housing Ministry were helping residents move their
belongings to other areas where some said they were told they could
rebuild.
   Housing Ministry and company officials were not available for
comment.
   Many squatters said they had not been given any notice that they
would have to leave and had been led to believe they could
eventually settle in the district. They had installed a water pipe
from the street.
   The pipeline was removed by police.
   ``If they wanted the land, they could have told us and given us
some time to move. They should not have done it this way,'' said
Leonel Mora. He said he had moved his family into the area two
months ago after he lost his job and had to leave a house he rented
for $50 a month.
   Many people have lost their jobs and there is a critical
shortager of money becasuse of the economic sanctions imposed by the
United States in an effort to force Noriega, the power behind the
civilian government, to resign and leave Panama.
   Noriega was indicted by two federal grand juries in Florida in
February that accused him of drug trafficking. The general has
denied the allegations and rejected the U.S. appeals that he quit as
head of the 15,000-member Defense Forces.
</TEXT>
