<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Claims Attack On Ship; Iran Says It Repelled Iraqi Ground
Attack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq reported it attacked a tanker moored
at an Iranian oil terminal Saturday and Iran claimed its forces
repelled an Iraqi attempt to regain captured land in the northern
mountains.
   The official Iraqi News Agency, monitored in Nicosia, said
fighter-bombers scored ``a direct and effective hit on a large
maritime target'' in the tanker holding area near Iran's Kharg
Island in the northern Persian Gulf.
   The agency, quoting a military communique, did not identify the
vessel.
   There was no confirmation from gulf-based shipping officials or
Iran.
   The Iraqi agency quoted a military spokesman as saying the attack
was part of the campaign to deprive Iran of ``oil revenues used to
finance its war effort.'' Iran and Iraq have been at war since
September 1980.
   The air strike was the first Iraqi shipping raid reported in
three weeks. The last attack was May 14, when Iraq's French-built
Mirage F-1 jets bombed tankers off Iran's Larak island terminal in
the southern gulf.
   Five tankers were set ablaze in that raid. The 235,000-ton
Spanish supertanker Barcelona later exploded and sank. The
564,739-ton Liberian-flagged Seawise Giant was badly damaged.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency, also monitored in
Nicosia, said Revolutionary Guards and Iraqi dissident forces killed
or wounded 200 Iraqi troops in repelling an attack on positions in
the Shemiran mountains in northeast Iraq on Friday.
   The Iranians and Kurdish guerrilla allies seized the heights in
the Darbandikhan region of Kurdistan in February.
   There was no word from Iraq on fighting in that region.
   Iraq has been expected to launch assaults in that area following
its success in driving the Iranians out of two other key footholds
on Iraqi soil _ the southern Faw Peninsula on April 18 and a
bridgehead east of the southern port of Basra May 25.
   In another development, Austrian President Kurt Waldheim arrived
in Jiddah, Saudi Arabia, Saturday on a state visit. The rest of his
planned gulf tour was scrapped because of a scheduled Arab summit
conference on the Palestinian issue.
   Leaders of Kuwait and the United Arab Emirates, who were to
receive him in their capitals, were leaving for the summit which is
opening in Algiers on Tuesday.
   The Saudi monarch, King Fahd, will fly to the Algerian capital
just as Waldheim is concluding his three-day visit to the kingdom.
</TEXT>
