<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash Landing,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Candidate Not Injured In 30 Mph Crash-Landing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican gubernatorial candidate state
Rep. Bob Williams and his pilot escaped injury when their
single-engine private plane crash-landed on a highway near the
Olympia Airport.
   State Rep. Bob Williams, 46, and pilot Dan Pryor, 38, were on
their way to Olympia from Long Beach when the accident occurred
Friday evening, Pryor said.
   The pilot said he had cut power while approaching the airport,
then tried to abort his landing but was unable to get enough power
to go around for another landing attempt.
   The 30-year-old Cessna 175 gradually lost altitude until it
clipped a row of 3-foot-tall trees on a tree farm, and slid sideways
about 40 feet before coming to rest on the highway.
   Pryor estimated the plane was traveling 30 mph when it hit the
ground.
   Pryor, of Olympia, said the plane ``simply choked out'' and he
could offer no further explanation for the engine trouble.
   Williams, of Longview, said one car passed at the time of the
accident and the driver checked to see if anyone was injured before
leaving to notify authorities.
