<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Angola     06-04 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Angola,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Africa Reports Angolan-Cuban Buildup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angola is threatening peace
negotiations by massing equipment and soldiers, including Cubans,
near its border with South-West Africa, the military said Saturday.
   The Foreign Ministry declared earlier in the day that future
talks must be held in Africa and said Angola should apologize to the
Congo for trying to change the venue.
   Angola said Thursday the next meetings on peace in Angola and
South-West Africa, also called Namibia, would be held in Europe.
   Cuba and the United States also are involved in the talks, which
began May 3 in London. Their aim is to get foreign soldiers out of
Angola, end the civil war there and achieve independence for
neighboring South-West Africa, which South Africa controls in
defiance of U.N. resolutions..
   On May 18, South Africa and Angola followed up the previous talks
with discussions in Brazzaville, Congo, and then the argument began
over a site for future meetings.
   The South African military statement Saturday spoke of ``a
provocative and aggressive buildup of forces in South Angola ...
which prove the Cubans are obviously not displaying any seriousness
toward the peace negotiations.''
   Some South African troops remain in Angola, helping
U.S.-supported rebels fight the Marxist government and a Cuban force
of at least 40,000 soldiers stationed in the country. Rebels of the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola, known as UNITA,
are not involved in the peace talks.
   Gen. Jannie Geldenhuys, South Africa's military commander, said
May 26 that Cuban and Angolan troops were moving south toward the
frontier with South-West Africa. South African soldiers regularly
cross into southern Angola to attack guerrilla bases of SWAPO, the
South-West African People's Organization.
   In the statement Saturday, the military said Cubans, Angolans and
SWAPO guerrillas had occupied nine more towns near the border,
supported by tanks, armored personnel carriers and artillery.
   It said SWAPO used the protection of the Cuban-Angolan buildup to
move its headquarters closer to the Namiobian border.
   Guerrillas were seen in Cuban uniforms and were using vehicles
disguised as South African to abduct Namibian children, the
statement claimed. It said ``whites with long hair ... which could
possibly point to Russian ... soldiers or East Germans'' had been
seen in Umfilo, 25 miles from the border.
</TEXT>
