<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 1755EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ParksConference     06-04 0810</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Parks Conference,0829</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>National Parks Chiefs Gain New Tips, Memories of Old Friends</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAD BARTIMUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAND TETON NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   During coffee breaks and
after dinner, alone, in groups, or with their children,
superintendents of America's national parks wandered over to a small
plaque on the wall of Jackson Lake Lodge during their convention,
which ended Sunday.
   As they read the congressional mandate that created their agency
72 years ago, they inevitably looked out the floor-to-ceiling
windows next to the plaque to stare in silence at the majestic Teton
Mountains, protected forever by a national park.
   The purpose of the parks, the mandate says, ``is to conserve the
scenery and the natural and historic objects and the wildlife
therein and to provide for the same ... in such manner ... as will
leave them unimpaired for the enjoyment of future generations.''
   ``This is what it's all about,'' said Dick Marks, chief of Grand
Canyon National Park in Arizona. ``I look out there and I'm inspired
to do a better job. I look around this room and I know 75 percent of
the people. I have memories of them, not as just friends, but of
what they've accomplished. Each represents some portion of my 27
years in the park service.''
   Repeatedly during the first general superintendent's conference
held by the National Park Service in 12 years, park managers
embraced colleagues they hadn't seen for years and greeted with hugs
the families of long-ago co-workers.
   The four-day meeting was packed with business sessions.
Politicians, Interior Department bureaucrats, and experts lecturing
on issues relevant to running the parks dominated the schedule.
   But the gathering called by NPS Director William Penn Mott for
his 342 superintendents, 10 regional directors, and dozens of
Washington, D.C., staff members was more of a family reunion than a
business convention.
   Two young rangers who served with him at the Blue Ridge Parkway
in June 1961 joined Dick Marks as top managers at the convention.
   ``These people are more than associates, they are family,'' said
Marks, a hint of a tear in his eye. ``I will use them as sounding
boards to help me solve problems. When we sit down and talk
together, they remind me of the things that brought me into the
service, the dedication to the mission of protecting our best
resources.''
   They were brought together to talk of issues, such as planning
for the 21st century, but they were also told to have a good time.
   ``I felt bringing everybody together for inspiration and
education, and for getting acquainted with each other as a total
national park system, would be a highly desirable thing to do for
the morale of the organization and for the consolidation of our
commitment,'' said Mott.
   The 78-year-old director, who said he's taken three weekends off
during his three-year tenure, built a free afternoon into the
schedule so his managers and their families could get outdoors in
Grand Teton National Park and nearby Yellowstone National Park.
   Alan O'Neill, superintendent at Lake Mead National Recreation
Area in Arizona and Nevada, got to take his first rafting trip in
years.
   Bob Heyder, superintendent at Mesa Verde National Park in
Colorado, took his wife, Kathy, and daughter, Gretchen, hiking, the
first time the family has taken a walk together ``in ages,'' said
his wife.
   Marks took a sack lunch and sat on a rock, then took a walk.
Asked to recall the last time he had two hours by himself in the
outdoors, Marks thought for a minute, then replied: ``I can't
remember.''
   Chrysandra ``Sandy'' Walter, superintendent at Lowell National
Historical Park in Massachussetts, said, ``Being together in this
beautiful place has given us time to reflect on what the National
Park Service means to the United States and what it stands for in
the world ... I've had my `family' around me, including four of the
ranger recruits I went through basic training with nearly 20 years
ago who are now superintendents.''
   Robin Winks, a history professor at Yale University and a
passionate visitor to more than 300 of the 342 units in the system,
told the superintendents Thursday, ``You begin to get into a heart
of a people by what they have chosen to preserve.''
   Mott said America's park stewards are a dedicated corps of
``elite'' men and women. There is an average six-year wait for a
seasonal ranger to become a permanent employee. Within the service,
which has about 16,000 full-time workers, the annual turnover rate,
including retirement, is 2 percent.
   ``This week has been almost like a religious retreat,'' said
Heyder. ``I'm going away refreshed and inspired.''
   Like the other superintendents, Heyder faces a summer of
anticipated record crowds, maintenance problems that include
everything from overflowing toilets to chuckholes in the roads, and
too much work to do with too little money.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
