<1ST_LINE>r i AM-YugoslavActivist     06-04 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslav Activist,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Slovenian Youths Protest Arrest of Dissident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 150 Slovenian youths have
established a committee to help defend a political activist who was
arrested on suspicion of revealing military secrets, a committee
member said Saturday.
   He said the committee sent a letter to President Raif Dizdarevic
demanding the release of Janez Jansa, who was arrested Tuesday in
Ljubljana after reporting alleged plans for a military coup in the
northern republic of Slovenia.
   A journalist and one of four candidates for president of the
Slovenian Socialist Youth Union, Jansa had published a number of
articles in liberal periodicals criticizing army policies.
   In one he said the military planned a coup in Slovenia to quell
dissent in Yugoslavia's most liberal republic. That report was
denied last week by the government.
   A committee member, speaking with the condition he not be
identified, told The Associated Press in a telephone interview from
Ljubljana that Jansa has refused to be represented by a military
lawyer and apparently has decided to defend himself at his trial.
   In a statement issued Friday, the Slovenian Socialist Youth Union
said information about Jansa's detention was ``insufficient and
contradictory, which leads us to doubt the correctness of the
procedure.''
   The army has said Jansa is being held at a military prison, but
has refused to release details about his arrest.
</TEXT>
