<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 1816EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-OldestPriest     06-04 0612</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oldest Priest,0631</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Great-Granddad Becomes Father Of Much Larger Family</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just 24 days short of his 80th birthday, William
R. Schumacher on Saturday became the oldest man ordained as a Roman
Catholic priest in U.S. history.
   Schumacher, the father of six, the grandfather of 13 and the
great-grandfather of one, became the father of a much larger family
in a two-hour service at his hometown church.
   ``What he's taught all of us is, there's nothing you can't do if
you really want to do it _ he believes that,'' said Fran Lipton, 48,
Schumacher's daughter. She attended the service with her five
brothers and several of the new priest's grandchildren.
   Wearing a simple white robe, the bespectacled white-haired
widower was ordained into the priesthood by Bishop Thomas Tschoepe
of Dallas. Tschoepe gave Schumacher a chance after he was rejected
by scores of others because of his age.
   Schumacher shrugged off his historic status, which was confirmed
by the National Conference of Catholic Bishops. ``Being a priest is
all that concerned me,'' he said after the ceremony at St. Tarcissus
Roman Catholic Church.
   The service culminated a childhood dream for Schumacher, who
first took steps to attend a seminary when he was 17, but deferred
his plans to care for his widowed mother. Then he got married and
had a family of his own.
   A few weeks after his wife of 52 years, Genevieve, died in 1984,
Schumacher telephoned the Chicago archdiocese and said he wanted to
be a priest.
   ``That's when I knew I was released,'' Schumacher said. ``I no
longer had responsibility because the kids were all taking care of
themselves.
   ``I was then free to do what I originally wanted to do.''
   But officials in Chicago turned him down, saying he was 35 years
beyond the cutoff age of 40 for archdiocesan sponsorship.
   After 49 Catholic dioceses either rejected or ignored letters
from Schumacher, Tschoepe promised to give him an assignment in his
diocese.
   Tschoepe's backing allowed Schumacher to enter the seminary, and
in May, he graduated from Holy Apostles Seminary in Cromwell, Conn.
   ``Bill impresses me as a vigorous man of about 60 or so,'' said
Tschoepe, 72.
   A man almost 80 years old ``can be a good priest,'' the bishop
said. ``With the experience they have they can be very, very
effective, especially in counseling, and their understanding of what
other people are going through is one of `I've been there.'''
   Though he will serve in Dallas, Schumacher requested to be
ordained in his neighborhood church, where he had been a lay leader
for 31 years.
   About 300 people attended the service, and scores of parishioners
lined up in the church's reception hall afterwards to be blessed by
the new priest. Schumacher embraced them one-by-one, praying,
laughing and talking with them.
   As a priest, Schumacher's main responsibilities will be working
with the elderly and sick people.
   Schumacher married in 1931 while enrolled in law school, but he
quit his legal studies with less than a year to go because of
economic responsibilities of caring for a wife and baby during the
Depression.
   For the next four decades, Schumacher pursued various careers in
Chicago including insurance broker, politician, credit manager, and
job counselor for the state of Illinois.
   After retiring from his government job at the age of 68,
Schumacher became a travel agent, a career he continued until he
applied for the seminary, Mrs. Lipton said.
   ``As I was watching the service I thought, my mother would have
been proud to be there; but of course if she was there he wouldn't
have been,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
