<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 1826EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson     06-04 0650</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Urges Tighter Restrictions On Pesticides</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>McFARLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson, campaigning in an
agricultural community with an unusually high rate of child cancer
cases, called Saturday for tighter federal restrictions on
pesticides that may be carcinogenic.
   ``We should not use any untested pesticides,'' he said, adding
that people who work in sprayed fields are being ``used as guinea
pigs.''
   The Democratic presidential candidate, joined by several
celebrities from Los Angeles and United Farm Workers leader Cesar
Chavez, led a march by more than 1,500 people through the modest
McFarland residential area where a ``cancer cluster'' has been
identified.
   ``Today in McFarland we focus on the right to breathe, the right
to drink water, the right to a clean environment,'' Jackson said at
a rally.
   Jackson, campaigning in the final days before California's
Tuesday primary, called for federal financing to find the cause of
the cancers, set up a free clinic for treatment and education, and
``close the data gap'' on pesticides about which little is known.
   A state study identified 12 cases of child cancer including six
deaths between 1975 and this year in McFarland, a town of 6,500
people in California's central agricultural valley.
   Many of the children came from the same heavily Hispanic
neighborhoods, and 80 percent of their fathers worked in the fields
as compared to 45 percent of the fathers in a control group, the
study said.
   Some community residents say there are more cancer cases, and
that the government was too conservative in assessing the size of
the cluster.
   The cause of the cancer has not been determined. The state found
no evidence to link the problem to water, but there is an ongoing
investigation into field pesticides that were heavily sprayed on the
fields in 1980-1982, said the state Department of Health Services.
   Chavez told the rally: ``The use of the pesticides is the cause
of all the problems in McFarland and there is no other cause.''
   Chavez has not endorsed a presidential candidate but many of
those who joined Jackson's march were from the UFW and their red
flags dominated the scene.
   Chavez said Jackson is ``a good friend'' and ``the only candidate
that will not fudge on issues.''
   Also marching were a handful of Los Angeles gang members who met
with Jackson earlier in the week, and celebrities including Bonnie
Raitt, Ned Beatty, Margot Kidder, Buffy Sainte-Marie, Kim Fields,
and Carl Weathers, whose movie title ``Action Jackson'' has become
one of the candidate's slogans.
   Jackson said he came to McFarland because its plight reflects
environmental problems in other areas.
   ``Why are we here? ... We are not finger-pointing, we are
embracing, we are reaching out. The whole nation must be
concerned,'' he said.
   Residents interviewed along the march seemed pleased Jackson was
calling attention to their situation.
   ``We want him to help the cancer victims,'' said bystander
Zenaida Murguia who speaks no English and came out with her husband
and two small children. She said they know the families of the
children who died.
   Jackson is ``the only candidate that has taken an interest in
this thing,'' said Fernando Gil, a postal clerk from nearby Delano,
who said he was undecided whether to vote for Jackson or
front-runner Michael Dukakis on Tuesday.
   Jackson has made the McFarland situation a priority item in his
campaign in recent days. This was his third visit to the town.
   He sees the issue as typifying a range of concerns, including his
calls to shift government priorities toward people who have no
resources, pay more attention to safety and health issues, improve
the lot of Hispanic field workers and demand responsibility from
corporations for the environmental and health effects of their
activities.
   Jackson told reporters that President Reagan, Vice President
George Bush and the head of the Environmental Protection Agency, Lee
Thomas, ``should be here today.''
</TEXT>
