<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 1835EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis 3rdLd-Writethru a0656 06-04 0813</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0656,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Assails White House Fumble of Noriega Negotiations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs, bgng: ``In the ...'' to UPDATE Dukakis
delegate count; INSERTS 2 grafs after 6th graf pvs, bgng: ``Jackson,
Dukakis' ...''; Picks up 7th graf pvs, bgng: ``Republican Vice ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHERRY HILL, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential front-runner
Michael Dukakis suggested Saturday that the Reagan administration
had fumbled an effort to remove Panama's Gen. Manuel Noriega from
office by failing to work with allies in the region.
   Dukakis, resuming his campaign schedule after his wife's spinal
surgery, charged there was ``great anger'' among leaders of Latin
America democracies over the administration's failure to consult
them.
   ``Three respected former presidents of Venezuela, Costa Rica and
Colombia had been working hard together with Spain to arrange for
Noriega's departure,'' Dukakis said at a news conference. ``To the
best of my knowledge their efforts were either unnoticed or
unremarked by the current administration.
   ``Their efforts to provide for Noriega's departure did not
succeed as a result,'' Dukakis said.
   In the final weekend of the 1988 presidential primary campaign,
Dukakis edged slowly closer to the magic 2,081 delegates needed to
clinch the Democratic nomination. The Associated Press count gave
him 1,811 to Jesse Jackson's 985. The Dukakis campaign is confident
the four final primaries on Tuesday, with 466 delegates up for
grabs, will put him over the top.
   Jackson, Dukakis' only remaining rival, campaigned in McFarland,
Calif., a largely Hispanic city of 6,500 that has lost six children
to cancer. Jackson called for increased state and federal
involvement in determining the cause of the mysterious cancers.
Jackson also planned a Hollywood fund-raising gala Saturday night.
   At a rally in McFarland, Jackson called for tighter federal
restrictions on pesticides that may be carcinogenic, saying people
who work in sprayed fields are being ``used as guinea pigs.''
   ``Today in McFarland we focus on the right to breathe, the right
to drink water, the right to a clean environment,'' Jackson said at
a rally.
   Republican Vice President George Bush spent the day at home in
Washington before heading to California for a three-day countdown to
the primary season end.
   The Massachusetts governor, a major advocate of the regional
peace plan proposed by Costa Rican President Oscar Arias, called it
``inconceivable'' for a U.S. administration to fail to talk with
leaders of those nations if it is serious about promoting democracy
in the region.
   He said their plan involved getting Noriega to leave Panama and
go to Spain.
   He said he did not know details of what went on within the
administration, but said, ``I know from my own consultations with
Latin American leaders that there was no consultation of any
significance between the administration and the democratically
elected chiefs of state on this issue.''
   ``To the best of my knowledge there has been little or no
consultation and there is great anger, I might add, among
democratically elected chiefs of state in Central and South America
at the failure of our government to consult with them,'' he told
reporters.
   The State Department announced two weeks ago that negotiations
with Noriega, including the dismissal of drug trafficking charges
against him, had collapsed.
   In his first events since his wife Kitty's operation to repair
herniated discs in her back, Dukakis spoke to a rally in a park in
the shadow of nearby Philadelphia by the Cooper River, where
pollution has been cleaned up.
   Dukakis stressed themes of family, the environment and of
combatting drugs _ all issues the Dukakis campaign hopes will appeal
to suburban swing voters, not just in New Jersey's primary next
Tuesday but in the fall against Republican George Bush as well.
   ``I spent a little time with Kitty,'' Dukakis told the crowd of
about 400 people. ``She appears to be OK and the operation appears
to be a success. I'm married to a very strong woman, and I'm proud
of her. ... She's going to be up and around in the next six to eight
weeks.''
   Mrs. Dukakis walked for the first time Saturday morning, and
Dukakis said her hip, where doctors removed bone grafts to place in
her back, was ``very painful'' and would be that way for four or
five days.
   Mrs. Dukakis' surgery on Friday was to replace two herniated
discs which doctors said, if uncorrected, could have led to
paralysis.
   The Massachusetts governor cited his wife's medical problem in
his appeal for family values, saying crises such as these make a
person ``think even more about things that are very precious to us.
... One of those things is family.''
   He cited the Cooper River clean-up in stressing that the
environment would be a budget priority in his administration.
   ``Is it going to be Star Wars or a clean ocean?'' he said,
referring to President Reagan's nuclear defense initiative.
</TEXT>
