<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Blast     06-04 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Blast,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Explosion at Regiment Headquaters Follows Bombing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-South Africa-Angola</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion shook the
headquarters building of a volunteer regiment hours after South
Africa's deadliest bombing in more than a year, police said Saturday.
   Police reported that an explosive device on the ground floor of
the South African Irish Regiment headquarters in downtown
Johannesburg went off at 11:18 p.m. Friday. That was 10 hours after
a bomb in the city of Roodeport killed four people and injured 19.
   No one was injured and damage was slight at the offices of the
regiment, a volunteer citizens' force connected to the South African
Defense Force.
   Police said they were not sure what type of explosive was used,
but were investigating the possibility it was a Soviet-made limpet
mine.
   A limpet mine exploded at lunchtime Friday in Roodeport, west of
Johannesburg. That bomb had been placed in a trash can at the city's
busiest intersection.
   Officials blamed the African National Congress, which has waged a
bombing and sabotage campaign to topple the white-controlled
government since the mainly-black anti-apartheid organization was
banned in 1961.
   The ANC does not comment on individual bombings, but said in a
statement from Lusaka, Zambia, Friday, ``The month of June must be a
period of united and decisive popular offensive'' against the
government.
   By South African law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially
segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in
national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
