<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Bird     06-04 0180</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Bird,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rare Bird From Siberia Draws Birdwatchers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTH RONALDSAY, Orkney Islands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of birdwatchers
have gathered in this small island off the Scottish coast for a
glimpse of a rare visitor that is believed to have traveled 6,000
miles from Siberia.
   ``The bird is most probably a Pallas's Rosefinch, which has never
been recorded in Britain before,'' said Eric Meek, an official of
the Royal Society for the Protection of Birds.
   The finch, which looks like a large, brightly colored sparrow,
summers in Siberia and winters in southern China and Japan.
   British birdwatchers are informed about the sighting of unusual
species by a telephone service named Birdline.
   ``More than 300 birdwatchers have come in and we are expecting
others,'' said Meek.
   The bird probably was helped along by recent easterly winds, said
Kevin Woodbridge, the bird observatory warden on North Ronaldsay, an
island two miles long and three miles wide 55 miles off Scotland's
north coast.
   He said a rarely seen Spanish sparrow, also possibly from eastern
Asia, was spotted on the island earlier this week.
</TEXT>
