<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 1919EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-NewmanCamp     06-04 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Newman Camp,0532</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paul Newman Enthusiastic about Opening of Camp for Sick Children</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto HF1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA STOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASHFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Paul Newman reflected on his new camp
for seriously ill children Saturday, saying the charitable venture
has helped him regain the enthusiasm of his youth.
   ``I'm pretty cool,'' Newman said during a 35-minute interview
with The Associated Press at the camp. ``I've seen a lot. I've been
through a lot. I lost my cool today ... I recaptured the enthusiasm
of my youth. This is awesome.''
   The Hole in the Wall Gang Camp, a $17 million project including
the camp facilities and an endowment, was initiated by Newman in
1986 and is scheduled to open for children this month.
   Newman's food company, Newman's Own Inc., donated $7 million to
the camp. He raised another $7 million from donations. A.E.
Hotchner, a business partner and close friend, said Saturday that
another $3 million is needed to complete the endowment for the camp.
   While the fund-raising continues, Newman is defending against a
lawsuit by a Westport delicatessan owner who claims he was promised
8 percent of the stock from the food company. The plaintiff's lawyer
accused Newman in court in Bridgeport Friday of misrepresenting a
profit-mkaing food company as a charity. Newman dismissed the
allegations as being without merit.
   ``And the money going to the lawyers could have been used for a
more productive purpose, like giving an ambulance to a hospital,''
he said.
   Newman, an Academy Award-winning actor and race car driver, was
at times quiet, at times exuberant as he talked about the camp
before private dedication ceremonies.
   ``This (camp) may ultimately be the champ,'' he said of his
achievements. ``I don't know ... it just depends on how it goes.''
   The camp, nestled in the woods of northeastern Connecticut, is
free for children with life-threatening diseases, ages 7 to 17.
Newman said there is still room for more kids.
   Located on about 300 acres, the camp is modeled after a frontier
logging town of the old Wild West.
   It will have horseback riding, boating, a baseball field, tennis
courts, a gymnasium, dining hall and spacious cabins with sitting
rooms and front porches. Golf carts are available for transportation
around the camp.
   Newman grew quiet as he talked about one young boy who was
featured in one of the camp's first promotions.
   ``I visited him in Boston,'' Newman said. ``He didn't make it.
All he wanted to do was toast marshmallows.''
   The camp's name was the one used for a gang of outlaws in the
movie, ``Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid,'' which starred Newman
and Robert Redford.
   ``I prize irreverance,'' Newman said of his choice for the name.
   Newman said he wanted to give the ill children a sense of
unpressured time through the camp.
   ``You know, time is the major ingredient that gives you the
opportunity to leave a mark,'' he said. ``And that's the least of
what these kids have. They've never been given the gift of time.
It's always living on the edge for them.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
