<DOCNO> AP880604-0173 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 1941EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Media     06-04 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Media,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinistas Close Down Another Radio Newscast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Saturday announced it
has shut down another radio newscast for broadcasting ``false
information'' in violation of communication laws.
   The Interior Ministry said the privately owned Radio
Corporacion's ``Ten on the Dot'' news program was ordered closed
Friday night for eight days for broadcasting an item from an
international news agency that the ministry claimed was false.
   The newscast reported the leftist Sandinista government
``admitted it had assassinated'' Jorge Salazar, a leader of an
anti-government business group, and Moises Mondragon, a rebel who
had sought government amnesty.
   Salazar, vice president of the Private Enterprise Superior
Coordinating Council, was killed during a gunfight involving police
Nov. 17, 1980, in what authorities at the time claimed was an
attempt to smuggle firearms into Nicaragua.
   Mondragon's body was found near the Honduran border last year and
he had been shot. Officials have not publicly commented on the
circumstances surrounding his death.
   ``Ten on the Dot'' was the only privately run news program on the
air since Wednesday, when the government closed down ``Six on the
Dot,'' another Radio Corporacion newscast, and Catholic Radio's
``Church'' program for 10 days, both also for allegedly broadcasting
false information.
   The ``Six on the Dot'' and ``Church'' items that the government
objected to were reports that Felix Garcia Hernandez, a rebel leader
also known as Commander Alfa-Lima, had not surrendered as the
Sandinistas claimed but had been kidnapped.
   Catholic Radio is operated by by the Roman Catholic Church.
</TEXT>
