<DOCNO> AP880604-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 1957EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChimneySweeps     06-04 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chimney Sweeps,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chimney Sweeps Trading Sooty Image for High-Tech Trade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mary Poppins wouldn't recognize today's
chimney sweeps. They carry high-tech breathing masks, power tools
and even video cameras, said an organizer of a weekend convention of
chimney sweeps here.
   Gone are the long-stick brushes and literary images of young boys
with soot-smudged cheeks and long black coats climbing on rooftops,
said Clint Bernard, president of the North Carolina Guild of
Professional Chimney Sweeps.
   The country's estimated 5,500 sweeps are getting serious about
their business, and they want people to know it.
   ``We're trying to get away from the cutesy image,'' Bernard said
at the Charlotte hotel where chimney sweeps from 11 states were
gathered for the guild's ninth annual convention. ``(People) should
be looking for credentials _ not somebody wearing a top hat and
tails and looking like they walked out of a Dickens novel.''
   The top-hat-and-tails image hearkens to 19th century Europe, when
sweeps wore the fancy garb to distinguish themselves as masters of
their craft, Bernard said.
   The four-day convention, which attracted about 180 sweeps from as
far away as Texas and New York, runs through Sunday with seminars,
speeches and a trade show where merchants displayed the latest in
chimney cleaning devices.
   Chimney sweeps avoid the rooftop settings where actor Dick Van
Dyke, playing a sweep, danced in the movie ``Mary Poppins,'' Bernard
said. Instead, they generally clean chimneys through the fireplace,
using brushes attached to polyurethane expandable poles.
   They also wear special fireproof jackets, shirts and hats and don
full-face respiratory masks when needed to avoid inhaling clouds of
soot, he said.
   About half own closed-circuit video cameras, which are extended
on long poles into the flue to peer into corners and detect other
problem spots a sweep cannot see, Bernard said.
   Electric rotor tools with whirling discs and high-powered vacuums
help finish the job, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
