<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 2016EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AtlanticBeach     06-04 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Atlantic Beach,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Atlantic Beach May Lose Town Hall, Other Property In Settlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC BEACH, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This coastal community may lose its
town hall and other property to foreclosure because it can't afford
to pay off a $140,000 settlement to the daughter of a man killed by
town police four years ago.
   ``I've never heard of a situation like this,'' said Deputy
Secretary of State John Stokes.
   Donnie Riggins, 20, was shot at a restaurant in 1984 by a
part-time town police officer running to catch a suspect smoking a
marijuana cigarette. The death was ruled accidental, but the town
agreed last year to pay Riggins' daughter $140,000 in an
out-of-court settlement. The decision came just moments before a
federal court was to hear a wrongful death lawsuit.
   The town had no liability insurance at the time of the shooting.
   After paying the first three installments totaling $15,000, the
town fell behind on a court-mandated schedule. A $50,000 payment was
due Aug. 2, 1987, but attorneys for Riggins' daughter, Tyanna M.
Vaught, aged 3 at the time of the shooting, said the town has not
paid.
   In January, U.S. District Judge C. Weston Houck ordered the town
to put up its property as collateral. That includes the town hall,
community center and fire station.
   Lawyers for Riggins' daughter said they will begin foreclosure on
the property within two weeks. Attorney Fayrell Furr Jr. said Friday
he will seek foreclosure unless the town pays the balance of the
settlement _ $125,000.
   ``It's imminent,'' said attorney John Leiter, who also represents
the little girl. ``The family doesn't want to cause Atlantic Beach
any undue hardship. They're just asking Atlantic Beach to live up
the agreement reached in court.''
   Mayor Joe Montgomery was reluctant to discuss the debt, but he
said he believes Atlantic Beach won't lose any property.
   ``It's highly unprobable we'll lose anything because of the
options we have,'' Montgomery said. He declined to say what the
options were, except that they didn't involve a tax increase.
   A council member who said she did not know of Montgomery's plans,
Sullivan said no other funds have been available since the town was
able to make the $15,000 payment through property tax revenues.
   ``If we had the money, we would have paid,'' Fannie Sullivan said.
   With a per capita income in 1983 of $4,553, Atlantic Beach is one
of the poorest towns in the state.
   Current appraised values weren't available for the community
center or the single-story brick town hall, which also holds the
police department. The community center was estimated in 1986 to be
worth $42,000.
</TEXT>
