<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Soviet     06-04 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Soviet,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church of England Clergyman Says Soviets Rejected His Visa
Application</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Millenium</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Church of England clergyman who publishes
information about the state of religion in communist countries said
Saturday he had been refused a visa to the Soviet Union for the
fifth time.
   The Rev. Michael Bourdeaux said he was barred from taking
pilgrims to the 1,000th anniversary celebrations of the founding of
Christianity in Russia which start Sunday.
   ``It (refusal of visa) makes one call into question whether the
reforms in the Soviet Union are as genuine as they appear to be on
the surface,'' Bourdeaux told Independent Radio News.
   Bourdeaux, 54, who studied at Moscow State University in 1959-60,
founded the Keston College Center for the Study of Religion and
Communism near London in 1969. The center publishes frequent
information on communist persecution of religious believers.
   Bourdeaux was awarded the 1984 Templeton Prize for Progress in
Religion, founded by Sir John M. Templeton, a multimillionaire,
U.S.-born investment counselor who lives in Nassau, Bahamas.
   Archbishop of Canterbury Robert Runcie, spiritual head of the
Anglican state church, flew to Moscow on Saturday with a party of
British churchmen to attend the ceremonies.
   Speaking to reporters at London's Heathrow Airport, Runcie said
Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev's policy of glasnost, or openness,
is in part responsible for the extent of the celebrations.
   ``It's something that is deep in the Russian spirit. The whole
history of Russia is impregnated with Christianity,'' he said.
   ``But it would not be taking place on this scale and it would not
be taking place with an element of participation from the general
public and indeed from state officials, if there were not a new
policy,'' he added.
</TEXT>
