<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Victim'sCash     06-04 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Victim's Cash,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>80-Year-Old Woman Killed, $99,000 Left In Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 80-year-old woman who was killed in her
apartment may have been victimized by robbers seeking cash she
wouldn't put in banks, but her assailants didn't find $99,000 left
at the scene, authorities say.
   Julia Menoni's body was found May 25 in her suburban Highwood
apartment, next to a boarding house she owned, police said Friday.
   The widow had been stabbed in the chest and abdomen, her throat
had been slashed and she had suffered severe trauma to the head,
said Highwood Police Chief Forrest Grandi.
   ``She was known to keep money around,'' Grandi said, adding that
she may have been killed because she refused to reveal where the
cash was hidden or because she recognized her assailants.
   Police found the $99,000 in $10, $20, $50 and $100 bills in the
apartment.
   ``There were several purses hanging on a bedroom door knob, with
clothing hung over the door,'' the chief said. ``We found some
$20,000 in those purses.
   ``In the living room, we found $46,000 in a tea cannister. We
found more cash under the kitchen sink in coffee and tea
cannisters.''
   ``She was a trusting little old lady,'' said Lake County Coroner
Barbara Richardson. ``Police tried several times to get her to put
her money in banks.''
   Grandi said evidence indicates two men were the killers.
   Grandi said it was doubtful the killers got much money.
   ``Maybe they got a couple hundred dollars _ some money that was
under a tablecloth,'' he said.
</TEXT>
