<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Meese-Posters     06-04 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meese-Posters,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Ticket, Arrest Those Posting ``Meese Is A Pig'' Signs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least eight members of an informal group
distributing ``Meese is a Pig'' posters have been ticketed or
arrested in the past month for posting the signs critical of the
attorney general, an organizer of the project said Saturday.
   The signs aimed at Edwin Meese III read ``Experts Agree! Meese is
a Pig,'' and have appeared around the Washington area on traffic
signal boxes, fences, buildings and in public transportation areas.
   Organizer Mark Andersen, 28, of Arlington, Va., said about 60
people, many of them punk rock musicians and their friends, are
involved in the project.
   He said the informal group objects to Meese's law enforcement and
civil rights policies and believes his conduct in the Iran-Contra
investigation and his dealings with scandal-plagued Wedtech Corp.
are grounds for ouster.
   He said the group is voicing its opposition to Meese ``with
creativity and with humor.''
   Four people were arrested in Arlington for posting signs on
county property, and four others have been ticketed in the District
of Columbia in the past month for their role in posting the
anti-Meese signs, police officials confirmed.
   Andersen said Secret Service officers followed him and pulled him
over for driving a car with faulty brake lights in mid-May after he
picked up some poster supplies left in a parking lot.
   Secret Service spokesman Richard Adams said the department's
officers have the same rights as District of Columbia police to stop
traffic violators, but he had no information on Andersen's case.
   Andersen said he subsequently was contacted about the posters by
the FBI, and has asked the bureau to submit its questions to him in
writing.
   ``I can't understand it at all other than that they're trying to
intimidate me,'' he said.
   FBI spokesman Harry Mount had no comment.
   Both the posters and T-shirts bearing the same slogan are part of
a local grass-roots effort to bring about Meese's resignation,
Andersen said.
   Common Concerns, a Washington bookstore, has sold about 150 of
the T-shirts in the past two months, said bookstore employee Linda
Ellis.
</TEXT>
