<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FirestoneVote     06-04 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Firestone Vote,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Des Moines URW Local Approves Master Contract</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN P. ROSENFELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rubberworkers in Des Moines approved a
proposed contract with Firestone Inc. on Saturday, putting it close
to ratification in the final weekend of voting on a pact that
affects about 4,700 workers in six states.
   One union official said that after years of concessions, ``we're
getting something back.''
   The tentative agreement ended a week-long strike against
Firestone that began May 15, and it was in line with a master
contract negotiated by the United Rubber Workers union and the
Goodyear Tire & Rubber Co. on May 17.
   Votes were scheduled Sunday by URW members at Firestone plants at
Akron, Ohio, and Noblesville, Ind., and approval by either one would
result in ratification of the three-year pact, said Curt Brown, a
spokesman at URW headquarters at Akron.
   Ron Smiley, president of Local 310 at Des Moines, said Saturday's
approval already gave the contract support of a majority of the URW
members working for Firestone. But union rules also require approval
by a majority of the locals.
   Earlier, the pact was approved by locals at Decatur, Ill., and
Russellville, Ark., but it was turned down at Oklahoma City.
   In Des Moines, the proposal was approved by a 398-258 vote at a
plant with more than 1,400 workers, Smiley said.
   Smiley said there was some dissension in Iowa because even with
raises, some workers would not catch up with past concessions.
   However, he said: ``I'm glad it's over. It's not a bad package.''
   The Iowa workers had made wage and benefit concessions to keep
their factory open in 1982, 1985 and 1987.
   ``Now we've reversed that trend and we're getting a little
something back,'' Smiley said.
   He said that with employment climbing at Des Moines, Japan's
Bridgestone Corp. taking over Firestone and a new contract
apparently approved, ``we're in good shape.''
   An average Firestone worker at the six plants earns $12.50 an
hour, according to the union. The proposed contract with Firestone
would provide a 25-cent-an-hour increase, but it would be considered
an advance that would be deducted from future cost-of-living raises
in increments of no more than 10 cents a year.
</TEXT>
