<1ST_LINE>u i AM-LebanonHostages 1stLd-Writethru a0695 06-04 0768</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon Hostages, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0695,0788</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Reports Foreign Hostages Held In South Beirut School</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to CORRECT that school and recent fighting
in south Beirut and Hezbollah means Party of God. Pickup 4th graf
pvs ``The Mail...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Sunday newspaper reported the 18 foreign hostages
kidnapped in Lebanon are being held in a former school in south
Beirut and it carried a front-page photograph of a building it said
was the school.
   The Mail on Sunday said the hostages, including nine Americans
and three Britons, were taken there during recent fighting in the
area between gunmen of the pro-Iranian Hezbollah organization and
Shiite Amal militiamen.
   Hezbollah, or Party of God, is believed holding the captives.
   The Mail on Sunday attributed its report to Amal officers it did
not identify.
   In other developments:
   _ London's Guardian newspaper said the United States is holding
talks with Hezbollah leaders in Lebanon and directly with Iranian
representatives in Geneva in another effort to gain the release of
the hostages. It based its report on information from unidentified
political sources in Beirut.
   _ The British Foreign Office said Saturday it has proposed paying
Iran the equivalent of more than $3.2 million as compensation in a
settlement over damages to British diplomatic buildings in Iran and
Iran's Embassy in London.
   A Foreign Office spokesman, who was not identified in line with
government practice, said the proposal is to be discussed at a
meeting in London starting Wednesday but the talks will not cover
the question of the British hostages in Lebanon.
   Of the nine American captives, Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press, has been held the longest.
He was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   Many previous published reports on where the hostages were being
held and about talks to gain their release turned out to be
unfounded.
   The Mail on Sunday said the captives are being guarded at the
school by high ranking Hezbollah officers supervised by Iranian
Revolutionary Guards.
   It said Amal militiamen have infiltrated Hezbollah and quoted one
Amal fighter as describing the school where it said the hostages are
held.
   The newspaper said militiaman Abu Abass was interrogated by
Hezbollah members at the building, the former Azariyeh primary
school.
   Reporters in Beirut said they knew of an Azariyeh primary school
located in the southern suburbs of Beirut but they did not how it is
being used.
   The newspaper quoted Abass as saying, ``The tunnels and
passageways have recently been excavated and a ventilation system
has been installed. The whole area has been partitioned into tiny
cells.''
   Abass also said a doctor occasionally goes to the school,
accompanied by guards.
   The Mail on Sunday quoted other Amal officers as saying: ``We
know they (the hostages) are there and that they are alive. But any
attempt to take them by force will only result in bloodshed.''
   The dim front-page photo showed what appeared to be part of a
one-story building with sandbags at strategic points.
   In its article, the Guardian said the purported talks in Lebanon
and Geneva were not expected to produce quick results for the
American hostages, but to ``accelerate'' as the American
presidential elections approach in November.
   It said the United States is thought to be seeking a ``package
deal'' that also would involve Church of England envoy Terry Waite
who was in Lebanon trying to arrange the release of the foreign
hostages when he disappeared on Jan. 20, 1987.
   The Foreign Office spokesman said the British proposal on
settlement of damages to diplomatic buildings was first made in May
1987. Britain has said repeatedly that it will make no deals to gain
the release of the hostages.
   The spokesman said the Iranian representatives at Wednesday's
meeting will only be considering the questions of damage to Iran's
Embassy at London's Princes Gate, which caught fire when British
commandos stormed it in 1980 to end a hostage siege, and damage to
British diplomatic offices in Tehran and elsewhere in Iran.
   British government buildings and the British Embassy were damaged
by mobs in 1978, 1979, and 1980.
   ``We want compensation for the damage to our property in Iran and
we want to ensure that the necessary repairs are done to the Princes
Gate property, which is a health hazard and an eyesore,'' the
spokesman said.
   He said under the proposal, Britain would pay Iran about 1.8
million pounds ($3.24 million) and Iran would pay Britain about
about 900,000 pounds ($1.62 million).
   A series of diplomatic explusions has left just one British
official in Tehran and one Iranian official in London.
</TEXT>
