<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DredgeSpill     06-04 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dredge Spill,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dredge Sinks In Channel, Oil Slick Threatens Beaches</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FERNANDINA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dredge vessel sank in a river
channel Saturday and was leaking thousands of gallons of oil that
spread over more than a mile, threatening beaches and sensitive
marshlands, officials said.
   The 168-foot vessel was dredging the St. Mary's River channel,
which straddles the Georgia-Florida line, when waves crashed over
its bow causing it to flood and sink, said Capt. Robert O'Pezio of
the U.S. Coast Guard, the on-scene coordinator.
   ``The people on board ended up in the water,'' said Dave Kelly, a
Coast Guard damage control officer. ``They didn't have time to get
off.''
   Seven crew members from the dredge were plucked from the water as
it sank near the entrance to the 50-foot deep channel, he said. The
ship held 40,000 gallons of diesel fuel and was leaking about 500
gallons an hour.
   John Spendlove, a crewmember aboard a Navy tug, was injured in
the rescue effort and was in satisfactory condition at University
Hospital in Jacksonville, said Judi Skelton, a hospital spokeswoman.
   From a helicopter, an oil slick could be seen drifting into the
Atlantic Ocean and pushing southward about a mile from Fernandina
Beach, O'Pezio said. The slick extended at least a mile from the
dredge and was at least a mile wide.
   Choppy seas were breaking the fuel into streaks, which drifted
two to three miles west into the St. Marys River in the direction of
the sensitive Cumberland Sound and Amelia River wetland areas. No
fuel appears to have entered those areas yet, O'Pezio said.
   To prevent the fuel from spreading further, the owner of the
dredge hired an oil containment contractor to erect floating
containment booms at the entrances of creeks and tributaries
extending from the channel.
   Ships will be unable to get into or out of the Port of Fernandina
or Kings Bay Naval Submarine Base until the debris of the sunken
dredge is pinpointed, said O'Pezio, who declined to speculate how
long that might take.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
