<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PipelineSpill 1stLd-Writethru a0633 06-04 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pipeline Spill, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0633,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cleanup Crews Siphoning Heating Oil Spill</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with details of cleanup, comments from
officials; no pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WAUWATOSA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crews with siphon hoses worked along a
creek Saturday to clean up some 128,000 gallons of oil that
officials said caused no serious environmental damage.
   Bob Wimmer, assistant fire chief in the Milwaukee suburb of
Wauwatosa, said the heating oil poured from a two-foot hole in an
underground pipe for 18 minutes before pumps were shut down. The
leak was discovered early Saturday.
   The leak's cause was unclear, Wimmer said.
   Residents who reported an oil odor were told it carried no health
hazard. Dean Kelley, spill coordinator for the state Department of
Natural Resources, said the fumes were the same as those when fuel
is being fed to a dwelling's furnace tank.
   Oil traveled about five miles through Underwood Creek into the
Menomonee River, a tributary of Lake Michigan. Authorities said no
oil reached the lake harbor.
   Underwood Creek is lined with concrete, which should prevent
contamination to drinking water, ground water or private wells and
would protect wildlife from serious damage, said Doug Hoskins, a
conservation warden with the state Department of Natural Resources.
   The spill was ``one of the bigger ones we've had in the area for
some time, if not the biggest,'' Hoskins said.
   Fish in Underwood Creek primarily are small minnows and chubs,
Hoskins said. He said he had heard waterfowl were nesting along the
banks but he found no injured or dead birds.
   ``I think we got off lucky,'' Hoskins said.
   Kelley said temporary dams 100 feet upstream and 100 feet
downstream from the spill site on Underwood Creek would contain the
bulk of the oil and simplify the use of siphon hoses to pump the
fluid into storage tanks.
</TEXT>
