<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 2221EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-MineDisaster 6thLd-Writethru a0680 06-04 1024</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mine Disaster, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0680,1061</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rescuers Intensify Search After Six Miners Pulled Out Alive</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 15 grafs to UPDATE with survivor reportedly saying
rescuers had made radio contact on day of blast. Pickup 12th graf
pvs ``Another survivor...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BORKEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers intensified the search
Saturday for survivors of a powerful mine blast after rescuing six
men who survived 65 hours in an underground air pocket.
   The rescue came with the help of a television crew's microphone
that picked up tapping sounds when it was lowered into a mineshaft.
   A West German television station early Sunday quoted one of the
six survivors as saying rescuers unknowingly made radio contact with
them hours after the explosion on Wednesday.
   The rescuers apparently thought the six were with the teams
searching for 57 people missing after the blast, the television said.
   All 57 had been given up for dead. Late Saturday, a 37th body was
recovered. Fourteen other miners were still missing.
   Officials said the miners were trapped about 500 feet underground
in an air pocket away from carbon monoxide estimated at 50 times the
level fatal to humans.
   ``It's a miracle,'' said Peter-Carl Ruehland, a spokesman for
Preussen Elektra, the company that owns the coal mine.
   Heinz Cramer, a spokesman for the mine owner, said the men were
in an area ``which was about to run out of oxygen, and time was
running out when they were found.''
   Another survivor, mine supervisor Thomas Gepperth, said:
``Everybody was making their last wills and testaments. I told them
they didn't have to.''
   Gepperth saved the men by leading them away from the carbon
monoxide gas, the supervisor told Hesse state television.
   ZDF television said a Turkish survivor, Ahmet Batkan, told the
network the radio contact occurred hours after the blast Wednesday.
   ``The buried miners had given their position on a radio,'' the
television reported Batkan as saying. ``They were then told not to
use the radio again, in order not to disturb other signals.''
   ``At first they stopped (using the radio), and when they tried
again they were not able to make contact,'' the television said.
   Officials could not be immediately reached to comment on the
television report.
   But on the day of the accident, Borken Mayor Bernd Hessler told
reporters of radio contact with a group of miners who reported
themselves uninjured, but other officials said later in the day that
the contact was made with other rescuers.
   Another survivor, also interviewed on state television but not
identified by name, described hearing drilling on Friday, followed
by silence.
   ``That was really agonizing, because nothing more was going on up
there. You start thinking, `Have they forgotten us or something?
Maybe they're figuring it's not worth it,''' he said.
   Searchers, some with tears in their eyes, broke into applause as
the exhausted but otherwise unhurt survivors reached the surface.
   The dramatic rescue sparked hopes for finding more survivors
inside the Stolzenbach mine.
   ``It's a faint hope, but a supervisor said there were tracks of
two people who may also be in an area where they may have
survived,'' said Cramer, a board member of Preussen Elektra. ``We're
stepping up the search.''
   ``You can certainly call Gepperth's actions something special. He
reacted in exactly the right way,'' Cramer added.
   He said about 200 workers were involved in the search in Borken,
a town of 15,000 people 70 miles northeast of Frankfurt.
   Family members who rushed to the scene embraced the five West
Germans and one Turk. Fourteen Turkish immigrant workers were among
the 57 trapped miners.
   The six survivors later paused for photographers but told
reporters not to ask them any questions.
   They were examined at nearby hospitals, then allowed to go home.
   Cramer told reporters the six were found in a dead-end tunnel
about 10 feet wide and eight feet high.
   The rescue came after crews drilled an air shaft in the east
field of the mine. Officials said that carbon monoxide levels
registered lower there than in the north field, where they were 50
times higher than the amount lethal for humans.
   Rescuers had believed that all 13 miles of underground shafts
were filled with such high levels of carbon monoxide that no one
could be found alive.
   But Friday night, rescuers detected tapping sounds through the
air shaft and tried to verify them with a stethoscope. A television
cameraman suggested lowering a microphone, which picked up the
trapped men saying, ``They have drilled a hole.''
   Early Saturday the microphone detected regular tapping sounds.
   After more than three hours of digging, the rescue workers broke
into the air pocket and found the men.
   Some victims' relatives criticized the rescue efforts, saying
they believed the retrieval of bodies had been given priority over
the search for survivors. They also said they could not understand
why workers didn't think to use a microphone earlier.
   Company and state officials staunchly defended the rescue
operation.
   When the group felt the shock wave of the blast Wednesday, Cramer
said, they ran toward an exit. But Gepperth, 36, a veteran miner and
trained rescuer, realized they were running into high concentrations
of deadly carbon monoxide when he saw another man staggerering.
   Gepperth turned the group in the other direction and instructed
them to be as calm as possible to conserve oxygen, Cramer said.
   Many of the confirmed fatalities died of carbon monoxide
poisoning.
   In addition to Gepperth and Batkan, company officials identified
the survivors as Egon Dehn, Helmut Gesner, Heinz Roese and Wilfried
Doench. They range in age from 21 to 36.
   A man who identified himself as Dehn's brother-in-law, said the
six men had kept up their hopes by talking about the ``Miracle of
Lengede.''
   That was a reference to a 1963 mining disaster in the Lower
Saxony iron ore mine of Lengede, when 11 miners were found alive two
weeks after water flooded the mine. Twenty-nine miners died in that
accident.
   The Borken explosion is the worst West German mining accident
since 299 men died in 1962 at the Luisenthal mine in Saarland state
along the border with France.
</TEXT>
