<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 2243EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CrazyHorse     06-04 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crazy Horse,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ceremony Marks 40th Anniversary Of Work On Mountain Monument</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET BROKAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CRAZY HORSE, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Korczak Ziolkowski died before he
completed carving a Black Hills mountain into a likeness of Sioux
Indian leader Crazy Horse, but Ziolkowski's widow, Ruth, helped to
continue his work as she oversaw Saturday's ceremony marking the
40th anniversary of the project's start.
   Three explosions removed rock from Thunderhead Mountain in
western South Dakota as part of the ceremony, though the first
charge detonated earlier than planned.
   The final two blasts were set off as scheduled by Mrs. Ziolkowski
and Gov. George Mickelson.
   The unexpected early blast ripped rock from the mountain as
Mickelson began to deliver a speech to a crowd of several hundred
people who gathered for the event. ``The power of a voice,'' he
joked after the explosion.
   Mrs. Ziolkowski said the first blast was set off prematurely by
static electricity. No one was injured by the detonation.
   Ziolkowski died in 1982 at age 74, but his wife and eight of
their 10 children have continued working to shape the mountain.
   Crazy Horse helped lead the Indians who defeated Gen. George
Custer at the 1876 battle of the Little Big Horn. But after he and
1,000 starving followers were forced to surrender, he was killed by
a soldier's bayonet in 1877.
   When completed, a statue 563 feet tall and 641 feet long will
show Crazy Horse astride a horse and pointing east to the Plains.
Ziolkowski said it will depict Crazy Horse's answer to a white man
who asked what had become of his lands. Crazy Horse pointed over his
horse's head and replied, ``My lands are where my dead lie buried.''
   Some Sioux leaders asked Ziolkowski to create the monument. ``My
fellow chiefs and I would like the white man to know the red man had
great heroes, too,'' Chief Henry Standing Bear wrote in a letter
asking Ziolkowski to carve the monument.
   The explosions Saturday removed rock at what will become the
Indian's elbow, his pointing finger and the horse's mane.
   Private donations and entrance fees are financing the Crazy Horse
project. The Crazy Horse Memorial Foundation, which purchased the
mountain from the federal government, collects the money to keep the
project going.
   The mountain is beginning to take on the rough form of
Ziolkowski's vision as about 8.2 million tons of rock have been
removed. Mrs. Ziolkowski said she and her family will work in the
coming decades to complete the carving.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
