<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DesertAliens 3rdLd-Writethru a0703 06-04 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Desert Aliens, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0703,0542</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede Marana</HEAD>
<HEAD>36 Mexicans Found Wandering In Desert; 3 Dehydrated</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with all 36 treated and released;
picking up 7th graf pvs ``The Mexicans...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR H. ROTSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty-six undocumented Mexican aliens were
found Saturday wandering without food or water in the searing Sonora
desert north of Tucson after two of them came to a ranch seeking
help, authorities said.
   The 35 men and one woman, whom officials said had been walking
four days since crossing the border onto the Tohono O'odham Indian
Reservation, were brought to Northwest Hospital by Border Patrol bus.
   The 36 were in generally good condition, said nursing supervisor
Cheryl Lanier. Three men were treated for dehydration, and the rest
were simply given drinks and a chance to cool off in the hospital's
cafeteria, said emergency room services director Ardis Waite.
   After treatment, all 36 were returned to the custody of the
Border Patrol, Ms. Lanier said.
   Those in good physical condition who wanted to return to Mexico
would be allowed to do so voluntarily, said Border Patrol
Supervisory Agent Clyde J. Benzenhoefer.
   The Mexicans, ranging in age from 18 to about 50, all came from
the state of Oaxaca and crossed probably from the town of San
Miguel, Sonora, south of Sells, Ariz., Benzenhoefer said.
   He said they had told officials they were en route to look for
farm work, probably near Phoenix, had been traveling mostly at night
and had run out of water Friday afternoon or Saturday morning.
   Benzenhoefer said the group was found about 3 p.m. He said the
group had located runoff water near the Silverbell branch mine
operated by the Asarco Co., about 60 miles north of the Mexican
border and about 20 miles northwest of Tucson, where the temperature
reached 108 degrees Saturday.
   ``They had just found it when we got to 'em. Apparently they
would have kept on going if we hadn't found them,'' he said.
   ``They were probably in pretty bad shape. I would imagine it was
110 degrees out in the desert today,'' Benzenhoefer said.
   He said all but three men had crossed in one group. He said the
three came across the rest on Saturday.
   Both groups were out of water, and two of the three went to a
rancher about four or five miles from the mine, and asked for help.
The rancher notified the Pima County sheriff's authorities, who in
turn called the Border Patrol, Benzenhoefer said.
   He said none of the Mexicans had acknowledged having a coyote, or
paid guide who smuggles undocumented aliens across the border.
   ``None of them have identified him yet if they did. I'm sure they
did have somebody that guided them across,'' Benzenhoefer said, and
added that it was possible one of the group could be a coyote. He
also said a coyote ``might have cut off from the group'' upon seeing
the Border Patrol approaching.''
   He said the route was a common one for illegal border crossings.
   Last summer, U.S. Border Patrol agents said about 70 bodies since
1980 had been found in the Sonora desert area.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
