<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FatalFire     06-04 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fatal Fire,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mother And Two Children Killed In Newark House Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McMAHON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A distraught woman killed two of her children
by setting fire to their bedroom and later died herself from the
blaze Saturday afternoon, fire officials said.
   Newark Fire Director Stanley Kossup said Michelle Noble, 26,
tried but failed to trap her two other children in the 2{-story wood
frame house.
   Neighbors told investigators the woman had a history of mental
problems and engaged in frequent arguments with her children.
   ``Somehow she became distraught and made the decision to do what
she did,'' Kossup said.
   One of the children who escaped, 8-year-old Lamarr, told
investigators that his mother set fire to a first-floor bedroom in
the house and restrained her daughters, Lakia Santrice, 5, and
Comfort Nichole, 4.
   The boy told officials that his mother tried to trap him and his
2-year-old sister, Latiffa, in the room, but they escaped.
   After flames engulfed the room, the mother fled outside for a
brief period and then returned to the house's kitchen, the boy said.
   From the boy's account, investigators believe the fire was
started ``with the intent to kill the children,'' Kossup said. The
boy said his mother lay over the two girls to trap them in the room,
according to Kossup.
   Ms. Noble asked her son to give her some materials to help build
a fire, but he gave her some wet papers and ``had the presence of
mind to get his baby sister out of there,'' Kossup said.
</TEXT>
