<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CubanPrisoners     06-04 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuban Prisoners,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Castro Vows to Free Political Prisoners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fidel Castro has said he is ready to free nearly
all the political prisoners in Cuban jails, according to a published
report.
   The New York Times reported in Sunday's editions that Castro sent
a letter to Cardinal John O'Connor, archbishop of the New York
diocese of the Roman Catholic church, saying he would free 385 of
the 429 political prisoners in his jails.
   Archdiocese officials would not discuss the list of prisoners,
the Times said, but State Department officials said Saturday the
list had been passed on to them.
   The group of 385 would be one of the largest freed by Castro in
recent years and U.S. officials say it would be a significant step
in improving human rights in Cuba, the Times reported.
   The 44 who would not be released have been in prison since
shortly after Castro took power in 1959 and have resisted political
indoctrination, the Times said. Castro said the 44 were convicted of
``grave and dangerous violations.''
   It is likely to be several weeks before any of the others are
released, the Times said, because Castro said he won't let them go
until the United States agrees to accept them as refugees. Congress
requires that records be studied and prisoners interviewed to make
sure each prisoner is a victim of political persecution and not a
common criminal.
</TEXT>
