<HEAD>Five-Year-Old Street Preacher Suspended Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARION, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 5-year-old street preacher returned to
school Friday after a 10-day suspension only to be suspended again
when he struck a policeman and resumed shouting Bible verses,
officials said.
   McDowell County Sheriff Bob Haynes said Matthew Strode hit Lt.
John Lite in the face during the incident at Eastfield Elementary
School.
   Matthew returned for the last day of class and began preaching
just inside the school's exit gate Friday morning, according to
reports from the sheriff's department and the school.
   Principal Jim Gorst asked the kindergartener to come into the
building, but he refused. Gorst then told the boy he was suspended
and asked Matthew to come with him. The boy continued to preach and
spun away from Gorst when the principal tried to escort him into
the building.
   Meantime, about 300 McDowell County residents went on the Sally
Jessy Raphael TV talk show Friday to vent their frustration with
Matthew and the rest of his family.
   Matthew and his brother, Duffey, 10, have been suspended from
the school five times each. Their 6-year-old sister, Pepper, has
been suspended four times over incidences involving preaching and
refusing to enter the school building when requested by school
officials.
   When the children's father, David Strode, took Duffey back to
school after a suspension May 27, there were two altercations with
protesting parents. The parents gave him a petition with 474
signatures calling for him to stop his children from preaching.
   During the taping of the show at the Marion Community Building,
David Strode drew the biggest response from the audience when he
attacked women.
   ``When God has a message to deliver, he sends a man,'' he said.
``When the devil wants to say something, he sends a Jezebel.''
   The show taped Friday is scheduled to be aired Tuesday.
</TEXT>
