<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 0208EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-EMPSuit     06-04 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-EMP Suit,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judges Refuses To Continue Ban On Military Tests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge on Friday cleared the way for
government testing of a high-powered electrical generator designed
to simulate one of the effects of a nuclear explosion, the Navy
said.
   Navy spokeswoman Lt. Janet Mescus said U.S. District Judge John
Garrett Penn on Friday refused to extend a temporary restraining
order he had issued on Tuesday, a day before testing originally had
been set to begin.
   Following Penn's decision Friday not to extend the restraining
order, Mescus said testing from the Navy's Empress II barge would
begin Monday. The tests are planned for international waters about
15 miles off the Virginia-North Carolina coast.
   Although the Pentagon had scaled down electro-magnetic pulse, or
EMP, research facilities and conducted an environmental assessment
to settle a suit brought by the Foundation on Economic Trends, the
environmental group argued in court that a second study was
necessary.
   The Empress barge is equipped with two diesel generators and a
huge antenna system, capable of sending ``pulses'' of electrical
power into the atmosphere at power levels up to 7 million volts to
test the EMP phenomenon.
   Each pulse lasts only a billionth of a second, and the Navy
maintains the testing will have no effect on human or marine life.
   Electro-magnetic pulse is a powerful wave, or surge, of
electrical energy that is released by a nuclear explosion and which
can travel long distances through the atmosphere or water.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
