price trends</NOTE>
<HEAD>Platinum Rally Reflects Surge In Japanese Demand</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's seemingly insatiable demand for platinum has been
largely responsible for a 25 percent increase in the metal's price
since the year began, and analysts say the rally is likely to
continue.
   Fear of rising inflation has prompted many U.S. investors to
return to the precious metals markets, which they pretty much
abandoned after the October stock market collapse, observers note.
   And the possibility of supply disruptions from South Africa, the
world's leading platinum producer, is never far from the minds of
traders at the New York Mercantile Exchange, where platinum for
near-month delivery has risen from about $500 a troy ounce in early
January to $625 this past week.
   Even without a breakdown in the South African pipeline, ``our
expectations are that primary supplies of platinum will for a
fourth successive year fall short of net demand,'' the London-based
precious-metals refiner Johnson Matthey PLC said in its recently
published annual platinum review.
   The British firm noted a 70 percent leap in Japanese imports of
platinum last year to 1.7 million ounces, or 50 percent of total
demand.
   The surge in Japanese demand corresponded with the dollar's
dramatic decline against the yen, which sent dollar-denominated
platinum to near 10-year-lows, in yen terms, in a country that
prizes platinum more than gold.
   ``Traditionally, the Japanese have looked at platinum the way
the rest of the world looks at gold,'' said Richard Levine, vice
president of Elders Futures Inc.'s precious metals and foreign
exchange group.
   ``Wedding rings in Japan are made of platinum, not gold,'' he
said. ``For one reason or another, platinum always was a desired
metal in Japan.''
   Johnson Matthey noted a huge increase in Japanese purchases of
platinum in the last two months of 1987 as U.S. investors, spooked
by the stock-market crash, moved their money out of precious metals
and into less-risky investments, such as government securities.
   Japanese buying continued apace as the sell-off of precious
metals in the United States sent platinum prices plunging below
$460 an ounce in February, when platinum futures actually traded at
a discount to gold, analysts said.
   New Japanese tax laws making precious metals more appealing than
savings accounts to investors also encouraged Japanese buying of
platinum, experts agree.
   Back in the United States, the calamity that many economists had
predicted last fall failed to materialize. Instead, the economy
appears to be picking up steam, which, combined with sharp
increases in agricultural commodity prices, has been interpreted as
a harbinger of rising inflation.
   The inflation fears have renewed interest in precious metals
among U.S. investors, who traditionally see gold, silver and
platinum as safe havens against rising prices.
   ``I think investors got tired of earning 7 percent or 8 percent
on their riskless investments, particularly when they think
inflation is picking up, and they're taking on a little bit of a
more speculative bent,'' said Jacques Luben, executive director of
investments for the New York-based Platinum Guild International.
   Analysts said the return of U.S. investors to the precious
metals has supported the entire complex. But platinum has responded
most sharply because of the already strong demand from the Far East.
   In addition, the economy's unexpectedly strong showing suggests
growth in industrial demand for platinum, which is used in
automobile pollution-control devices.
   The possibility that South Africa may halt platinum shipments to
the United States if Congress approves tougher trade sanctions also
has underpinned platinum's gains, but most analysts say the threat
is very remote.
   The platinum market, much thinner than the gold market, is
inherently volatile and some analysts warn that platinum's gains
may be overdone.
   ``The very fact that the market has even focused on South Africa
indicates the market is taking the most bullish stance it could
possibly take,'' said George Anagnos, metals analyst for Thomson
McKinnon Securities Inc. in New York.
   ``Some price increase is justified,'' he said, ``but unless this
bullish interpretation pans out in every respect, we're going to be
very vulnerable.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
