<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions June 4-5</NOTE>
<HEAD>October Crash `Can Happen Again,' Former NYSE President Warns</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Any shred of innocence Wall Street may have
retained was lost in last October's crash, leaving stock exchanges
of the future to grapple with challenges their leaders could barely
imagine a few years ago.
   Robert J. Birnbaum, who left the New York Stock Exchange this
past week after serving as its president and chief operating
officer since 1985, warns that ``anything that happened once can
happen again.''
   Birnbaum, 60, is an amiable, self-effacing lawyer and elder
statesman among stock exchange managers. He came to the NYSE after
18 years at the smaller American Stock Exchange, including eight as
its president, giving him an excellent vantage point on the stock
market's recent rocky past and daunting future.
   He will become special counsel in the New York office of Dechert
Price & Rhoads, a large law firm.
   As the ``inside'' manager in charge of day-to-day operations at
the NYSE, Birnbaum lacked the high public profile of John J. Phelan
Jr., the exchange's chairman. In the panicky days of the October
collapse, while Phelan presided over packed news conferences in an
effort to calm the jittery investing public, Birnbaum quietly
worked behind the scenes to restore order to a market that had
veered out of control.
   In an interview last Thursday, his final day at the exchange,
Birnbaum took an inventory of what he had seen and the challenges
that lie ahead for the securities industry.
   One of the stock exchange's most imposing tasks is
technological. To help cope with another potential cataclysm, the
NYSE has to gear up to handle billions of daily trades, Birnbaum
said. The exchange was strained to the breaking point on Oct. 19 by
the plunge in stock prices and an unprecedented volume of trading _
about 600 million shares.
   Birnbaum's successor, 41-year-old Richard A. Grasso, is known
for his expertise with the exchange's computers and communications
systems. He is responsible for upgrades of the systems that
recently gave the Big Board the capacity to manage volume of 600
million shares a day as efficiently as it once handled 200 million.
   But Birnbaum doesn't believe the technological revolution will
eventually create a trading floor populated only by machines,
without the push-and-pull of human interaction.
   ``You don't allow technology alone to decide the type of
marketplace that is best for the United States,'' he insisted.
``You need the interface on the floor.''
   Another huge change that Birnbaum underscored is the growing
involvement of government with the stock exchanges _ especially
after the crash and the recent insider trading scandals. The Reagan
administration appointed a special panel to study the October
debacle and make recommendations, while Congress, the Securities
and Exchange Commission and others have also gotten involved.
   ``It's light-years different from what it used to be; there's a
much more intensive involvement with the government,'' Birnbaum
said. ``You have to touch the bases. (The government) turns slowly
... you have to deal with it delicately and slowly.''
   Birnbaum understands the government perspective on regulation of
the financial markets: He worked as an attorney at the SEC in
Washington from 1961 to 1966 before going to the American Stock
Exchange.
   As NYSE president, Birnbaum tried to convince brokerage firms
that they must regulate themselves, or Washington would step in and
do it for them. He was instrumental in fashioning a package of new
rules for exchange members early last year in response to the
insider trading scandals.
   Birnbaum is a staunch defender, on the other hand, of the NYSE's
``specialist'' system _ which has come under criticism for not
doing more to smoothe out the market during the crash. Specialists
are appointed by exchanges to make markets in individual stocks.
They are charged with ensuring the market is orderly, even if that
means buying and selling equities from their own accounts.
   Reports this past week, first published by the New York Times,
indicated the specialists enjoyed their most profitable year ever
in 1987 despite the crash and yet failed to bolster their capital
reserves to protect themselves against another disaster.
   ``The specialist system was outstanding'' during the crash,
Birnbaum maintained. ``I haven't seen, in my own time in the
business, a system that works better.''
</TEXT>
