<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions June 4-5</NOTE>
<HEAD>Muni Market One of the Bright Spots In the Credit Markets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The municipal bond market has held up well in
recent weeks despite the sharp rise in interest rates, becoming one
of the brighter spots in the credit markets.
   And the buzzword around the marketplace is ``premium.''
   Traders and analysts say several factors have helped support
municipal bond prices while keeping yields down, among them,
continued disenchantment with the stock market, concerns about
future tax increases and a decline in supply.
   ``The municipal market is on a roll, and it is not likely to end
soon,'' according to a recent report by investment bankers John
Nuveen & Co. Inc. ``In each of the last three months, demand has
exceeded supply, and the June outlook is for more of the same.''
   Municipal bonds took a beating last spring due to a resurgence
in interest rates caused by a deteriorating dollar in foreign
exchange. Interest-rate jitters resurfaced this year causing state
and local governments to shy away from issuing more bonds, noted
Neal Attermann, manager of municipal bond research at Kidder
Peabody & Co.
   For the first five months of this year, the volume of issues
from state and local governments totaled about $39.8 billion, down
15 percent from about $46.6 billion the same period a year ago,
according to Securities Data Co.-Bond Buyer, which tracks the
municipal market.
   The data showed the decline largely could be blamed on a drop in
refunding issues, bonds sold for the sole purpose of retiring
earlier debt carrying a higher interest rate. Since rates have
risen, many municipalities saw no point in going to market.
   The volume of refunding issues plunged 53 percent, to about
$13.6 billion during the January-May period from around $29.2
billion last year, Securities Data said.
   Traders, though, are reporting a slight increase in activity
recently. Several new issues this past week alone have come to
market, including $200 million in general obligation bonds from New
York City and a $184 million issue from Georgia. A few others,
including a $1 billion refunding issue from Louisiana, are in the
wings, traders say.
   Still, some analysts predict rising interest rates due to the
economy's apparent growth may continue to keep municipal issuers
out of the market. And at the same time, they say, demand isn't
expected to let up.
   ``Since mid-March demand for municipals has increased steadily,
first on a seasonal basis, due to the approach of April 15, and,
subsequently, because of a growing realization that taxes are
likely to be headed upward, without the creation of any new
shelters,'' the Nuveen noted.
   ``People want to get that tax exemption now,'' added James F.
Lynch, editor of the monthly investor newsletter Lynch Municipal
Bond Advisory.
   Attermann noted that the rising demand and declining supply of
munis have made them more attractive than some Treasury bonds with
comparable maturities.
   For those who are worried that interest rates will go through
the roof, causing their bonds to erode in value, a number of
analysts are recommending investments in ``premium'' bonds. These
bonds sell for above par, or $1,000, but deliver a higher total
return to investors than bonds of similar term purchased at face
value.
   ``The high coupon (rate) of this investment prevents a fast
erosion of principal in a declining market,'' Lynch said.
   Lynch especially recommends premium municipal bonds that have
been ``pre-refunded'' by issuers, meaning borrowers already have
put other securities such as Treasury obligations in trust to
redeem the bonds. Investors, therefore, don't run the risk of
having those bonds ``called,'' or refunded before they mature, he
said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions June 4-5</NOTE>
