<1ST_LINE>a f AM-PurchasingManagers Adv06   06-04 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Purchasing Managers, Adv 06,0489</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 06
^For Release AMs Monday June 6</NOTE>
<HEAD>Economic Growth Contnues, Purchasing Managers Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The economy grew for the 22nd consecutive month
on the strength of new orders in May, according to a survey of
corporate purchasing managers released Sunday.
   The National Association of Purchasing Managers said its index
of economic activity rose to 55.1 percent last month from 54.9
percent in April.
   The index had fallen slightly the first three months of the
year, indicating a slowdown in the pace of economic growth.
   A reading above 50 percent generally indicates economic
expansion, while a reading below that benchmark indicates the
economy is declining, the group says.
   For the first five months of this year, the index has averaged
55.1 percent.
   ``The economy continues to expand at a moderate rate,'' said
Robert J. Bretz, chairman of the purchasing managers' survey
committee.
   ``New orders fueled by robust growth in export orders, increased
at a brisk pace and all but assure the first half of 1988 will end
with a record of modest but healthy economic growth.''
   An increase in new orders, particularly among exporters, helped
boost the May index, although the growth in production slowed from
the previous month, the report said.
   Thirty percent of the 250 purchasing managers surveyed said
their companies had more new orders, compared with 16 percent that
reported fewer orders. Fifty-four percent said orders were running
at the same rate as in April.
   In April, 37 percent of the respondents reported more orders,
compared with 14 percent who reported less and 49 percent the same.
   Of those members exporting, 35 percent reported higher orders in
May, compared to 40 percent in April.
   The respondents in the survey also reported:
   _Production continued to grow, those reporting better results
fell to 27 percent from 37 percent in April. Eleven percent
reported a decline in production, compared with 53 percent in the
previous month.
   _The pace of vendor deliveries picked up slightly. Nineteen
percent of the executives reported slower deliveries, down from 21
percent in April, while 76 percent reported no change in the
delivery rate, up from 74 percent the previous month.
   _Inventories expanded. A quarter of managers reported rises in
inventories, against 17 percent reporting drops. In April, 20
percent said inventories had risen, while 15 percent reported
decreases.
   _Rising prices led declines for the 20th consecutive month.
Sixty-four percent of the executives said prices were up, while 35
percent said they were down. In April, 70 percent said prices rose
and 29 percent said they fell.
   _Employment fell slightly, with 14 percent of the managers
reporting increased hiring at their companies, compared with 16
percent in April. Eleven percent reported a drop in jobs in both
months.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv AMs Monday June 6</NOTE>
